<HEADLINE>Clarke firm on interest rates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Geoffrey Parkhouse</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By Our Political Editor
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke is under severe pressure from his party to cut the
cost of borrowing to compensate for his neutral Budget. Britain's biggest
building society, the Halifax, added to this with a 0.25% cut in its lending
rate.
However, the Chancellor is waiting to see what Germany does today and what
interest rate action might be taken in America. He told a news conference:
``The one thing I am not going to do is play fast and loose with interest rates
in response to political pressures.''
The surprise 0.25% reduction to 7.74% by the Halifax was followed immediately
by its competitors, including the Nationwide, National &amp; Provincial, Abbey
National, Bradford &amp; Bingley, Northern Rock, and Britannia.
The cut will benefit more than six million borrowers.
The political pressure on Mr Clarke to boost a slowing economy with an early
cut in the interest rate saw sterling fall against the deutschmark and the
dollar yesterday. Despite this, at the Commons, back-bench Tories were
insisting that the rate should fall from 6.75%.
Mr John Townend, chairman of the Tory back-bench finance committee, said: ``The
Budget has provided a window of opportunity to cut interest rates within the
next few weeks.''
He had been demanding a much more substantial cut in the standard rate of
income tax than the 1p that the Chancellor delivered.
He was supported by several other back benchers. Mr David Nicholson said: ``We
very much hope that there will be a fall in interest rates.''
Mr Mathew Carrington insisted that a ``substantial cut in rates is needed. Mr
Clarke has been very modest and prudent on tax cuts. There should be a half per
cent cut very quickly and a further half per cent before too long.''
Nevertheless, Mr Clarke insisted: ``My job as a Conservative Chancellor is to
run the economy and keep this economy growing faster than anybody else's and
that is what we will do.'' Future economic growth and control of inflation
depended on ``a sensible economic policy and running it in a sensible
fashion''. He added: ``That is what Conservative Governments are for.''
q The Halifax said the reduction in its standard variable mortgage rate would
reduce monthly payments on a #30,000 repayment mortgage by #4.07 to #206.45, a
#50,000 loan goes down by #7.37 to #352.68, and a #100,000 mortgage is cut by
#15.67 to #734.37.
On an endowment loan the reductions are: #30,000 loan down #5.32 to #164.48;
#50,000 down #9.49 to #293.48; and #100,000 down #19.91 to #615.98.
