<HEADLINE>Forsyth's grand plans fail to win over critics Scots new deal jeered</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth was greeted by derision yesterday as he
unveiled his much-publicised new vision for the treatment of Scottish politics.
Opposition MPs laughed openly as he suggested that the Prime Minister and the
Chancellor of the Exchequer could take part in debates in the Scottish Grand
Committee, which would meet in different locations around Scotland.
The committee is in line to be given greater powers but it emerged from Mr
Forsyth's statement that these would only be ``when it makes sense to do so'' -
in other words controversial Bills would still have to go through the full
Commons procedure even if their initial stages were taken in Scotland.
Third Readings of Bills also could be taken in the Scottish Grand Committee but
that would only be after they had gone through ``detailed consideration and
amendment''.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson described the plans as a
``travelling circus'' which was no substitute for a Scottish Parliament elected
by and responsible to the Scottish people.
Mr Forsyth will put some meat on the bones of his plans in a St Andrew's Day
speech this evening but his line last night was that it was right to expand the
role of the Scottish Grand Committee, with senior Ministers called in to
present policies, react to criticisms of them, and for this to be done in a
forum accessible to the people of Scotland.
He has plans for eight meetings next year of the committee to consider
Government business, all of which will be held in Scotland.
He angrily rejected plans for a tax-raising parliament which, he said, would
damage Scotland's jobs and prosperity, and said the Government already had made
clear in the White Paper, Scotland in the Union, that it believed the current
approach was to work within the existing framework to make Government and
Parliament at all levels more visible and relevant to the people.
He claimed the changes he proposed would greatly strengthen the role of the
Scottish Grand Committee in considering legislation affecting Scotland.
``It will provide a new focus for the role of the Scottish Grand Committee in
scrutinising and calling to account not just Scottish Office Ministers but
every Minister. The Scottish Grand Committee will thus assume an increasingly
pivotal role in the parliamentary government of Scotland, in bringing
Government closer to the people and in underpinning the Union.
``What the people of Scotland want is government close to them, government
listening to them and, above all, government accountable to them.''
Mr Robertson described the Secretary of State's remarks as a ``stark admission
that the Government's policies towards Scotland have utterly failed.'' For
taking stock we now had taking the Michael, and do nothing had been replaced by
do as little as possible, he said.
He demanded: ``Is this the full breadth of the Secretary of State's vision? New
Forsyth, New Status Quo?
``Is this the Secretary of State's big idea: weekend breaks for the Cabinet?
After all the hype, all the publicity, is this the best he could come up with?''
Mr Robertson questioned whether the revamped Scottish Grand Committee would be
anything more than a rubber stamp for non-controversial legislation. ``What has
changed?'' he asked. ``An extra stage to Scottish Bills, a few more meetings, a
few more debates, a few more opportunities to hear Ministers and their
reinforcements from the  Cabinet  dodge difficult questions?''
For the Liberal Democrats, Scottish leader Jim Wallace said: ``These changes
amount to no more than a series of away-day returns for a succession of
Government Ministers. They can come to Scotland, explain their policies and
react to criticism, but nowhere is there any suggestion that the Government
will change its policies in the light of Scottish opinion.
``There is nothing in this statement which would have prevented the poll tax,
nothing that will stop the introduction of nursery vouchers in its tracks. Far
from strengthening the Union, these proposals may well weaken it by showing how
clearly unresponsive the Government is to Scotland's needs and its political
agenda.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said: ``The proposals announced by Forsyth confirm that
the Westminster veto remains intact over every aspect of Scottish affairs.
Scottish MPs are trusted to examine uncontroversial Bills but are not to be
trusted to consider anything contentious. Even on uncontroversial measures,
Westminster would still rule, OK.''
Mr Major and Mr Kenneth Clarke, meanwhile, have agreed dates for their
appearances in Scotland, which are expected to be announced shortly. Last
night, Mr Forsyth claimed other Cabinet Ministers were queuing up to appear in
Scotland, and extra dates for meetings of the Scottish Grand Committee would
have to be laid on.
He accepted that the cost of taking it to towns and cities around Scotland - he
suggested Stirling, in his constituency, and Hamilton, in that of Mr Robertson,
as two possibilities - would be high.
