<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major pays tribute to `long-standing friend'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British-American special relationship was given new impetus yesterday with
the visit to London of President Clinton.
Mr Clinton's major duty on the first day of a three-day visit was to address
the Houses of Parliament. He hailed the ``extraordinary relationship'' between
the countries and was praised warmly later by Prime Minister John Major at a
state banquet at No 10 Downing Street.
Mr Major described the speech as ``memorable'', adding: ``It showed detailed
knowledge of our history, a great deal of it shared with the United States.''
``It could only have been made by a long-standing friend of this country.''
Mr Clinton and his wife Hillary started their visit to London, Belfast, and
Dublin, with a wreath-laying ceremony at the grave of the unknown soldier at
Westminster Abbey.
Then Mr Clinton and Mr Major walked from the abbey to Downing Street amid
massive security.
Later, the president was welcomed amid pomp and pageantry to Westminster by the
Prime Minister and Commons Speaker Betty Boothroyd.
Arriving to a fanfare of trumpets, he addressed a packed Royal Gallery in the
House of Lords.
Baroness Thatcher, who invited former President Ronald Reagan to speak to
Parliament in the early 80s, was among the guests to hear Mr Clinton describe
the links between the two countries.
Hailing the ``extraordinary relationship'', Mr Clinton said ``it unites us in a
way never before seen in the ties between two such great nations''.
Recalling that he had been to Westminster many times before, he said he always
``felt the power of this place, where the voices of free people who love
liberty, believe in reason, and struggle for truth, have for centuries kept
your great nation a beacon of hope for all the world''.
Mr Clinton said: ``For a long time, I thought if my forebears had not left this
country perhaps I might have gotten here on my own, at least to the House of
Commons.
``But now our American television carries your question time and I have seen
Prime Minister Major and Mr Blair and other members slicing each other up face
to face with such great wit and skill against the din of cheers and jeers. I am
now convinced my forebears did me a great favour,'' he said to laughter.
Although the Cold War was over, the forces of destruction were still a
challenge.
``We see it in the growth of ethnic hatred, extreme nationalism, and religious
fanaticism which most recently took the life of one of the greatest champions
of peace in the entire world - the prime minister of Israel.''
It was also evident in acts of terrorism that resulted in deaths from Islamabad
to Paris, from Riyad to Oklahoma, and the organised drug trade.
But both the United States and the United Kingdom bore a special burden of
responsibility.
``After so much success together, we know that our relationship with the United
Kingdom must be at the heart of our striving in this new era: because of the
history we have lived, because of the power and prosperity we enjoy, because of
the accepted truth that you and we have no dark motives in our dealings with
other nations.''
As if to underline the strength of the partnership, Mr Clinton announced that a
US warship would be named after Winston Churchill.
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind later praised the close bonds of the
UK-American relationship in the Commons.
</TEXT>
