<HEADLINE>Budget fails to dispel gloom</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>88</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANYONE in the property sector who had been hoping for a boost from the Budget
found themselves disappointed on Tuesday.
``I can't see the Budget having any impact whatsoever on commercial real
estate,'' said Ted Webster of international surveyors Richard Ellis. ``To be
fair, I don't think it's the Government's job to stimulate commercial property
development. But by stimulating activity in the economy the Government can
create an increased demand for industrial, office and retail space. Essentially
property is a reactive sector.''
However, if the Budget was to be followed up by a reduction in interest rates
then the investment side of the property sector could receive a boost. ``For
the last couple of quarters, total returns from property have out-performed
gilts,'' said Mr Webster. ``Combine that with a further lowering in interest
rates and you will see a stimulus of the investment market. People would be
seeking to buy income streams, even if rentals did not increase.''
In declining to take the traditional route of boosting demand by announcing
extra public expenditure in the construction sector, the Chancellor is clearly
signalling that future capital projects will be funded via the controversial
Private Finace Initiative (PFI).
``The construction and property industry now accepts that the PFI will replace
the normal procurement route for large capital projects,'' says Webster. ``But
in many ways the big companies are ahead of the Government. There is a
willingness to get on with these schemes but the Government and the civil
servants are slow in bringing suitable schemes forward to the tendering stage.
There's also a widespread worry that the cost of tendering for PFI schemes is
too high.''
Phil Reid, of international surveyors Jones Lang Wootton, says: ``Apart from
one or two hot spots, such as the retail sector, commercial property is marking
time at the moment. Only an increase in demand will create new activity - and
it's patently obvious that no such increase in activity will flow from the
Budget. People still see property as a cost on which they must keep a tight
rein.''
He has seen several clients postpone relocation decisions over the last six
months, despite the availability of good premises at good prices. However, he
does see one chink of light.
``If it's true that industrial demand is a barometer of the economy, then
things seem to be getting better. We are seeing a steadily increasing demand
for space across all the industrial sectors, from traditional space users to
high-tech firms - but many lettings are still supported by public sector
subsidies of one sort or another.''
The Chancellor's introduction of a landfill levy of #7 per tonne has
implications for the regeneration of derelict and contaminated sites, often
known as brownfield land. ``Developers and agencies considering the remediation
of brownfield sites will have to take the new levy into consideration - and in
some cases the additional #7 per tonne could push redevelopment schemes out of
financial kilter,'' says Alistair Dalziel of environmental consultants RPS
Cairns.
``The other big impact will be on individual companies which will now have to
look very carefully at controlling the waste they generate. Such companies will
now see waste as a threat to profitability. The cost of waste is accelerating
faster than the Retail Price Index and is now an important influence on bottom
line profits.''
Kemp Lindsey, an environmental specialist with surveyors Grimley, welcomed the
landfill levy. ``An incentive to reduce the amount of waste that goes into
landfill must be a good thing. But there are many practical implications which
still need to be hammered out.'' And he warned that the levy will not be
absorbed by waste operators, but will be passed directly on to the waste
producers.
</TEXT>
