<HEADLINE>New house for home furnishings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>88</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR furniture manufacturer is poised to settle into new large-scale
premises. Forrest Furnishing has acquired a 148,000 sq ft facility at Dalkeith
(above) from the administrative receivers of Ferranti International plc. The
building is set in within its own 13.3 acres of ground at Thornybank Industrial
Estate.
Conditional consent has been obtained to allow change of use from industrial to
50,000 sq ft of furniture retail space, plus ancillary storage, manufacturing,
assembly and office accommodation.
The five-storey building was developed 22 years ago and extended in 1989.
Forrest Furnishing is undertaking a #1.2m refurbishment programme to convert
and upgrade the facility. The site has parking for 200 cars.
``This acquisition will allow us to service the market in the East of Scotland
and the Borders and will enable expansion of our existing Glasgow based retail
operations,'' says managing director Ken Forrest. ``At Dalkeith, we will also
be able to expand our facilities for manufacture, assembly, storage and
distribution.''
Surveyors Graham &amp; Sibbald acted for Forrest Furnishing. Ryden acted for
administrative receivers Arthur Andersen. The purchase price was not disclosed.
Meanwhile a rental of #14 per sq ft has been achieved in a new deal at South
Gyle Park, the West Edinburgh business park recently acquired by Grosvenor
Estates Holdings. The 3,630 sq ft first floor at 36 South Gyle Crescent has
been let to Usher Systems Ltd, a provider of software packages to the legal
profession.
The starting rental is #51,000 per annum on a full 20-year lease. A further
7000 sq ft is available in 36 South Gyle Crescent, which has been fitted out as
offices by Grosvenor. South Gyle Park also offers some 6.5 acres of development
land. Usher systems was represented by Alexander Macaulay Associates, while
Chesterton acted on behalf of Grosvenor.
</TEXT>
