<DOCNO>GH951130-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prayers on the Internet bring results</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHO'S on the Internet, then? The Diary will be on it from this weekend, but the
only rugby club in Scotland on at the moment is Annan.
It's thanks to Angus Robertson, an MSC chappie from Napier and son of Annan
president Alan, who has put the club at http://www. gopages. com/
Colosseum/1920 . . . or something like that.
Most of the contact so far has been from America, where there are hundreds of
clubs on the Internet, although some have also come from England. Among the
fascinating aspects available for perusal at other clubs are player profiles of
Brian Moore and Will Carling. Leicester, Harlequins and Sale are all on. Oh
yes, we'll be spending hours in that bit of the web all right.
But mischief is in the air. Our computer buff friend has created a spoof
Dumfries page for all the world to communicate with as well.
There is bad blood, from the dark ages of history, between Annan and Dumfries.
So young Mr Robertson has taken a spoof page in the name of Dumfries Prayer
Page, where the rugby people of the world have been invited to deposit a prayer
to help Dumfries rugby club. Many beautiful prayers have arrived, and since
then Dumfries have won their last two games.
``It's a great way of spreading news about the club,'' said a taken aback Colin
Brown, the Dumfries secretary. ``We will do the same.''
``Do the same?'' retorted Dumfries committee man Don Wylie. ``I'll be selling
prayer mats behind the bar from now on if it works.''
A hint there for the rest of us perhaps.
q.THERE are few ladies in Scotland who will have a better understanding of
rugby than Rhona Lawson, the Isle of Arran rugby team secretary.
She is famous in rugby for being super organised, and she goes everywhere with
the team. Arran are about to build new pitches at Brodick costing #800,000, but
that is not what this little piece is about.
The Diary understands that Rhona, who is now retired after having started her
interest in rugby as a tea girl at Hillhead school in Glasgow, is writing a
book called A Woman's Perspective of Rugby. To settle a few minds, this is not
an expose, but a beautiful look back at her involvement in the game since those
early days, charting her progress through Rose Street in Edinburgh, and taking
us to the present.
``I have had discussions with a publisher,'' says Rhona. ``It's been a 40-year
involvement in the game, and it's been my life. I may need a sponsor.''
Rhona tells the Diary that she is mid-way through her third chapter, which is
all about Bill McLaren, and it is entitled, The Comfortable Alternative.
McLaren will be delighted to learn that this is about how listening to the
great man's tones compares to a hard day and night at Murrayfield ..... and not
about Rhona testing Bill McLaren's testosterone levels.
q.DOCTOR James Dabbs of Georgia State University has proved that sporting
excitement can make you feel that warm, affectionate way. Come on, you remember.
During the football World Cup in Atlanta he sent volunteers into bars for
samples. Of saliva, you'll be glad to know.
When Brazil played Italy his tests showed that the testosterone levels of the
Brazilian supporters had risen by 27% after the game, but had dropped 26.7% in
the Italian fans. Brazil beat Italy.
I conducted my own research after the Scotland v Western Samoa draw. Results
were inconclusive. Big Jill from Haddington turned me down again. And something
I can't mention happened when Kenny Logan came on the TV.
q.JOHN Jeffrey may have needed some of that medicine. Playing for a golden
oldies team in Bermuda last week, where the players are farmed out to local
families, he was billeted with a 40-year-old divorcee.
Much to his discomfort the lady in question made breakfast in her nightie,
waited up for him to come home late at night, popped off work to help him pack
his bag, and came to every game.
JJ says he has never had so many headaches in his life. That's what he's saying
and I believe him.
q.PETER Wright fell foul of Ken McCartney as we all know. But the Diary
understands that Jim Fleming, one of Scotland's international referees, was
getting fed up with a player's back-chat recently.
``You want to be a referee?'' quipped Fleming to the player. ``Wednesday
evening, six-thirty, Edinburgh referee's society, Inverleith ..... be there!''
qTHE in-crowd held a surprise party for Kenny Milne at his father's house at
the weekend. Gav, the lot really, were there.
As the unsuspecting Baby Bear entered the house Bohemian Rhapsody which, as the
world knows, is Kenny Milne's party piece, started to blare at full volume.
Yes, it was wonderful. Don't know why the Diary is so delighted though. We
weren't flaming invited.
</TEXT>
