<HEADLINE>Ralph Blane</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ralph Uriah Hunsecker Blane, songwriter, born Broken Arrow, Oklahoma, July 26,
1914, died there November 13, 1995
WITH his partner, Hugh Martin, Ralph Blane wrote the score for one of the
greatest of all MGM musicals, Vincente Minelli's Meet Me In St Louis, in which
Judy Garland sang The Trolley Song. It won the 1944 best song Academy Award,
but it was not a one-song score.
The film was rich in ballads still sung today, including Have Yourself a Merry
Little Christmas, which vies with Berlin's White Christmas for being the most
recorded Christmas song, and the wistful The Boy Next Door.
Born in Broken Arrow, Oklahoma, Blane maintained close links with his home
state throughout his long career, and eventually retired there. He was educated
at Northwestern University, where he studied piano, dancing, and voice, before
joining the St Louis Muncipal Opera Company in 1934. Then he went to Broadway,
working as a singer in revues and musicals, and met Martin.
The partnership was one in which they took credit together for everything they
produced, regardless of who thought of it first. Before finding success in
their own right as composers, they had a fair career as orchestrators, working
for Richard Rogers on The Boys from Syracuse.
In 1941 they wrote the college boys musical, Best Foot Foward, for George Abbot
with its rousing hymn to the alma mater, Buckle Down Winsocki. That led to MGM,
signing them up for films like Thousands Cheer and then Meet Me in St Louis.
Blane's solo career as a composer included the the Jane Russell film, The
French Line, and the Betty Grable musical, My Blue Heaven. With Martin he wrote
The Girl Rush, which starred Rosalind Russell, Athena, and The Girl Most
Likely. In 1989, both aged 75, they worked together on the Broadway version of
Meet Me In St Louis.
</TEXT>
