<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Price lands title hat trick</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gordon Dunwoodie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Price, the defending champion, became the first player to win the CIS
Masters for a third time when he beat world champion Andy Thomson 7-3, 0-7,
7-4, 7-5 in last night's final in Coatbridge. Scottish interest had ended
earlier in the day when Price cruised to a 7-1, 7-2 win over Commonwealth gold
medallist Richard Corsie while Thomson beat Scottish champion Paul Conlan 7-3,
1-7,     7-1.
Price, who was lining up in his fifth final in the seven-year history of the
Masters, made a great start with doubles on the opening three ends. The world
No.1 broke his duck with three shots on the fourth end, but a single on the
next gave Price the set 7-3.
However, the match then swung dramatically in Thomson's favour. With Price's
deft touch suddenly deserting him, Thomson counted 11 shots over the next five
ends to take the second set on a whitewash and move 4-0 ahead in the third.
Then it was Price's turn to take command. Ten shots over the next six ends saw
him take the third set 7-4 and move 3-0 ahead in the fourth before Thomson
pushed himself     back into contention with       two doubles and a single to
lead 5-3.
On the next, with both     players having dead-length touchers, Price played
the shot of the match with his final delivery, turning Thomson's toucher
through the head for what almost produced a match-winning count of 4, but the
Swansea man had to settle for a 3 that pushed him ahead again 6-5.
Price then added the single he needed to take the #1600 first prize on the next
end, wrapping up a 7-3, 0-7, 7-4, 7-5 win.
Both players later agreed that Price's shot on the penultimate end was the
match-winner.
``From 5-3 down it gave me a 6-5 lead and just the boost I needed at the right
time,'' said Price, while Thomson said: ``It was a risky shot that could have
gone wrong, but full marks to John for playing it. He took his courage in both
hands and was rewarded.''
Earlier, hopes of a home victory disappeared at the semi-final stage when both
Corsie and Conlan tumbled to defeat.Corsie was the first to bow out, going down
against Price, and then Scottish champion Conlan lost 3-7, 7-1, 1-7 to Thomson.
The eagerly anticipated Price-Corsie clash failed to produce the fireworks
expected with Price dominating from the opening end and wrapping up his
straight-sets win in just 13 ends.
Conlan, who had survived a slow start in his quarter-final victory over Alex
Marshall, started well with an opening end double but Thomson slowly hauled
himself back and went on to take the set 7-3. Conlan then needed just three
ends to take the second set 7-1.
</TEXT>
