<HEADLINE>The Break of Day, Royal Court, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TIMBERLAKE Wertenbaker's The Break of Day is one brave play. Flawed,
over-schematic, and bedevilled by sentimentality, unusually for Wertenbaker and
her director Max Stafford Clark, this is, however, a tugging, pioneering,
modern counterpoint to Chekhov's Three Sisters - the other work currently on
tour by Stafford Clark's Out of Joint company.
Wertenbaker has updated Chekhov's ideas of the search for happiness and hope in
the future and the sisters' longing into the very pertinent issue of women and
fertility, setting beside it, as saviour to all those swirling female hormones,
the necessity of work.
Without it, Wertenbaker shows, women are at the mercy of their bodies. Equally
bravely, she plants her colours firmly in the intellectual camp.
``We only want to try and understand what's happened,'' declares former
magazine editor Tess, at the end reduced to a jangling wreck by her obsession
to have a child.
Her sister in feminism, the doughty, determined Nina (Maria Friedman) has also
been laid low by the hunger of the unfillable void, trailing off to the eastern
block to find and adopt a baby.
Taking us behind the headlines of those heartbreak mothers, Wertenbaker shows
the madness, the humiliating IVF tests, and the anguish and bewilderment of the
various husbands and spouses with ground-breaking honesty.
Only partially sucessful, though parallelling Three Sisters to a remarkable
degree, the first half falls into a fairly familiar Royal Court style of sharp
one-liners about art and life and an England in despair.
However, the second half with Nina and Hugh's battle against crazed bureaucracy
in a post-communist world is the true child of Chekhov - tragic and farcical in
equal measure.
The Break of Day runs to 6 January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
