<HEADLINE>Lt-Col Alec Brodie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Appreciation by Colonel Robert Gurdon,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975126551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lt-Col A C C Brodie, DSO, OBE, MC
THE Black Watch has recently lost a depressingly large number of gallant
wartime officers, the latest being Alec Brodie who was certainly the most
colourful and best known. He was a legend in the regiment and anyone who knew
him would have some hilarious story about him.
He was born in London in 1912 - the son of a city merchant. He was educated at
Stowe and, while a boy, contracted polio which left his face with a rather
crooked appearance. He was commissioned into the Black Watch in 1932 and was on
operations in Palestine at the outbreak of war in 1939.
The first part of his war was rather peripatetic. He learned Serbo-Croat in
Belgrade and served as military attache in Athens and Sofia. He had spells in
the second battalion and in the Middle East Commando. On his own admission he
was frequently moved on as no-one could quite handle his unorthodox behaviour.
He described his various sackings as ``catching the 11 o'clock train''.
He joined the 5th Battalion in Normandy and won the MC at Colombelles. He
stoically stuck to his position to allow the rest of the battalion to withdraw.
Although badly wounded he remained with his men to recover an anti-tank gun.
Some six months later he won the DSO at Goch near the Rhine. On this occasion
he led his company in a series of daring attacks which bordered on suicidal.
However, despite being severely wounded many times he took the position and was
able to hold it against determined counter-attacks.
It was this reckless bravery that made commanders wary of putting him in
command of soldiers. However, the Jocks adored him and he could remember the
name and family background of all those who served under him. As a result of
his boyhood polio and war wounds he cut rather a grotesque figure and his
high-pitched voice and eccentric mannerisms were frequently mimicked.
One frequently told and suitable exaggerated story concerns his activities in
the town of Gennep. It was cold and wet and there was intermittent enemy fire
coming down the street when Alec appeared round the corner under an umbrella.
When questioned about the umbrella he pointed out that it was raining. He led
that sort of charmed life.
After the war he was military attache in Seoul, Laos, and Beirut. It came as no
surprise that war broke out in each place just after the arrival of Alec.
Nevertheless, he was awarded the OBE for his work in Beirut. After retirement
he was commandant of Barry Buddon Training Camp for 17 years.
Alec was a kind and caring person and was always willing to help the young and
inexperienced. He cared little for rules or orthodoxy. No more so than in the
way he dressed. In uniform he never conformed to the accepted forms of dress
and made up his attire, I suspect, as it came to hand.
He laughed at himself and we did so with him because he was a larger-than-life
funny man. Such characters are not in the Army now and the Army is poorer for
it.
n Appreciation by Colonel Robert Gurdon, regimental secretary, the Black Watch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The sums cut both ways</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Iain Wilson considers the effect the Budget will have on Scotland
WHEN giving Budget details, it's not what you do but the way that you do it
..... and Michael Forsyth certainly did it his way. His response to Kenneth
Clarke's Budget for the Scottish Office over the next three years was one of
``delight''.
Predictably, the Scottish Secretary also sang loud and long about next year's
total allocation being, in cash terms, the highest ever - up #173m on this
year. He also celebrated retention of the Barnett formula, which guarantees
Scotland an enhanced fixed share of spending.
In the world of politics, there was nothing wrong with such a triumphal
presentation of his public expenditure negotiations, reputed to be ``the
toughest'' for many years.
The reality is different. In real, not cash, terms, there is no denying a #329m
cut in the Scottish Office budget next year. Or that by 1998-99, cuts will have
risen to 5%.
It would also appear the rest of the UK has fared better than Forsyth in the
battle for spending money. The Red Book, the Government's financial statement,
shows the Scottish Office budget will increase by 2.3% in cash terms by 1998-99
- compared with 7.9% for the UK overall.
However, in real terms, over the same period - once inflation is taken into
account - the Scottish Office's planned ``out-turn'', what it really spends, is
scheduled to fall by 5%, in contrast to a 0.2% rise elsewhere in Britain.
Scotland's overall decline in spending power is put at #700m, down from #14.1
billion next year to #13.4 billion in 1998-99.
The ``brutal truth'' will emerge within weeks, according to Shadow Scottish
Secretary George Robertson, when Forsyth has to provide Parliament with a
detailed breakdown of expenditure plans.
Robertson is among political opponents who believe Forsyth's initial cheer
after Tuesday's Budget was based merely upon limiting damage during Treasury
``negotiations''.
However, even Professor Brian Ashcroft, director of Strathclyde University's
influential Fraser of Allander Institute, suggested yesterday Forsyth's delight
was misplaced.
Ashcroft stressed there are substantial differences between increases in cash
terms and real terms, when the Government's own projected inflation figures of
between 2.25% and 2.75%-a-year up to 1998-1999 are taken into account.
He stressed it was possible the Government expects Scotland's population to
decline over the next three years. If so, it would be possible
spending-per-person will not fall by as much as 5%. He reckons that scenario
could explain why the Scottish Secretary failed to get more money in real terms.
Meanwhile, Labour predicted the public expenditure cuts will hit housing,
roads, and Scottish Enterprise in particular - regardless of claims that
spending will be supplemented by an estimated #2.2 billion worth of Private
Finance Initiatives by 1999.
Robertson expects budgets for education and law and order will hold up, but
fears many other areas will be damaged. He especially fears that Scottish
Enterprise's expenditure on training will suffer.
The Shadow Secretary said of Forsyth's pleasure at defending the Barnett
formula: ``Who was he fighting? We are told it was a great victory, but the
truth is that he `battled' to keep something we have had since 1978.
``Barnett survived the whole period of Margaret Thatcher; Michael Portillo as
Chief Secretary to the Treasury, and others from Jonathan Aitken to William
Waldegrave. What is the big deal?''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said Forsyth's delight was obligatory, despite the
sharp fall in spending power over three years. He pointed out public
expenditure will fall in Scotland yet increase slightly in UK, and added:
``That is a fact, whether Michael Forsyth likes it or not.
``I do not understand why he is celebrating because the Scottish Office budget
is more a wake than a party.''
``Perhaps he is happy because he has not lost more than #700m. But it is very
difficult to see where such cuts will come from without damaging key services.''
Forsyth himself says: ``I fought and won the battle for Scotland to make sure
the Scottish people continue to benefit from the greater spending they have
enjoyed for many years.
``The most important victory was to make sure the Scottish settlement was in
line with other departments and I was successful in that fight.''
He adds, support for local authorities had increased by over #100m, and the
Scottish Office was one of the most successful departments in pioneering PFI.
Private investors would spend #930m in the next three years on important
projects to boost Scotland's infrastructure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
