<DOCNO>GH951130-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Candy Dulfer, Plaza, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Williamson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEW would doubt Candy Dulfer's inordinately large instrumental ability: one of
the world's most naturally gifted saxophone players, her services have been
hired by everyone from the seriously funky (Prince) to ageing hippies (Dave
Stewart, Van Morrison) trying to give their increasingly dull outputs some
spark.
In between times, Dulfer has mixed with the jazz elite (David Sanborn and
Marcus Miller contribute to her current album Big Girl), which makes it
something of a surprise that the Plaza is so sparsely populated for what is her
first appearance in Glasgow.
It becomes easier to establish why as the set wears on, for Dulfer's
eclecticism serves to alienate, rather than embrace a wide range of potential
audiences from jazz through easy listening to funk: whetting many an appetite,
satisfying none.
The seventies backing band are, as expected, flawless but fussy, the set
building from lightweight and meandering jazz doodlings into some infinitely
more serious funk.
Tommy Gun and Capone are next year's elevator music, calling to mind the likes
of Mezzoforte and Shakatak, while the Miles Davis tribute, 2 Miles,
encapsulates Dulfer's dilemma. For all its tightness of execution, you know
that Davis himself would never have come up with something so cluttered, flashy
and underwhelming.
Ironically, the prosaic nature of the opening part of the show is abruptly
halted by the arrival of three powerful gospel-driven singers for an extended
funk workout. Equally banal in content, the likes of Get Funky and Funkyness
are at least more enjoyable, encroaching on Brand New Heavies territory.
However, when her own Heavenly City merges into Rufus's Stop On By and she
embarks on a lengthy run through the Average White Band's Pick Up The Pieces,
it becomes obvious that Dulfer's real talent lies as an interpreter rather than
originator of songs.
</TEXT>
