<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Celtic Swing, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rob Adams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE gig that sounded like a race horse looked like one you could have put your
money on - and so it turned out. It was the sort of night that restores your
faith in the package tour: three of Ireland's foremost folky attractions, each
of whom could have headlined.
These are busy times for Eleanor Shanley. No sooner had she stopped touring
with Christy Moore than she was back on the road, back in Glasgow and back on
form.
Last time round she sounded road weary. This time, the sharpness was back. She
sang with confidence, a jaunty new song, The Dawning of the Day, in there
beside strong regulars like her voice and bodhran Still I Love Him and the
wholehearted Magdalene Laundry, with Robbie Overson's percussive guitar pushing
her on.
Sharon Shannon's current band may not have quite the virtuosic depth of the one
she brought a couple of Mayfests ago but it's certainly as mobile, rattling off
Simon Jeffes's Music for a Found Harmonium with unstoppable gusto. Shannon may
not have much to say for herself but with her equally ridiculous talents on
button accordion, fiddle and tin whistle, who cares?
Luka Bloom, on the other hand, worked alone, at least initially, before various
bill sharers arrived to help out, and confirmed once again that he doesn't need
a band. He can draw the listener in with a simple wordless refrain.
Like his elder brother, Christy Moore, he has vast reserves of quiet power and
whether crooning Black is the Colour, rapping I Need Love or railing against
French nuclear experiments, he is a fascinatingly persuasive performer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
