<DOCNO>GH951130-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time for Smith to strike</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS another thunderstorm rumbled in last night to give The Wanderers ground in
Johannesburg a third soaking in 24 hours, there were fears that England's
second Test against South Africa would be ruined by bad weather, just like the
first.
But for two batsmen at opposite ends of the experience scale, Robin Smith and
Mark Ramprakash, the pressure has been rising even quicker than local reservoir
levels.
Smith, England's most capped player and leading run scorer among a tour party
of 16, has produced just one convincing innings so far. Happily for him, it
came during the first Test at Centurion Park, where he scored 43 and displayed
typical courage until defeated by a superb delivery from Brian McMillan.
But against Orange Free State in Bloemfontein, Smith collected his third duck
of the trip - and worse, took 42 minutes and 30 balls to do it.
``I am very worried about how Robin is playing,'' admitted manager Ray
Illingworth. ``He's not played particularly well on tour and that wasn't the
most exciting nought you've seen. But we are backing his Test experience and
temperament.
``I don't think he's doing anything more wrong than he's always done,'' added
Illingworth, offering less than 100% backing for Smith's technique when asked
whether any particular problems were obvious to his expert eyes.
What England do know, though, is that Smith possesses a proven track record,
will fight as though his life depends on the outcome, and revels in a big match
atmosphere.
Two of those three huge pluses cannot yet be entered in the credit column under
Mark Ramprakash's name. No-one doubts his determination, nor his natural talent
for that matter, but to date, 31 Test innings have earned him a ludicrously low
average of 17.
``We know he can play, he knows he can play,'' said Illingworth. ``I think he
does get a bit uptight about Test cricket, but one nice big score would ease
that.``
Waiting in the wings and unable to get a Test outing at the moment is John
Crawley, scorer of 312 first-class runs from four completed innings to date.
England's bowlers will get their chance, weather permitting, to explore the
strength of South Africa's batting. But the exact composition of the attack was
still uncertain last night.
A last look in the morning at a pitch that was damp and grassy yesterday will
sort out whether spinner Richard Illingworth, fast bowler Devon Malcolm or
left-arm seamer Mark Ilott gets the final spot.
South Africa, who badly misread the pitch in the first Test, plan to field a
more balanced attack this time. They fielded five pace bowlers at Centurion
Park only to watch England amass 381 for nine.
``We miss Fanie de Villiers, and Meyrick Pringle's ability to swing the ball
away from the bat gives us the variety that Fanie brought,'' said South African
coach Bob Woolmer.
Pringle replaces Brett Schultz, who bowled only 16 overs in the first Test
after sustaining a recurrence of a strained buttock muscle. Woolmer also
indicated that Transvaal slow left armer Clive Eksteen was part of his plans.
Teams (from):
England - M Atherton (captain), A Stewart, M Ramprakash, G Thorpe, G Hick, R
Smith, J Russell, D Cork, D Gough, R Illingworth, A Fraser, D Malcolm, M Ilott.
South Africa - A Hudson, G Kirsten, H Cronje (captain), D Cullinan, J Rhodes, B
McMillan, D Richardson, S Pollock, C Eksteen, A Donald, M Pringle, C Matthews.
q DEMAND for tickets for England's Texaco Trophy one-day international against
India at The Oval next season has broken all records. Tickets for the match,
which takes place on May 23 next year, were snapped up in just four weeks.
q INDIA beat New Zealand by six wickets in their sixth and final one-day
international in Bombay yesterday to win the series 3-2. One match was washed
out by rain. Scores:
New Zealand 126 (35 overs); India 128 for four (32 overs).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Erasure fans miss the boat Erasure, Renfrew Ferry, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Peter Easton</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO much for your Internet and the communications revolution. All it takes is a
postal strike and civilised discourse grinds to a halt.
What could have been cheerier than for Erasure to invite members of their fan
club onto the Renfrew Ferry for an unpublicised song session? Well, the actual
delivery of said invites would have been a help.
Thus it was that the Ferry was in no danger of being over-laden on Tuesday
night. A disappointment for Erasure, whose low-key appearances elsewhere have
met with a riotous response, but what a treat for those who managed to get
onboard.
It is possible to like Erasure for their danceability, their melodies, and
their outrageous costumed campery. Amid the bleeps and sweeps of Vince Clarke's
programmed keyboards - irritating or ecstatic depending on your chemical
balance - it is easy to miss the fact Erasure generate some nifty melodies, and
Andy Bell actually sings them with a voice that soars all the way up from his
tummy and projects far beyond the microphone.
Simplicity was thus Tuesday's keynote. Dressed plainly for a night down the pub
or for chatting with fans, the amiable Messrs Bell and Clarke, plus guitarist
Nick Johnson, provided three songs performed acoustically: the last single Stay
With Me, (as you might expect), Sono Luminus, and Always from the I Say album
which sounded almost medieval. Quite beautiful. Remove the computers and you
have troubadors, timeless and true.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Angelo Fazzi</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EMILIO FAZZI</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975126557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Angelo Fazzi, food and wine expert; born, February 15, 1903, died November 24,
1995
THE 16-year-old Italian, dressed in a smart coat, who arrived for the first
time to a cold and foggy Motherwell Station at 11am in the morning of November
19, 1919, just wanted to turn round and go back home to the warmth of Tuscany.
An action-packed 76 years later and that same man's last words were: ``I belong
to Glasgow.'' He never lost the love of his native land but like other
immigrants before, he had grown to love this country and its people and chose
to die here.
Angelo Fazzi was the youngest of the three original Fazzi brothers who founded
the famous delicatessen in Clyde Street in Glasgow and thus started the
education of Glaswegians on the delights of Italian cooking.
Born in a well-established, close family in the enchanting countryside of
Lucca, a small town in western Tuscany, he belonged to a generation where life
signified constant struggle. By his eighth birthday both his older brother and
his father had died young from causes that now no longer challenge modern
medicine.
The year 1914 heralded the departure of his oldest brother Pietro to Motherwell
and the other brother Guiseppe to the front to fight for his country in the
Great War. During the difficult war years, young Angelo learned to tend the
vine and the olive and developed that empathy for the land and its fruits which
characterised his later life. The joy that came with the arrival of the
armistice was tempered by his leaving home at a very young age to come to our
distant northern land.
As one would expect, being an Italian in Scotland in those days meant long
working hours serving in a cafe or making ice cream or lemonade in a dingy
cellar. It took at least one year before the new arrivals to this country had
made the time to visit its capital, which they liked and its major city,
Glasgow, which they found to be far too busy and dirty.
The success they reaped from their energy and commitment to the business (they
worked from 6am to 12pm seven days a week) gave them the resources to import
the food and wine of their homeland for their own consumption.
Thankfully the liberal trade laws of this country made this an easy exercise
and thus in 1923, in response to their perception of an unsatisfied demand for
Italian produce from by then a large immigrant Italian population, Angelo Fazzi
bought a bike and started to travel to sell the surplus.
In 1926 they rented their first shop in Maxwell Street, Glasgow. It was such a
success that they were forced, in 1928, to move into new, larger premises in
232 Clyde Street, Glasgow, where the business remains to this day.
In the Second World War Angelo Fazzi was interned in the Isle of Man and
narrowly escaped having to go aboard the Arandora Star on its fateful journey
to Canada when it went down with all souls. Angelo was one of the founder
members of the Casa D'Italia and a leading member of the Italian community in
Scotland.
After helping to re-establish the firm after the Second World War he retired
finally in 1977 to his house in Glasgow. He was a man of prodigious energy with
the greenest of fingers, honed by the knowledge and experience handed down by
his predecessors in Italy.
In recent years, he bore with great fortitude and dignity the intense pain of
seeing the beloved business that he and his brothers had spent so much time and
energy developing, fall apart so badly.
He was clever, always elegantly dressed, and a gentleman of the old school with
solid old-fashioned values. He is survived by his wife and three sons and one
daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>All in such a good Claus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975126558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS comes but once a year and when it comes - how the heart sinks at the
prospect - it brings with it the Christmas movies, those seasonal tales with
which each distributor trys to secure the biggest share of the seasonal
box-office jackpot. They are invariably drenched in whimsy, smothered in
treacle, bedecked with fake snow, and feature some old ham in red with false
whiskers going ``Ho, ho, ho''.
This year, however, the first to appear is a delight, a fresh, inventive, witty
tale which manages, without spoiling the myth, to reassure the doubtful that
Santa Claus exists, while making clear he is, of course, really Daddy. Directed
by John Pasquin, The Santa Clause tells how Scott Calvin (Tim Allen), a
divorced parent, is outraged when his ex-wife (Wendy Crewson) brings their
small son Charlie (Eric Lloyd) over to spend Christmas Eve with him, only to
find she and her new husband, a psychiatrist (Judge Reinhold, wonderfully
nerdish) have told the moppet Santa does not exist.
Not that Scott believes in Santa either. He just hates his ex-wife's new
husband, a pompous psychiatrist with terrible taste in seasonal sweaters. In
the middle of the night there is a bump on the roof, and when Scott and Charlie
investigate they disturb a stout old party in red about to climb down the
chimney.
Losing his footing, Santa Claus, for it is he, falls into a snowdrift and is
knocked out. Scott rummages in his pockets to find some I D and extracts a card
which he reads, but neglects to study the small print. The body in the snow
drift disappears, and Scott and Charlie find they have been landed with
delivering the presents in Santa's place. There is nothing for it but to get in
his sleigh, still on the roof, and let the reindeer do the flying. When they
end up at the North Pole a bolshie elf called Bernard reveals the clause in
question. Scott has inherited the job of Santa and has until next Thanksgiving
to put his affairs in order.
What happens next? Go and see, because this truly is film for the entire
family. Leo Benvenuti and Steve Rudnick's script is blissfully sharp. When
Scott finds himself flying through the air, suspended from Santa's bag of toys
which acts as a balloon, Charlie cries - ``You're flying.''
``It's OK, I'm used to it. I lived through the sixties,'' Scott replies.
Erik Lloyd is an endearing Charlie, his loyalties divided between his parents,
and Reinhold makes the most of an unsympathetic role. But the film's mainstay
is Tim Allen, star of the TV sitcom Home Improvement, in a wry, charming, and
nicely prickly film debut.
Maybe the film does ignore the fact that Christmas is about more than Santa
Claus and toys, but its heart is in the right place since it is, at the least,
about a dysfunctional family getting its act together.
Shown at this year's Edinburgh Film Festival Antonia Bird's Mad Love, her
Hollywood debut as director, is a dire tale written by Paula Milne about a
young voyeur (Chris O'Donnell) who falls in love with the girl across the lake
(Drew Barrymore) whom he spies on while she is skinny dipping.
He is so besotted that the fact she is barking mad escapes his notice and the
pair run away from home. Eventually it penetrates his thick, albeit pretty,
head that she is a danger to herself and everyone else, so they go home. Not a
moment too soon.
We are back in the world of Warners with Murder in the First, a stylishly
directed piece about the awful regime in Alcatraz. On his release, Kevin Bacon,
kept in solitary confinement for three years for trying to escape, murders the
convict he believes betrayed the escape attempt. Christian Slater is the brash
attorney on his first case defending him, and Gary Oldman the sadistic warden.
The three stars act for all they are worth, the horrors of the Hole are
unsparingly shown and the courtroom scenes are gripping. But Alcatraz has long
since closed and Marc Rocco's film, although based on a true story, says
nothing that has not been said many times before about a penal system gone
wrong.
A sense of deja vu also hangs over Scott Kalvert's The Basketball Diaries,
another true story, which tells how Jim Carroll (Leonardo DiCaprio), a good
Catholic boy, became a junkie, not a basketball star, and went to hell and
back, only saved by the diary he had kept.
Carroll's literary talent was recognised and he ended up both a celebrated
writer and an off-Broadway performer. Kalvert lingers too long on his
degradation, and scampers over the really interesting stuff - how his
redemption came about.
DiCaprio, however, gives a blazingly good performance, confirming he is one of
the best young actors in Hollywood today. As for Candyman: Farewell to the
Flesh, we are back with the ghostly slave with a hook for a hand who
disembowels his victims, this time in New Orleans where, as Noel Coward said,
the wrought-iron screens are frightfully overwrought. So is the film.
The Santa Clause (U) directed by John Pasquin.
Murder in the First (15) directed by Marc Rocco.
Candyman: Farewell to the Flesh (18) directed by Bill Condon.
Mad Love (12) directed by Antonia Bird. On general release.
The Basketball Diaries (18) directed by Scott Calvert.
Filmhouse, Edinburgh.
All the above films open tomorrow.
Shanghai Triad (15) directed by Zhang Yimou.
GFT from Monday, December 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smoke and mirrors.  Surely there must be more, Mr Forsyth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAN this be it? The Secretary of State for Scotland was obliged to go to the
House yesterday and give some explanation of his plans for the governance of
Scotland, at least inasmuch as they would affect the workings of Parliament at
Westminster. This was the first instalment of the fruits of Mr Forsyth's
thinking on the subject in recent months and it did not amount to much. Nor was
it intended to. It is inconceivable that a man of the energy and subtlety of Mr
Forsyth would choose to make as little of the 15 or so months left to him in
office as was represented by his statement in the House yesterday. Therefore it
is possible that we will soon hear more than is contained in this mousy effort.
There were interesting bits to it, of course. The Scottish Grand Committee is
to be beefed up to enable Scottish MPs to have more power over legislation
affecting Scotland. The second and third readings of Scottish Bills would be
heard in the Grand Committee, but only when it makes sense to do so. What is
meant by that enigmatic phrase is anybody's guess but at the very least it
signals the utter determination of the Secretary of State for Scotland to
exercise control over everything within reach.
A Special Standing Committee is proposed so that professional bodies and
interest groups in Scotland may have more of the sort of access to the
formative stage of proposed legislation which is at present enjoyed by their
counterparts in England. This sounds more promising and if it permits the great
and the good of Scotland to let off some steam, so much the better. We must
not, however, pretend that it will have any great significance in the manner in
which the Government goes about its business. Requiring the presence of the
Prime Minister, the Chancellor, and other Ministers to explain Scottish policy
is significant, though it could be argued as little more than a sop to vanity.
It is clear that Mr Forsyth's way with things is very much a matter of smoke
and mirrors. Budget day found him enthusing over the highest ever cash-terms
increase in next year's allocation for Scotland. As we point out elsewhere in
this newspaper this morning the reality is somewhat different. In real terms
the budget allocation for the Scottish Office has been cut by #239m next year
and by 1998-99 the cut, again in real terms, will have risen further. The
heavily trailed suggestion that Mr Forsyth will give back to the new unitary
authorities many of the powers which were taken from the old authorities is
intriguing, but how can it sit comfortably with Mr Forsyth's determination to
retain powers to cap local authority spending and the measures to force
councils next year to curtail their capital expenditure to force the
establishment of joint ventures with the widely disregarded Private Finance
Initiative?
There must be more to Taking Stock Mark Two than this. But what? Mr Forsyth may
be content to believe that strengthening the Scottish Grand Committee will
allow him to argue that it will thereby have every function proposed by the
Opposition for a devolved parliament, except for tax-raising powers. He might
hope to use this to drive a wedge between Labour devolutionists and those in
the party who are doubtful, but the power to raise tax and to enact relevant
legislation is what makes the difference. Some Scots Tories, notably Sir
Michael Hirst, have spoken in recent days of a referendum on devolution. Could
this be Mr Forsyth's bombshell for today? If it is he is a wilder gambler than
we had thought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
