<DOCNO>GH951130-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joan Francis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Actress Joan Francis, an original member of the Coronation Street cast, has
died after a long illness at the age of 75.
JOAN FRANCIS played Dot Greenhalgh - Elsie Tanner's best friend and fellow
good-time girl - in 83 episodes of the TV soap, Coronation Street, from 1961 to
1969. She had been born into a theatrical family and appeared in plays,
pantomimes, musicals, and revue before going into television.
She originally auditioned for the part of Street siren Elsie Tanner but was
offered Dot instead. Her final scenes in the show were in a dramatic court case
where she let Elsie take the blame for some dresses Dot had stolen. Elsie was
let off but Dot had to leave the street.
In a racy plot for the 1960s, Dot and Elsie, played by Pat Pheonix, returned in
1967 to the American air base at Burtonwood where they had ``entertained'' the
Yanks during the war to rekindle old flames. Elsie ended up marrying Steve
Tanner and Dot's husband threw her out when he discovered her affair with a GI.
Francis retired from acting in the 1980s because of ill health. She suffered a
stroke seven years ago from which she never recovered and died in a South
Manchester nursing home after developing a chest infection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hector Blackburn</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH cricket has lost top umpire Hector Blackburn who died suddenly
yesterday at the age of 52. Mr Blackburn was one of the most respected
officials in the game and had been on the SCU's international panel for several
years.
SCU Chairman Chris Carruthers said: ``It's difficult to reminisce about Hector
without talking in cliches. But he was, quite simply, the most respected umpire
in the country. He would have been a strong front runner to represent Scotland
at the Mini World Cup in Malaysia in 1997.''
Mr Blackburn, who underwent a serious heart operation in September, officiated
at Scotland's friendly match against the West Indies last June. SCU general
manager Alex Ritchie revealed: ``Hector knew he was due to go into hospital for
a bypass, but he told his doctor in no uncertain terms that he wouldn't have
the operation until he'd stood in the Windies game. It was the highlight of his
career.''
The death of Scotland's top umpire follows the loss of the chairman of the
selectors, Hugh Stevenson, in August. Mr Blackburn's funeral will take place in
Bannockburn tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>James Henderson</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Houston Henderson, a solicitor with one of Dumfries's oldest family
firms, died at home after a long illness, aged 88.
JAMES Houston Henderson, was born in Dumfries and educated at Dumfries Academy,
Fettes College, and Edinburgh University where he was a rugby blue. He
graduated as a Bachelor of Law.
In 1931 he joined the firm of John Henderson and Sons which had been founded by
his grandfather and remained there until he was 80, with a break for war
service.
During the war he served as an officer with the 5th Battalion of the King's Own
Scottish Borderers and won the Military Cross in Holland. He was always
reluctant to talk about this heroic episode and even his own family did not
know the details. He left the Army with the rank of major and later served with
the TA.
Mr Henderson was a well known and highly respected member of the Dumfries legal
fraternity. He was secretary to Dumfries Savings Bank, clerk to the
Comissioners of Inland Revenue, and an honorary sheriff-substitute. He was also
a Rotarian and keen bridge player.
His wife Doreen died in 1986 and he is survived by his sons, David and John,
and daughter, Elizabeth. John has followed him into the family business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stuart Henry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Appreciation by ANDREW YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975126563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stuart Henry, disc jockey; born February 24, 1942, died November 24, 1995.
MY first memory of Stuart Henry was of a jaunty nautical figure holding court
in a tavern in Dunbar shortly before Radio Scotland, the ship, was due to go on
air in 1966. There was the cap at the perfect angle, the shoulder-length hair,
but, above all, those glowing eyes which seemed to tell you that life could be
fun.
While he could do the shiver-me-timbers bit to perfection, having trained as an
actor at the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama, Glasgow, he couldn't
cope with the ocean waves. Which was why he was to be dubbed ``the seasick
pirate.''
He was given a rare dispensation to be a landlubber pirate DJ, recording his
bits from the the rock-steady studio in Cranworth Street beside Byres Road in
Glasgow. While still at sea he had been so popular they couldn't do without
him. No-one listening realised that his most essential piece of broadcasting
equipment was the bucket.
The rusty old tub, MV Comet, stripped of its engine, started broadcasting on
January 1, 1966. Then, because the signal was not getting through strongly
enough to the West of Scotland, it was towed to a point off the Ayrshire coast
near Troon. Fellow pirates included Paul Young who had been at drama college
with Stuart.
Another was Tony Meehan who recalls that Henry was the complete professional
who would let nothing - not even sea sickness - prevent him doing his bit as he
felt it had to be done.
With the scuppering of Radio Scotland through the Marine Offences Act, Stuart
helped launch Radio 1, and became the most popular DJ in Britain with a Sunday
morning audience of more than 11 million. With his kaftans, long hair, and
droopy moustache he was in complete contrast to the traditional BBC DJs in
suits - more a product of the Flower Power generation.
In his Scottish accent he would address: ``Ma friends . . .'' He began to slur
his words on air, seemed clumsy off. The BBC management thought that this was
due to drink or drugs, not realising it was the start of the multiple sclerosis
that was to cripple him.
He was fired in 1974 but went on to Radio Luxembourg where he met his wife
Ollie who helped him continue broadcasting until 1987. It was in Luxembourg
that I met him again, in the early eighties. Nothing about his personality had
changed. There was still the kindness behind those eyes, the sensitivity, and
the love of music.
He was getting around on two walking sticks but he was still able to drive me
back to his house outside the town for dinner. At one point he lost balance,
and fell on the floor. He was immediately back on his feet again, talking
animatedly as though nothing had happened. He was a gentleman of great style.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Countdown to tragedy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan MacDermid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE lights in Edinburgh's public buildings will be switched off at 5pm tomorrow
for a period equivalent to one second for everyone in Scotland who has died
from Aids.
The gesture - one of the ways in which the capital is marking World Aids Day -
will demonstrate a grim statistic. Last year the lights were off for six
minutes. This year it will be 10 minutes and 10 seconds. And the worst is yet
to come.
``The majority of deaths from Aids are still ahead of us,'' Dr James Inglis,
consultant in public health medicine with the Health Education Board for
Scotland, warned yesterday.
With 10 years the typical time-lag between infection and death, what we are
reaping now follows the explosion of HIV infection in the mid-1980s.
``There have been 600 deaths in Scotland to date and there will be at least as
many, if not more, in the next few years,'' said Dr Inglis.
``Hopefully the death rate will fall away again after 1997, when our success in
reining in the spread of infection starts to show.''
Complacency, however, could undo this work, a report prepared by Dr Inglis and
his colleagues points out. Building on Good Practice catalogues the 800
prevention initiatives being carried out from Shetland to the Borders. One of
the statistics they came up with for the report which set them back on their
heels was the discovery that one-in-500 Scots males in the 15-44 age group is
now infected.
``That is a significant proportion of the sexually active population,'' said Dr
Inglis. ``When we were working it out it took us by surprise. We had to check
our arithmetic, and the epidemiologists at the Scottish Office went over it.
``In Edinburgh the figure is as high as one in 100. Most people will now know
someone who has HIV.''
Of particular concern is the inroads HIV is making into the community at large.
It can no longer be dismissed as a disease of gays or drug addicts.
More than a quarter of those who tested HIV positive last year became infected
through heterosexual contact - for HEBS the first priority for prevention
campaigns is now the first priority for prevention.
Other Aids facts:
n-The World Health Organisation estimates that 18.5m people, including 1.5m
children, are infected. Two million of these infections took place last year
alone.
n-The number of people known to be infected in Scotland is 2000, but the true
figure is thought to be double that.
n-Deaths from Aids last year were double that of the previous year.
n-Over the past eight years new infections have averaged 150 a year. That is
less reassuring than it may sound, for two reasons, said Dr Inglis: There has
been a dramatic decline in the number of new infections among IV drug users;
and there is no sign of a downward turn in new infections.
He explained: ``Normally an infectious disease peaks and then fades. There is
no indication of a downward trend and modest evidence of a slight creep
upwards. This increases the prevalence in the population, even though people
are dying from the disease.
``It is in many respects the fastest-moving epidemic we have seen. The virus
could change and become more lethal, or become more easily transmissable. Flu
can alter its characteristics and HIV is even trickier.
``The message has to be continuous, and it has to adapt to the style that will
reach each wave of young people reaching sexual maturity.''
For all the warnings, people travelling abroad still appear to be indulging in
unprotected sex. Dr Graham Hart, who works for the MRC Medical Sociology Unit
at Glasgow University, discovered in a survey of 400 people who had travelled
abroad within the previous three months that one in four had sex with a new
partner during the trip, and two-thirds claimed they had never, or
inconsistently, used a condom.
Since the 400 were all patients at a genito-urinary medicine clinic in London,
Dr Hart is first to acknowledge that they are not entirely representative. It
is the kind of place you would expect to find the victims of sexual
indiscretion.
But he points out in a re-search journal, Genitourinary Medicine, that between
30 and 40 million overseas visits are made by the British every year, so his
sample doesn't have to be all that near the mark to show a major potential for
the spread of infection.
``We need targeted health education for men and women who are sexually active -
whether this is prior to, during or after recent travel. In particular, single
men travelling alone should be considered a major risk group in terms of sexual
behaviour risk and travel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enduring images of the holocaust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE year's remembrance of the Second World War is drawing to a close, and the
reliving of victory has often overshadowed commemoration of the faceless
millions killed by the Nazi holocaust.
Hence the importance of the exhibition opening tomorrow at Edinburgh City Art
Centre which asks, and answers, one question: can art come out of the horrors
of Auschwitz?
Inspired by the words of the philosopher Theodor Adorno, who claimed that
``after Auschwitz there can be no poetry'', curator Monica Bohm-Duchen has
assembled the works of a variety of artists who are intent on creating art that
is relevant, that explores the nature of memory and loss without trivialising
the truth of what happened.
The exhibition opened in London, where journalist and author Rabbi Hugo Gryn,
himself a camp survivor, said Adorno was wrong: ``It's not true. There's art
and there's poetry and there's music. Look at these images, engrave them on
your hearts, tell them to your children and see to it that it is never ever
repeated.''
The work ranges from the disturbing architectural drawings of Melvin Charney to
the moving installations of Shimon Attie, in which photographic images of
pre-war German-Jewish street life are projected onto their original locations.
Also included in the exhibition is a series of black and white photographs by
the German artist Henning Langenheim, whose ongoing Memorials project aims to
document the known and unknown holocaust sites.
His work was partly set off by the shock of discovering that the Berlin
wasteland he had commuted past every day was once the Gestapo headquarters from
where the murder was managed.
n After Auschwitz: Responses to the Holocaust in Contemporary Arts, is at
Edinburgh City Arts Centre, Market Street, until January 20. A programme of
readings, lectures, and lunchtime videos accompanies the show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When it is trial and error</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bruce McKain</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF lawyers are feeling slightly paranoid at the moment it is probably because
everyone really is out to get them. Five judges in the Court of Criminal Appeal
will rule tomorrow on whether incompetent legal representation during a trial
can amount to a miscarriage of justice and provide a good ground for setting
aside a conviction.
And a leading Queen's Counsel was recently sued unsuccessfully for #150,000 in
Edinburgh Sheriff Court in a civil case in which it was alleged he had been
guilty of professional negligence.
The current law in criminal cases was laid down in the case of McCaroll in 1949
when a man charged with theft by housebreaking claimed his solicitor had failed
to ensure he received a fair trial.
The allegation was he had not competently cross-examined Crown witnesses and
that the defence case had not been properly placed before the jury. However,
the Court of Criminal Appeal ruled that lack of skill or diligence in the
preparation or conduct of a defence could not be pled as a basis for claiming a
miscarriage of justice.
Five judges, headed by Lord Justice General Hope, have been pondering whether,
nearly 50 years on, that can still be regarded as good law.
It is easy enough to see the rationale behind the 1949 decision. In court cases
there is always a loser unhappy with the outcome, particularly when he has been
convicted and sent to jail. It is easy to blame your lawyer even although he
might have done his best and the case was a no-hoper from the start.
In the middle of a court case lawyers also have to think on their feet as
evidence develops and it is easy with hindsight to say a certain question
should have been put or not put to a particular witness at a particular time.
Does the fact that it wasn't make the lawyer incompetent?
To suggest that the conduct of criminal trials by counsel (and solicitor
advocates) should not be open to scrutiny would leave Scotland out of line with
other legal systems which already allow an appeal on the grounds of incompetent
legal representation.
Appeal judges in England have indicated that an appeal would be competent where
counsel had taken a decision during a trial in defiance of or without proper
instructions ``when all promptings of reason and good sense pointed the other
way''.
Lawyers are naturally concerned the floodgates will open and every convicted
person with a grudge will be heading straight back to court no matter how well
their case was conducted. They are also afraid that trials could drag on
interminably with counsel having to safeguard themselves by getting
instructions in writing every time a major tactical decision has to be made.
The appeal court would obviously have to lay down extremely strict guidelines
within which any new rules would operate.
Mr Graham Bell QC, who appeared before the five judges to argue a change in the
law, suggested an appeal should be allowed where incompetent legal
representation had resulted in a accused person's defence not being properly
presented to the court.
The court would have to be satisfied that the defence in question was
important, likely to have had a significant bearing on the decision of the jury
and a miscarriage of justice had occurred.
One factor which may help persuade the judges to change the law is that,
whereas in 1949 the only option was to quash a conviction and allow a convicted
man to walk free, Scots law can now allow a retrial following a successful
appeal.
In the sphere of civil law, doctors, architects, surveyors, and other
professional people (including solicitors) can be sued for negligence if their
work does not meet the standards expected of an ordinary member of the
profession exercising reasonable care.
A solicitor could be held liable if he pursued a case under the wrong Act of
Parliament or failed to raise a damages action within the three-year time
limit. Since the last century, however, the received wisdom has been that
counsel cannot be sued for negligence for work done and advice tendered in
connection with a court case.
This immunity was based on the absence of any contract between advocate and
client (unlike the solicitor/client relationship) and the fact that counsel
owes a duty not just to his client but to the court and the public. These
duties may sometimes conflict.
The authority for stating advocates are an exception to the normal rule is the
1876 case of Batchelor v Pattison and Mackersy in which damages were claimed
against counsel for alleged professional negligence and disregard of
instructions.
Lord President Inglis said: ``The nature of the advocate's office makes it
clear that in the performance of his duty he must be entirely independent and
act according to his own discretion and judgment in the conduct of the cause
for his client.
``What he does bona fide according to his own judgment ..... will not expose
him to any action for what he has done, even if the client's interests are
thereby prejudiced.''
In the recent sheriff court case in which Mr Christopher Haddow QC was sued for
#150,000 it was argued that the modern trend in the law of negligence was
against the views expressed in Batchelor.
Mr Gordon Nicholson QC, sheriff principal of Lothian and Borders, expressed
sympathy with that viewpoint, saying: ``I think the time may have come when the
decision in Batchelor ought to be reviewed to see whether it still properly
reflects what ought to be the position of an advocate in relation to claims of
professional negligence.
``I have little difficulty in holding that, apart from the restriction imposed
by the case of Batchelor, an advocate must be under a duty to take care not to
act negligently in respect of his actings on behalf of his client.''
There have been a number of English cases in the House of Lords in the past 25
years which suggest strongly that the scope of counsel's immunity has narrowed
considerably since last century and may no longer include, for example, written
work unconnected with court proceedings.
The modern cases were put to Sheriff Nicholson but the sheriff principal said
he had no option but to follow the 1876 decision which was binding on him and
still seems to be the law in Scotland.
As he suggested, however, it is perhaps time the situation in Scotland is
reviewed by an authoritative decision of the Court of Session.
A restatement of the law might even be welcomed by advocates who are no doubt
wise to take out insurance cover for negligence, rather than rely on the
increasingly fragile protection of a case that is 120 years old.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wallowing in ignorance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS I read John Macleod's Faithful daughter of Mother Church (November 28) and
Ruth Wishart's fanciful redesigning of the role of Pope John II (November 27),
I was reminded of a recent Channel 4 quasi-religious programme cobbled together
by Kirsty Wark's TV company.
Before us an Orangeman, also flushed with the desire to free Catholics from
error, cut a morning roll in two; he then switched the halves around at speed
on a worktop, posed a rhetorical question, and, as the camera closed in,
declared the doctrine of transubstantiation to be false.
These three, John Macleod, Ruth Wishart, and the Orangeman, illustrate the
distinction which St Thomas Aquinas makes concerning the state of not-knowing.
The Orangeman's lack of knowledge can be called ``nescience'' since he is not
expected to know; his interests lie elsewhere. To Ruth Wishart's and John
MacLeod's lack of knowledge, however, must be applied the term ``ignorance''
since they write professionally on a subject of their own choice.
Because of the contrived gravitas of John Macleod's work it is not unreasonable
to describe his ignorance as being culpable. He wallows in it; it leads him to
vilify persons and to see evil where there is none.
Your readers, interested in accuracy or even fairness, can correct the
misinformation of these two Herald articles by referring to Catechism of the
Catholic Church and The Code of Canon Law in the public library. Therein they
will find a full description of the sacrament of matrimony, the office of Roman
Pontiff, and the nature of the Catholic Church itself.
Finally, Catholics rightly distance themselves from the frequent distortions of
their faith expressed in The Herald by a remarkably significant number of
feature writers and they wonder why contributions by Catholics, as a rule, are
relegated to the letters section. A statement of The Herald's policy might
clarify, or even justify, this phenomenon.
William Docherty,
22 Inveresk Place,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spoiling the show</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR once, I find some sympathy for that theatre pest, the sweetie-paper
rustler. He was probably making an inarticulate protest, doing it deliberately
to annoy Marcella Evaristi (Weekend Extra, November 18).
Why? Because, by her own (first-sentence) admission, she's an even bigger pest
- the balcony ``hing-er''.
These selfish, inconsiderate people, not content with an uninterrupted view of
the stage, stick their great elbows on the ``velvety balcony'' and do a Glesca
``hing'', thereby blocking out 50% of the stage from the view of the
unfortunate person behind.
That person has then to duck and weave to see the action - and everyone behind
him has to do the same. The sweetie merchant, instead of a cowardly rustling,
should have tapped Marcella Evaristi and asked her, politely, to sit properly
and not be so thoughtless.
John T Robertson,
6 Bute Crescent, Bearsden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
