<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Windsurfing in Tiree</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING just returned from a windsurfing holiday I was most interested in the
debate regarding windsurfing in Tiree. In the light of your study of tourism in
Scotland it seemed particularly pertinent.
I took up windsurfing some seven years ago, was introduced to Tiree by friends,
and have returned 12 times since then. I doubt that I would ever had gone there
but for windsurfing.
A distinction should be made between the people who attend the ``Wave Classic''
and the ordinary windsurfing tourist. Most of the competitors in the former are
young, male, single, and poor.
Neither windsurfing nor surfing are rich sports. Most ``pros'' live a
hand-to-mouth existence. It is no wonder that they are not big spenders. (I met
two competitors at Machrihanish some years ago whose supplies consisted of a
loaf of pan bread.)
But these people are not typical of the regular windsurfing tourist, as many
people of the island noted in their replies to a recent survey of attitudes to
windsurfers and reported in An Tirisdeach.
When my wife and I were on the island in the last week of September (hardly
peak tourist time) we were part of a group of people which included an actuary
and an engineer (the two ``pan loaf boys'', now somewhat older and wealthier),
two lawyers, a restaurateur, a Spanish factory owner, a PhD lecturer, a
surgeon, and a doctor. All the kind of tourists that most destinations would
roll over and beg for.
All of these people are in love with the island but would not be there but for
their love of the sport.
My own cottage, five people in all, ate out at the Tiree Lodge twice (#100),
spent #40 in the butchers, #110 in the Co-op, and #35 at the petrol station.
Not the biggest tourist spend in the world but from my observation of people in
the windsurfing resort of El Medano in Tenerife last week, about the same as
the tourists (windsurfing or not) in self-catering accomodation there.
These people will be visiting Tiree for the rest of their lives. To categorise
them as second-class tourists is a mistake.
The tensions between tourism and agriculture are not unique to Tiree but common
to all of the world that is a tourist destination. It was only natural that
some individuals in any community will suffer from increasing tourism while
others will gain.
I sympathise with the farmer whose land lies next to ``The Green'' but hope
that the local council could provide some way of recompensing him for the loss
of any productive land.
Certainly I know of no windsurfer who would not be willing to pay a small tax
to help pay for maintenance of tracks and ways. One of the problems is that
there are almost no signs whatsoever as to how to gain access to the relevant
beaches.
On behalf of the many passionate admirers of Tiree and its people I would ask
for understanding on all sides.
Ronnie Somerville,
36 Middlemuir Road,
Lenzie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enlightenment for the Governor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE Sir Bruce Pattullo, Governor of the Bank of Scotland, I too ``have no time
whatsoever'' for certain ideas, in my case for his dismissive views on
devolution or, for that matter, on economics (November 28).
The banking world is well-practised in looking after itself, and Sir Bruce and
his ``personal opinion'' are part of an outdated but powerful monetary system
which plays havoc with the human condition, and for which there is abundant
global evidence.
Enlightenment has to start somewhere and it might as well be here. If
responsibility and self-respect can be excited by devolution, then why not? Our
proven capacity for compassion and analysis is instanced by the real wealth of
Adam Smith's Moral Sentiments, but ignored by bankers in favour of an
avaricious over-emphasis on his Wealth of Nations.
Smith, of course, was not an economist but a moral philosopher, which probably
makes his own favourite treatise, the Moral Sentiments, ``romantic'' and
therefore an ``on-cost''.
George Wyllie,
9 McPherson Drive,
Gourock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Viable parties</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN his letter Norman Hogg states, ``The hard fact is the Scots do not support
the SNP in anything like the numbers that would make them a viable choice at
the next election'' (November 28).
If the 30% of Scots who do support the SNP does not make them a ``viable
choice'', should Norman Hogg not be questioning our so-called democracy? What
percentage of the vote does a party need before it becomes ``viable''?
Richard Newman,
26 Gartcraig Place,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dangers of CET</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH reference to Mr John Butterfill, MP for Bournemouth West, who wants to
change to Central European Time, I find his use of road safety as a vehicle to
do this quite distressing (November 24).
The Government already tried this experiment between 1966 and 1969 and while it
is true there was a reduction of accidents involving school children in the
afternoon, there was, however, sadly an increase of accidents to them in the
mornings, an increase of 1% overall.
There was a lot less traffic then, moving a lot more slowly than traffic on our
roads today.
Do not be misled by Mr Butterfill's words or by businessmen who want the
convenience of having their lunch at the same time as their counterparts in
Europe. It is up to all of us to protect our young and vulnerable road users.
After all, if a country the size of America can manage with eight different
time zones then surely Britain can cope with Europe as it is.
Ian MacLeod,
Road Safety Education
Officer,
Orkney Islands Council,
Kirkwall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shocking stamps</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DURING a recent holiday in Spain I noticed crisp, new 1000-peseta banknotes in
circulation. Half expecting to see Juan Carlos or some other member of the
Spanish monarchy, I was shocked instead to find portraits of Hernan Cortes and
Francisco Pizarro, butchers of the Aztec and Inca peoples respectively, given
pride of place.
Notwithstanding the obvious insult to the indigenous population of Latin
America, is this the only currency in contemporary Europe that honours the
perpetrators of genocide?
James Cormack,
194 Dumbuck Road,
Dumbarton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Irish first steps on the Gadarene slope</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME three months ago John Macleod was at great pains to denounce Catholicism
for the sensual roundness of its association with neo-paganism. Now he
castigates it for the angular intransigence of its fundamentalism in its stand
against divorce (November 28).
While I admit that the church is currently in bad shape nothing can be so
malformed as all that and hope to survive.
John Macleod informs us that the prohibition of divorce was ``against scripture
itself'' but the Master tells us that it was only allowed by Moses ``because of
the hardness of their hearts''.
The more things change the more they remain the same.
He will find cold comfort too in the Old Testament. For it says somewhere
``Thou shalt not commit adultery,'' and again ``Thou shalt not covet thy
neighbour's wife'' - thus gainsaying two overwhelming reasons for separation.
The apostles' counsel that it was ``better not to marry'' if divorce was not
allowed implies the fundamental change brought about by Christ. And to the
Christian it is the will of Christ that matters.
Therefore, despite the times, it is the function of the Church to ``preach the
good news in season and out of season and welcome or unwelcome to insist upon
it''. Come hell or high water or referendum.
Historically the unification of Church and State has brought nothing but
trouble into religious affairs. Eire is no exception. And there is always the
bright side. Their separation in Ireland should be a great stride towards
eventual political unification of that sad land.
But I doubt if the myopic will see it thus.
Tom McKay,
29 Manitoba Crescent,
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Irish first steps on the Gadarene slope</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN your editorial on November 15, concerning Bishop Holloway's opinions, you
rightly exposed the dangers involved in assuming that there is no such thing as
a moral absolute.
Before the Second Vatican Council, Ireland, and some other predominantly
Catholic nations, sought to enshrine such moral absolutes in their laws. They
considered the enshrining in law of these absolutes necessary to secure the
common good - which does not always correspond with the desires of individuals.
Alas, the gradual and sustained pressure of liberals and secularists has
removed almost every vestige of moral absolutes from the laws of these
societies, and many acts once thought heinous and destructive of social life
are now accorded as ``rights''.
The ever-increasing toll of ``easy'' divorce, broken homes, abortions, and the
looming and inevitable lurch towards compulsory euthanasia in our own country
bear witness to this abandonment of moral absolutes. Your observation that
``Societies and the way they interpret morals change; it is still wrong to
kill'' is of little comfort to aborted children.
That the Irish have chosen to take the first faltering steps on this Gadarene
slope to secularism gives comfort only to those who seek the final separation
of Church and State in Ireland. They will remain dissatisfied until the
American model is replicated in Ireland - a model which forbids children to say
prayers in state-funded schools.
John Macleod (November 28) berates Catholics in Ireland for enforcing their
morality on Irish Protestants and does so, smugly, as if liberal British
society does not force its amorality on its Catholic and Protestant citizens.
Through taxes we are forced to contribute to the killing of countless unborn
children, and we must also pay for the immense expense arising from the
consequences of divorce.
John Macleod, a closet secularist, will in true liberal style only tolerate
Catholics and some Protestants (because he doesn't even like some of them)
provided they accept the liberal model of society; a society in which the only
moral absolute is that there are no moral absolutes.
A S Fraser,
Burnbrae, Staffin Road,
Portree, Isle of Skye.East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Well rehearsed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WJACK Webster, that most lucid and reasonable of columnists, comments (November
27) on the cunning and possible hypocrisy of the Princess of Wales's
performance on Panorama. This does not appear to be a popular view but I
entirely agree with him.
Also, the ill-considered, albeit honest, comments on Diana by Nicholas Soames,
for which he has been duly caned, were at least made during a live programme in
contrast with the carefully rehearsed (17 hours of filming reduced to one hour)
Panorama broadcast which many people regarded as live and spontaneous.
David MacPherson,
51 Cresswell Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wallowing in ignorance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY is it that some people often begin a dialogue by displaying their stupidity
in all its glory and then spend the next 10 paragraphs or so trying to convince
us that they really do know a bit after all? In Ruth Wishart's case I'm sure
she does this completely unawares.
In her article about how ``Divorce can offer mixed blessings'' (November 27),
in the first column she points out ``it should not be the business of . . . the
Polish Pontiff to dicate to the men and women of Ireland''.
That seems to me a bit like saying it's not the place of a writer to write or
an artist to paint. As leader of the Catholic world, the Holy Father is only
performing his task as shepherd to the flock.
The next four columns were very positive and indeed sensible. It always
surprises me when I see good sense and great stupidity lying side by side.
Stephen F Carrick,
5 Hornbeam Road,
Abronhill, Cumbernauld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Staging a show of strength</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE of weeks ago the star of Braveheart and Hamlet collapsed at the end of
a day's rehearsal and was rushed to hospital. No, not that star. It was an
overworked and underfed Jimmy Chisholm, who plays alongside wee Mel in the
Wallace movie, who took a dizzy turn only a couple of hours before he was due
to go on stage in the Royal Lyceum's Caucasian Chalk Circle.
He would be back on typically ebullient form in time for the opening night of
the same company's Hamlet the following week.
However, for two nights the Edinburgh theatre was short of one actor in
Brecht's technically complicated show in which everybody was to play several
parts.
By chance, I was in the theatre that night and saw the company sail
effortlessly through, substituting artistic director Kenny Ireland (who was
word perfect, despite having less than two hours notice) and a
clipboard-carrying Tom McGovern (who, as the lead in Hamlet, surely had other
things on his mind).
Were it not for a pre-show apology, the audience might never have noticed
anything was up.
That the show must go on is theatrical lore, but that this show went on so
smoothly is testament to the way this past season has been organised at the
Lyceum.
Starting with Timberlake Wertenbaker's Our Country's Good, the theatre has
employed a core of around ten actors who stayed on first for Caucasian Chalk
Circle and then for Hamlet (which finishes on Saturday).
Apart from Pitlochry Festival Theatre, which operates such a system as a matter
of course, it's a surprisingly rare way to run a season - surprising, because
the benefits are all too apparent.
Agreeing to perform even when a key actor was absent is a prime example.
``At six o'clock we didn't know whether the show was going to go on or not,''
says Ann Louise Ross, who played Gertrude in Hamlet, several characters in the
other two, and will be back for The Steamie in January. ``We decided we could
do it and that was because we all felt secure with each other.''
It's a factor outsiders don't consider, but quite apart from the business of
acting, actors need time to settle in, just like anyone does in the first days
of a job.
Even being in work in the first place can take some getting used to if, like
most actors, you've just been unemployed. The company system bypasses these
distractions.
``It normally takes about a week to get to know people and that eats into
rehearsal time,'' says Ross. ``You don't know how a person works. Whether
they're quick or slow, you have to make allowances for each other.
``By the time we got to the read-through for Hamlet there was a relaxed feeling
because we all knew each other and how we worked.''
Audiences benefit too. It's not just that they appreciate the ensemble spirit,
it's also that they enjoy recognising actors and seeing them tackle a variety
of roles over a short period. And that variety is all the more broad when the
theatre, having to work with the same group of actors, is forced to break the
tyranny of typecasting.
It was no surprise, for example, to see Louise Ironside playing a convict in
Our Country's Good, but until now, who would have imagined her as Ophelia? It
is our good fortune somebody did.
``It was an excellent experiment,'' says Ireland, who is already trying to
through-cast for the spring season, although practical constraints are likely
to stop him repeating the full fixed-company model for some time.
``If you have a daunting task like doing Hamlet, any other company would have
had at least four weeks rehearsal. This is a practical solution. It means you
don't lose two or three days with them getting to know each other, you don't
lose two or three days when they're scared to show their performance. Everyone
dives in at the deep end.''
The system creates a sense of security that has both simple practical benefits
- Ross talks about the pleasure of getting to know the acoustic properties of
the auditorium, allowing her to develop a more subtle vocal range - and
aesthetic benefits because egos no longer come before the play.
``If you are an actor or a director doing the one show every so often, you have
to impress,'' says Ireland. ``In an ensemble company everybody knows they've
got a body of work to show themselves off, so you wouldn't do Hamlet in
hot-pants set in the 60s just to prove what a wonderful director you were, or
have Ophelia defecating on the stage just to prove how clever an actress she
was.''
The result has been a highly satisfying season of large-cast plays that have
stretched the theatre's technical resources and proved a hit with audiences.
When the company takes its final bow on Saturday night, it will be with a
thoroughly well-deserved sense of achievement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leila Mourad</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VETERAN Egyptian singer and actress Leila Mourad, who shot to fame in the 1940s
and 1950s, has died aged 77 The Jewish-born actress - who withdrew from the
limelight after a career spanning 39 years - died of heart failure in hospital
on November 22.
Mourad's vibrant voice and glamorous on-screen roles dazzled Middle Eastern
audiences during the heyday of Egyptian cinema. She retired in 1969 after
performing in more than 28 films and recording about 1000 songs.
She converted to Islam in the 1940s and was first married 1950s heart-throb
Anwar Wagdi and later Egyptian film director Fateen Abdel Wahab. She is
survived by her son Zaky Fateen Abdel Wahab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>At the end of the day, a cliche is worth its salt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Dr PAUL DAVIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLICH is the crime of our era. You may squeak by on adultery, sleaze, or
incompetence, but talk in cliche and a rabble of commentators and parvenus will
be clamouring with their wet sponges. Damn your opponent with a just charge of
cliche, and you have, ipso facto, won the argument.
The modern clichephobia is, like all cultural phobias, revealing of the
malformations and hang-ups of its time. It is sustained by a sloppy taxonomy.
At least five different kinds of semantic phenomena or social belief are
designated by the word ``cliche''. Clichephobes are unreceptive to the
differences, and therefore respond with enthusiastic but premature lack of
discrimination.
The first class of cliche is the ritual locution, expressive of a stance which
no-one, including the utterer, really endorses or is thought to endorse, the
purpose of which is evasion or obfuscation. Ask a football manager topping the
league in December if he thinks his team can win the title, and the questioner
is liable to be told that the club policy is one game at a time. No one
believes that this is ingenuous; the management, players, and fans are
excitedly contemplating the entire championship, and it would be a myopic
management, in fact, who considered only the next match. Similarly, sceptical
eyes are cast upon the exposed politician who claims he doesn't consider
hypothetical questions. Everyone knows political life, and any kind of valuable
human life, would be impossible without consideration of unactualised
possibilities.
The second kind of cliche is the ground-floor truth, belief, or assumption with
which someone might begin a discussion, for example: Turkey is the bridge
between East and West; women are historically subjugated; we live nowadays in a
global village. This class differs from the first, inasmuch as utterance is
generally believed ingenuous, and audience acceptance is usually universal.
Every business has its jargon, and this blameless fact underwrites the third
species of cliche. Reality is repetitive, and jargon mirrors this feature in
its own repetition. But modern clichephobes find this natural repetition
risible. Woe betide the football journalist sufficiently callow to report he
saw a ``game of two halves'', even if the regular pattern of match for which
the expression was coined is in fact witnessed by the scribe.
The fourth class displays comfortable and lazy folk-wisdom. It is a revealing
fact that some members of this class are seldom properly articulated,
subscription being betrayed by other statements and responses. Resistance to
articulation protects a belief from contestation, allowing it, instead, to
shape lived experience intimately and tactfully from within. The most
conspicuous examples of the rarely articulated members of the fourth class are
social beliefs about professions and interest groups: for example, that
scientists are emotionally repressed, accountants are boring.
The most obvious examples of the articulated cases are the formalisation of
national and provincial stereotype: London is impersonal; Glaswegians are
friendly and humorous.
The fifth class of cliche does not involve truth value. Its members are
expressions and turns of phrase: at the end of the day; over the piece; at this
moment in time; to be quite honest with you.
The five classes of cliche do not exclude each other universally. An obvious
combination is the second and fourth; for example, a speaker addressing a
Scottish audience might present as ground-floor truth the Scots are more
friendly than the English, and there might be uncritical acceptance in his
audience.
We now inhabit a culture which extends very little houseroom to the unshowy,
dogged use of the intellect. We demand increasingly that writers and speakers
jolt, thrill, and unsettle. We therefore thrust our accolades at the
strainingly clever and wacky performers of the pen and of the tongue.
Conversely, our era downgrades and parodies the rigorous, self-effacing use of
intellect. This reflects, in turn, our style-riven times. Cliche is
stylistically humdrum, therefore it is culturally inadmissible. Postmodernism,
with its dethronement of truth and elevation of text, offers a mild injection
of culturally timely intellectual sponsorship.
Intellectually, our culture finds it difficult to go the distance. Proper use
of intellect entails boredom. If correctness is sometimes as important as
flashiness, then the greyness of cliche is an ineliminable source of boredom.
And we are not at ease with the notion of an enriching or fructifying boredom.
n Dr Paul Davis is a freelance philosopher and writer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Log jam is breached. Now spotlight turns to men of violence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is much head-scratching over what exactly has happened to the Northern
Ireland peace process. Have the Irish and British Prime Ministers worked long
and mightily and brought forward a fudge, as alleged yesterday by some
disgruntled figures? Or do we have here a creative piece of political
manoeuvring which might allow the stalled process to move forward once more,
albeit on rusty rails? The answer to those questions is that both fudge and
creativity are involved, although working out where the fulcrum lies between
them is not easy. We should dispose first of all with the Washington
connection. It was said yesterday that the rush to agreement by Mr Bruton and
Mr Major was encouraged by President Clinton's imminent arrival in the United
Kingdom. This could be taken two ways: either the two Prime Ministers were
anxious to gain some sort of agreement to prevent the possibility of President
Clinton gathering the merit from any potential progress, or they rushed matters
along for fear of harsh words from the leader of the Western world.
The first point is the most reasonable. Having worked long and hard it is
perfectly understandable if Mr Bruton and Mr Major did not relish the prospect
of President Clinton claiming credit. The truth is that he is due a good
measure of credit but is too sensible to claim it, at least in public.
Washington has lobbied energetically in Dublin in recent days with the aim of
moving the Irish Government's belief that it is not possible for the IRA to
dispose of any weapons before all-party talks begin. Arm-twisting will also
have been applied to Sinn Fein, for Washington is less pleased with Mr Gerry
Adams than it was earlier this year. It is unlikely that attitudes have been
altered on matters of so-called principle, but the log jam has been breached a
little and negotiations may start to flow again.
This does not mean that a solution has been found. It may be unkind to describe
this week's agreement as a fudge but that is what it is. Nobody, as far as can
be seen, has changed their minds on the major issues. The British Government
and the Irish Government still hold their respective positions on the question
of disposing of arms but they have decided to set their differences aside to
allow someone else to shoulder the arms burden for a while. This, they hope,
will permit the preparatory talks to go ahead. Here we have movement and
creativity. The talks will be intensive, or so Mr Major hopes, and the Ulster
Unionists have been lured towards them by the promise that the issue of an
elected body will be discussed. This should allow initial Unionist scorn to be
dissipated somewhat, though for the sake of his electoral prospects Mr Major
would be advised to keep a weather eye on Mr Trimble and his associates.
Yet there is a positive side to all the manoeuvring of recent days. The British
and Irish Governments have re-established a momentum of sorts which will allow
the peace process to escape from the backwater in which it was mired. They have
done something else just as important. Mr Major was determined yesterday to
impress on the participants that he and Mr Bruton could not establish a peace
settlement by themselves. Speaking directly to the violent and the gun-holders
on both sides of the argument he is saying that the next move is up to them.
This is a powerful message; it is time they listened to it, and acted
accordingly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Light Opera, TSB, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bert McCann</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS presentation at the TSB's Edinburgh HQ was a review of a work-in-progress
and also an appeal for corporate sponsorship in order to assure the project's
future.
Set up two years ago by the Edinburgh-based Slide Workshop, Light Opera is a
multi-media project continuing Slide Workshop's Equal Arts Programme in
conjunction with the charitable Drake Music Project. For 10 years Slide
Workshop has encouraged people to discover their own hidden abilities using
image projection, lighting techniques, and sound.
Similarly, the Drake Music Project enables physically-disabled young people and
adults to make music utilising computer technology while carrying out research
in expanding uses of electronic machinery.
Light Opera's presentation combined instrumental and vocal music, slide
projection, and video production with a photographic display recording the
company's work. The band of five musicians and singers, disabled and
non-disabled, performed to a high standard.
Vicky Haylott's ballad, backed by David Trouton on keyboards and Rick Bamford
on percussion, filled the TSB's atrium with rich, strong sound. Richard Weir
took over on vocals with Brian Sutherland joining on keyboard arrangement with
a witty epigrammatic play on popular nursery rhymes. Liz Tainch projected slide
images to kaleidoscopic effect.
As we are currently in the National Week of Disabled People, it would be
fitting if funding were forthcoming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tis Pity She's a Whore, Ramshorn Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Minty Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
'ON one hand, it's highly commendable that Strathclyde Theatre Group's
semi-professional company should tackle difficult and challenging work . . .and
you don't get much more challenging than the black hearted, morally complex
world of John Ford's Jacobean tragedy.
Certainly, there's educational value in allowing the play to be seen and in
offering aspiring actors the opportunity to grapple with meaty roles.
Undoubtedly, STG's affiliations with Strathclyde University make sense of this
pedagogical function. But when, as in this instance, the quality of the
production is so uneven and shoddily staged, it raises the question of just for
whom the piece is intended.
Don't get me wrong, it wasn't all bad. It was revealing to see the Ramshorn
Theatre opened up into Traverse format, although sight lines into the
scaffolding structures at either end were a problem.
Strong performances, noteably by the female members, reached the necessary
level of passion and intensity. Above all, the power of Ford's horribly
pertinent drama of sexual taboos, madness, incest, and intrigue, shone through.
However, a piece of such heightened emotion, florid language, and ideological
complexity, needs a clear confident and coherent vision to guide it and give it
credibility.
The sheer visial panache and bold dramatic sweeps of the best of the Citizens'
Jacobean productions were sadly lacking in Susan C Triesman's direction,
leaving actors to struggle with a text they seemed not fully to understand and
strut woodenly around a bland set.
</TEXT>
