<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why it's tough at the bottom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONE parents and the young unemployed are to pay for the 1p cut in income tax
announced in the Budget. Chancellor Kenneth Clarke had barely sat down on
Tuesday before Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley was on his feet to spell
out who will be footing the bill for the Government's largesse.
Single people under 25 in private rented accommodation will face curbs in
eligibility for housing benefit. (Effectively, the young unemployed will
qualify only for the cost of shared accommodation, rather than that of a
self-contained flat.)
Lone parents are spared from this axe but will suffer two other blows. Both of
the special payments available to one-parent families are to be frozen and
eventually phased out. At present a lone-parent premium of #5.20 a week goes to
single parents on income support and all lone parents qualify for the #6.30 a
week one-parent benefit.
Both cuts were leaked by Labour earlier this month following the interception
of a letter from Mr Lilley to Treasury Chief Secretary William Waldegrave.
Nevertheless, confirmation that they were to go ahead provoked a furious
reaction yesterday from the Opposition and pressure groups representing those
who stand to lose out.
The cuts in housing benefit apply to all new claims and reviews of existing
claims made after next October and will affect an estimated 135,000 claimants
aged 16 to 24. This is expected to save the Treasury #100m over three years.
The benefit has been targeted already for large-scale pruning, mainly by
cutting back on the categories of people eligible. The Government is concerned
at the alarming way the housing benefit bill has doubled since they switched
housing subsidy from bricks and mortar to individuals in 1987, in a bid to
stimulate the private-rented sector. The effect has been large rent rises with
the suspicion that many landlords are milking the system.
In future a rent officer will base his assessment on the average cost in the
area of a bedsit or room in a multi-occupation flat when the applicant is less
than 25.
Justifying the cuts on Tuesday, the Chancellor said they would deter young
people from leaving home before they could afford to, that they would encourage
youngsters to rent within their means and would increase incentives to work.
Critics question all three arguments.
Shelter Scotland says the policy ignores the plight of those under-25s who
simply don't have families to return to because they grew up in care or because
they have been kicked out of the parental home or forced to leave because of
abuse.
And the charity argues that in many areas of Scotland, rural areas in
particular, shared accommodation is simply not available. As for incentives to
work, Michael Thain of Shelter says: ``The real issue is that unemployment
among young people remains high because there are not enough jobs.''
This cut in housing benefit can be seen as the latest instance of the
Government's policy of encouraging ``youth rates'' in both employment and the
benefits system. It began nine years ago with the removal of under-21s from the
pay protection offered by wages councils. Peter Hunter of the Scottish Low Pay
Unit said: ``These changes combine to create a package in which young people
get less, whether it's in work, benefits or training. This means they find it
harder to pay their rent. If anything, they require more help rather than less.
The obvious consequence of cutting help with housing costs is more young people
being forced on to the streets.''
The announcements about lone-parent premium and one-parent benefit signal the
ending of official recognition that lone parents face higher costs, especially
for childcare. ``The right approach is to neither penalise nor to promote lone
parenthood,'' Mr Lilley told the Commons yesterday. In political terms this is
clearly a move designed to pander to the Tory right who have caricatured lone
mothers as unmarried teenagers, happy to live off the state and even
deliberately becoming pregnant in order to maximise their benefits, despite
ample evidence to the contrary.
The phasing out of lone-parent premium is likely to increase the hardship of
some of the most vulnerable families. Around 40% of Scotland's 132,000 lone
parents live on less than #100 a week, compared with just 2% of two-parent
families, according to One Plus, which helps and lobbies for one-parent
families in Strathclyde. ``There can be no excuse for taking away benefits
which so many families need simply to survive,'' said One Plus  director, John
Findlay.
One-parent benefit was designed as a ladder to help lone parents climb out of
welfare back into work. That's why it isn't means-tested. Abolishing it appears
to fly in the face of everything the Conservatives stand for. Though the loss
of this benefit will be partially offset by an increase in childcare allowances
from #40 to #60 a week and there's the promise of a pilot scheme to help lone
parents get training and jobs, there are fears that much of the supposed
savings from the lone-parent benefits cuts will be lost in increased income
support payments to single mums who decide to stay at home.
</TEXT>
