<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peace signed but not delivered</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Cameron Simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Christmas tree and the coloured lights festooned on the shops at the top
cross in Hamilton proclaim it to be the season of goodwill to all men. But for
striking postal workers stamping their feet to keep warm around a dustbin
brazier just 100 yards away there is one man they would absent from the list.
He is Gordon Johnson, newly-promoted line manager at the Hamilton sorting
office, who has unwittingly found himself at the centre of a bitter local
dispute which threatens to rekindle the embers of last week's national
unofficial strike.
The national strike's epicentre was the tiny office of Portobello where a local
walkout over changing work practices and the threat they posed to jobs spread
shockwaves throughout the country which were to register more than 5000
Scottish postal workers taking unofficial action.
According to one postman, it was an ``outburst of underlying anger at the
manner in which management has undertaken the task of rationalisation over the
past five years''.
The men voted to return to work on Sunday and began clearing a 12 million
letter backlog which built up during the strike. Hamilton, the only place where
the strike was official, recorded a similar vote on Monday.
And it is the fact that the strike at Hamilton was official which is crucial to
the understanding of what has followed.
For the past 16 weeks workers there had been in the vanguard of additional
supervision and close monitoring as management introduced new working practices
and cut back on second deliveries of post.
The men had come to the end of their tether. As the unofficial dispute
escalated, they made their action official against the trend towards
casualisation, increased use of part-time staff, and heavier workloads.
Then, on Sunday, a settlement was reached with a 14-point peace plan promising
a review of delivery services. Talks would continue between the two sides until
mid-January with the Communication Workers' Union agreeing to suspend plans to
ballot members on taking official action.
As part of the deal, union officials at Hamilton claimed they were told Mr
Johnson, who in their minds is indivisible from management's drive to change
working practices and ultimately cut jobs, would be moved.
Mr Tam McHugh, the local CWU representative, said yesterday Mr Johnson himself
had told him he was being sent back to Shotts. However, when the nightshift
arrived for work at midnight on Monday they found Mr Johnson was still there -
a red rag to a bull.
Mr McHugh said yesterday: ``So we never actually went back to work and are
still on official strike.''
They genuinely believed, he said, that they had an agreement that Mr Johnson
would be moved and that the changes in work practices would be put on hold
while they are debated at national level.
Royal Mail see it differently and said yesterday they would not remove Mr
Johnson as a pre-condition of a return to work.
As Mr McHugh speaks he has constantly to raise his voice as passing cars toot
their support for the strikers. ``We want to go back and deliver mail to the
public but we will not work with Mr Johnson.''
He added: ``At one stage during the past 16 weeks we had 10 managers for 68
workers. If anyone stopped working they would come up and tell you to get on
with it. I have had my members called `lazy bastards' while I was called a `fat
bastard' by one of the managers. It was just ludicrous.''
Royal Mail as a business had made a profit of #1500m last year, but this it
would seem is not enough.
``As usual, they are trying to take it off the bottom of the tree. In Hamilton
we fear the management want to cut 25 second deliveries which would mean the
loss of 12!s jobs. It is all about saving money.''
Management allegations of unruly and violent picketing are vehemently denied.
``Ask the police. They will tell you there has been no trouble. The accusation
has been levelled by Alex Gibb, delivery director for Scotland, but he has
never been here.''
Mr McHugh also took exception to another of Mr Gibb's comments. Mr Gibb said
yesterday: ``We will no longer be able to open the inquiry office for customers
coming in to collect their mail. It's simply not safe. I am sure our customers
will understand that we cannot put our people at risk.''
However, Mr McHugh maintained that was just not true. He said: ``If the public
wanted their mail, we let them in. There was a wee lassie who didn't want to
cross our picket line but was desperate to collect her giro. We told her to go
in just as we have told any other members of the public. We have no problem
with that.''
Both sides now seem deeply dug in and what happens next is anyone's guess. As
Mr McHugh returns to warm his hands at the brazier, this could be the spark to
reignite the whole dispute.
Elsewhere there is a growing feeling it is at best an uneasy peace which has
broken out nationally with the day of reckoning postponed until the season of
goodwill ends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
