<RECORDNO>975126587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Rugby Union yesterday launched a scheme aimed at securing business
support for the country's leading players.
The idea was born before the rule changes on professionalism in a bid to
encourage employers to take on players with support from the SRU. It is
intended to formalise the kind of social and professional links forged at club
level throughout the country.
SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer said: ``The problems of reconciling the
demands of first-class rugby with a career will not be solved easily. We will
listen carefully to the views of employers before taking this initiative
forward. This is just the first step.
``Much has been said about professionalism and while it is true that there is
more money coming into the game, very few first-class players are likely to
benefit significantly, and certainly not in the short term.
``For the players to be successful they have to spend quite an amount of time
away from their work. We are trying to keep the best players in Scotland and we
are trying to keep the best players with the best careers as well.''
``If the correct player goes to the correct company, there is a mutual benefit
to both.''
The SRU plans further meetings to discuss careers with a variety of
organisations, including the police service and hospital trusts.
Among those speaking at the launch was Eric Barr, chairman of PEC Barr
Printers, whose sales manager is former Scotland hooker Kenny Milne.
``The problem now is that circumstances are changing so quickly that it is
quite      difficult to keep up,'' said Barr.
``We employed Ken not as an up-and-coming rugby star but as an established
internationalist. When we took him on we knew the ramifications and rugby
undoubtedly helped.
``The public relations aspect is an asset, but he is good at his job here, but
then his international status also helps him to be good at his job.''
q FORMER Scotland captain David Sole declined an invitation to appear at
Murrayfield last night following his reported criticism of referee Colin
Henderson, but the meeting went ahead, attended by two officials from Edinburgh
Academicals.
Sole, who coaches the Accies forwards, had been summoned to account for his
public outburst against the referee following the league defeat by Melrose at
Raeburn Place. Sole questioned the nine successive penalties awarded to Melrose
in injury time from which the Borderers scored their winning try to put
Academicals on course for relegation.
Academicals' secretary Ken Lauder said: ``It is likely that there will be a
future meeting between the SRU and David Sole at Murrayfield.''
Sole was unable to accept the SRU's invite because of baby-sitting duties, his
wife having to attend a meeting associated with her new business venture.
Meanwhile, Edinburgh Academicals, having been asked by Melrose to investigate
further the incident in which Melrose prop Mark Ross received a blow to his eye
that has caused sight impairment, have made ``a suitable response.''
``We have looked into the matter and our conclusion is that the incident
happened in the usual hurly-burly of front-row play. We believe that punches
were thrown by both sides,'' said Academicals secretary Lauder.
q THIRTY-THREE players have been called up for the Scotland squad session on
Sunday at Murrayfield. In addition to the 21 who were in the squad for the
Western Samoa match 12 others have been invited, significant among whom are
back row forward Eric Peters, centre Tony Stanger, scrum halves Andy Nicol and
Derrick Patterson, and hooker Martin Scott.
Also included are Scott Hastings and Craig Joiner, both ruled out of selection
for the Samoan match because of injury, and prop Peter Wright, who missed the
last international game because of a six-week suspension. The others invited to
attend         are Cameron Glasgow, prop Millan Browne and locks Ian Elliot and
Malcolm Norval.
</TEXT>
