<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McLeish supplies the killer blow</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Glasgow Under-21 22, South Under-21 17
GLASGOW opened their inter-district under-21 championship campaign with this
success at Murrayfield last night.
The winning try was scored by the former Kelso player, David McLeish, now with
West of Scotland. McLeish played well, with Steve Begley also making notable
contributions in the lineout.
Behind the scrum, Jamie Weston began to play more visionary rugby, tormenting
the South defence with some telling runs.
South applied the early pressure, Gavin Dalgleish putting over a penalty before
McLeish scored the first of his two tries from short-range to put Glasgow
ahead. Tony Greenshield added the conversion, but South scored a try from scrum
half David Paterson, Dalgleish adding the conversion.
When Steve Lawrie raced over for South's second try and Dalgleish converted, it
seemed the Borderers were heading for victory. However, Glasgow reasserted
themselves and Greenshield pulled them back with a penalty. Then the full back
was on hand to add the conversion of a splendid try by Geoff Caldwell from a
break by Weston.
Right on time Glasgow made their pressure rugby tell when McLeish, from a
pick-up at a scrum five metres out, evaded the fringe defence for his second
try to bring Glasgow victory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aitken kick-starts feast of points</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Edinburgh Under-21 45,
North-Midlands Under-21 0
EDINBURGH, the defending champions put on a polished performance at Murrayfield
to outclass an under-strength North-Midlands side last night.
Sammy Dow gave the game an excitement that has been missing in so much of
Scottish rugby, the Edinburgh Academical, until he retired injured 30 minutes
into the game, showing the value of a running stand-off.
Edinburgh, with likely senior players Graham Dall, Tam McVie, and Scott Murray
in their pack, were much too skilful for a North-Midlands side that at best
contributed with some resistant defence.
A Campbell Aitken penalty triggered Edinburgh's point-scoring machine into
action before Dow side-stepped through the defence for a marvellous solo try
which Aitken converted.
Aitken's second penalty gave Edinburgh a 13-0 half-time lead, but the
title-holders really cut loose in the second half. Winger Ally McLean opened
with an unconverted try before Aitken blazed through an eroded defence for
another unconverted touchdown.
Edinburgh increased their lead through tries by Grant Talac, Doug Rogerson, and
Scott Murray, a dropped goal by Mike Duncan and two further conversions by
Aitken.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
