<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SINGLE-MINDED STRUGGLE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n-LOSING #5.20 from the weekly income must hardly seem worth worrying about for
those with a job. The price of a couple of drinks or a taxi fare. So what. But
for lone parents subsisting on income support any erosion in benefits brings
unbearable financial pressure.
Yesterday in Glasgow a group of single mothers, currently studying for an
administration qualification in an attempt to find a job, listed everyday items
that would have to go when, as outlined by Social Security Minister Peter
Lilley, the one-parent premium is phased out along with the #6.10 one-parent
benefit paid to families regardless of income.
For women like Anne McAllister, who left an abusive partner and has one
daughter, or Alexis Couper, who has four children, a fiver buys a week's worth
of cheap dinners, a power card, a box of nappies or a bus pass. It pays for a
couple of trips to the swimming pool, for gymnastic lessons for Ms McAllister's
daughter, or contributes towards after-school care for Liz Fallon's
five-year-old son.
Managing on benefits that range from #77 a week to #150 a week the women say
while it can be tough on a daily basis, the biggest problem is coping long term
on benefits. Think what happens, says Ms McAllister, if the washing-machine
breaks down. Any loss of benefits means worrying about how to pay back a DSS
loan, usually 13% of a person's income, for a new machine. Phasing out premiums
totalling #20 a month means not being able to buy a new pair of shoes or a
jacket for a child or simply skimping on meals themselves to feed their
children.
Attacks on single mothers angers people like Ms Fallon who says that she is
trying to improve her life through education. Single parents, she says, are
portrayed by the Government as irresponsible teenage girls when the majority
have been in stable relationships and would not have chosen the circumstance
they find themselves in.
The 26-year-old lives in a privately rented flat in Renfrew. She has a
five-year-old son, Sean-Paul, and a three-year-old daughter, Gemma. The father
of her children died after taking a drugs overdose.
In addition to income support she receives #18 a week child benefit but pays
#20 a week in after-school care, a loan repayment of #10 and a fixed
electricity payment of #20. She is left with #43 for food, clothes, shoes, bus
fares to her mother's house in the north of Glasgow and, next month, Christmas
presents. Her son has already requested that he get more than two small
presents.
In spite of the difficulties Ms Fallon is optimistic about her future after
admitting spending a couple of years doing nothing. ``I've got up and decided
to do something. I want to study for an HNC and then go to London and do an HND
in business and computing.''
But that future depends on paying the #6 a week subsidised child-care costs at
Glasgow's Nautical College when she enrols for an HNC next year. So while some
may shrug at #5 a week, it is ironic that Ms Fallon's attempts to free herself
from state dependence could be dashed by a state saving of a fiver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doherty pays for mistakes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RECORD-BREAKING Stephen Hendry for once failed to hit the heights yesterday at
the Royal Liver Assurance UK Championship in Preston. But the Scot's
consolation for a below-par display against Irish stablemate Ken Doherty is a
6-2 overnight lead in their best-of-17-frames quarter-final.
When the duo met in the 1994 UK final, Hendry went on a potting spree, notching
five century breaks in seven frames and seven in 12 during his 10-5 triumph.
The world No.1 almost reproduced that dazzling form, this time in the earlier
rounds when he produced his 147 maximum against Gary Wilkinson in the last 16.
But after threatening to launch his bid for the penultimate round with another
massive clearance, Hendry surprisingly went off the boil.
He won the opening frame with a break of 85, but fluffed an easy pink with a
possible 144 on the table.
World No.9 Doherty, who has won only two of their 10 previous meetings,
levelled the score at 1-1 with runs of 48 and 34. This was the closest he came
to Hendry through bad luck and carelessness.
Breaks of 37 and 85 propelled the 26-year-old defending champion 3-1 ahead at
the mid-session interval. However, he seemed certain to lose the fifth with
Dubliner Doherty forging clear, courtesy of a 53 break.
To his cost, Doherty missed an easy pink and Hendry's own 53 eventually helped
him take the frame 77-53.
In the next frame it was Hendry's turn to make the mistake. He led 47 points to
nil but allowed Doherty to recover with a run of 59. All Doherty required was a
clearance up to the blue, but he snookered himself on the final yellow.
After several safety exchanges Doherty found himself snookered tight behind the
brown ball. Trying to find an escape to hit the green, instead he struck the
blue three times.
At the fourth attempt he reached his target, but left the ball on for Hendry to
clear green to pink and go 5-1 up.
The last two frames of the session were shared and Doherty will be disappointed
not to start on level terms for the conclusion of the match this afternoon.
Hendry requires only three of the remaining nine frames to stay on course for
his fourth UK title in six years.
Peter Ebdon, defeated by Hendry in the semi-finals 12 months ago, established a
5-3, first-session lead over Nigel Bond, and at the end of their quarter-final
last night there still were two frames between the pair, with Ebdon winning the
match 9-7.
In the other tie, Scotland's John Higgins, who in the previous round defeated
Jimmy White, was not having things his own way against Mark Williams in the
early stages, but steadied, eventually ending the session at 4-4 with the
Welshman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Beautiful South, SECC, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I
BEAUTIFUL South fans are tall. Nothing wrong with that. Unless you're
unfortunate enough to be stuck standing at the back of a packed-hangar SECC.
Then it's most unfortunate. Particularly when the tall ones have come along to
listen, motionless. Us small ones were forced to balance upon each others
shoulders if we wanted to see the band.
But this precarious act was worth it, if only to witness the sight of Paul
Heaton, he of the Clark Kent jaw and Bernard Manning belly, singing, I Think
the Answer's Yes, while sashaying across the stage. Sand dancing indoors.
Outstanding.
He's got a fine old voice this fellow. At times it worries, but always remains
this side of overblown. And the overall sound from the band was good too, just
what you'd expect from their records. Very nice. But no more than that. None of
yer raucous japery here mate. What you get are well crafted songs with clever,
ironic lyrics.
Ideal for home listening or a more intimate venue where the alcohol flows and
the only impediment to a good view is a thick curtain of cigarette smoke.
Heaton told us a tale of a recent drinking session with Blur. It involved
champagne, a hotel reception and a hot water bottle. Very funny I'm sure, but
the gist got lost somewhere in the ether off this high-vaulted hall.
They're troupers though, the Southies. The guitar player is apparently dead
from a broken arm, singer Jacqueline Abbott's missing, pregnant, the bass amp
broke down, and still the show went on. They might not rock, but they certainly
roll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Angela's target is Olympic trials</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elspeth Burnside</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANGELA Pendrich gave hint of a return to form at the Cumbernauld Meet and is
now determined to fight her way back into the international reckoning via the
Scottish winter championships in two weeks' time.
The 19-year-old Commonwealth Games swimmer spent the summer sidelined by
glandular fever, but bounced back to win a silver and bronze at Cumbernauld.
``It's not been an easy time,'' admitted the London-based youngster. ``I've had
to change clubs after my coach moved to Wales, and now I'm training with the
local Greenwich Borough Mariners.
``I was pleased with my performance at Cumbernauld, because I'd only been back
in training for five weeks, and now I'm hoping to build on that at Ayr. The
first priority is to force my way back into the Scottish team.''
The Olympic trials in March remain the big target, although she realises it is
a long shot. Last time, it all ended in tears when she lost out by fractions of
a second in the 400 metres free-style.
This time, she faces even tougher opposition. Sarah Hardcastle's comeback has
limited her chances in the distance free-style, while the evergreen Kathy Osher
will be form favourite to take the spot in Pendrich's other discipline, the
200m back-stroke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Swimming</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sport's governing body, FINA, has admitted an anomaly in their new
sanctions for drug offences, which means the penalty for refusing to take a
test is shorter than that for being caught using banned substances.
The FINA congress has agreed automatic, four-year suspensions for swimmers
taking anabolic steroids, yet those who refuse to take a test receive only two
years. The four-year ban is unenforceable in countries where civil law views
anything longer than two years as a restraint of trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trees in predominance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by David Coulter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>88</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AROUND seven miles north of Inveraray on the A83 near Cairndow, a casual glance
at the magnificent Highland scenery around Loch Fyne holds several surprises
for anyone interested in our much-vaunted natural history.
In among the indigenous crimson-berried rowans and stately Scots pines set by
the roadside is a standard North American Giant Redwood in the Ardkinglas
woodland garden. Behind them the more slender-limbed Southern Beech from South
America flourishes. Eucalyptus trees from Tasmania, whose leaves make up the
staple diet of koala bears, are also visible among a host of other exotic
varieties from China and the Far East.
But this isn't arboreal contamination of our native flora. Rather, the tree
shop garden centre aims at providing a very wide range of exotic and indigenous
trees, shrubs and plants to cater for the growing interest in world as well as
domestic species in and around British gardens.
Surprisingly, to those of us with little knowledge of arboreal matters, and
partly because of the frost and lack of sunlight, December is a good month for
tree planting. With the shoots dormant for the winter, even the more
temperamental species can be well dug in just now, with three months of snow
and heavy winter to bed them down in plenty of time before spring works its
annual miracle.
The mild and wild climate of Argyll provides a first-class environment for the
shoots to thrive in, giving the centre's manager Mark Sands the satisfaction of
seeing good growth in a comparatively short time. All of which, coupled with
his comprehensive range, free catalogue and following mail order business, is
gaining the Tree Shop a country-wide reputation for excellent service and
quality goods.
A recent addition to the range of woodwork is folding garden furniture, made
from British hardwood. Designed to be elegant, yet strong, it folds for storage
and is light enough for anyone to carry.
The centre prides itself in an interest in the unusual but with the emphasis on
quality and an assured, friendly service.
The Tree Shop has also the luxury of a tasty little oyster bar as immediate
neighbour, where superb seafood can be taken away to be enjoyed at home, or
eaten on site fresh from the tanks.
Just an hour from Glasgow, and well within reach from anywhere in the central
belt, this woodland garden and extensive shopping area is a first-class
destination for any family fed up with the hustle and bustle of festive
shopping and that feeling of fighting the crowd.
</TEXT>
