<HEADLINE>Bruce Trent</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Veteran singer Bruce Trent has died at his London home, aged 82
BRUCE TRENT was one of the top singer-actors in stage musicals in the 40s and
50s, making frequent radio appearances and selling more than one million
records.
He took part in three Royal Variety Performances and appeared on many
television shows in Britain and America.
He was born Billy Butters in St Helier in Jersey and trained as an architect
before turning to showbusiness and coming to England in 1936.
He made his first broadcast in 1937 before joining the Jack Hylton Band where
his baritone voice was immediately popular with female fans.
When Hylton became one of the West End's top producers in the 40s he made sure
Trent got starring roles in shows such as Brigadoon, Camelot, and The Student
Prince.
Trent was married with four children. Comedian Ted Ray was his best man at his
wedding in 1940.
</TEXT>
