<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Triad and tested formula</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975126598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chinese director, Zhang Yimou, has made some memorable films, including Red
Sorghum, Raise the Red Lantern and The Story of Qui Ju with his regular star,
Gong Li. His latest, Shanghai Triad, a brilliantly conceived gangster thriller
in which Gong Li plays Bijou, the ambitious, sexually predatory mistress of
Tang (Li Biotang), a Shanghai Godfather, breaks new ground for them both.
Bijou - a cabaret singer, who struts her stuff in scarlet feathers while the
chorus dance around in white, and the boss's acolytes mutter about her lack of
talent in the wings - is having an affair with the boss's sidekick, Song (Sun
Chun). The stage is set for disaster.
The life of the Triad is seen during the course of a week through the eyes of
Shuisheng (Wang Xiaoxiao) a small country boy brought by his uncle to be the
mistress's servant.
There is a gang war in process which forces Tang to flee to a remote island
with his mistress and his closest supporters. The arrival of these evil, greedy
city people destroys the innocent way of life enjoyed by the islanders and
leads to a shocking climax.
Yimou cunningly keeps most of the violence off screen. Although we know awful
things have happened, the full horror - Martin Scorsese take note - comes from
knowing, not from having bloody things thrust in front of one's eyes.
Yimou has taken a familiar Hollywood genre piece, the Warner Brothers mobster
movie with the Claire Trevor tart with the heart and Edward G Robinson gangster
characters, and translated them to an alien world with consummate brilliance.
Shanghai Triad looks magnificent, the performances, especially that of Gong Li,
are outstanding, while the ending, with the boy suspended upside down from the
mast of the Boss's boat for trying to protect his mistress, is truly chilling.
His world has literally been turned upside down.
</TEXT>
