<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A sporting chance is all art needs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Woods</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DREAD the coming of the Turner Prize and generally try to avoid the hype
surrounding it. This is partly because of a dislike of all artistic
competitions and prizes - which have turned music, above all, into a
competitive sport - and partly because I hate to be reminded of how great the
gulf is between contemporary art and the general public.
The Turner Prize, for all its good intentions - and I am charitably assuming it
has good intentions, though it has never really been clear what or who the
prize is for - widens that gulf. Contemporary art never gets noticed by the
tabloids unless there is an opportunity to re-run the Bricks at the Tate story.
There would be no chance, in Britain, of the type of reponse by the German
tabloid Bild to Christo's wrapping of the Reichstag in Berlin this summer: mad,
but wonderful. All art here must be categorised as mad, bad, and a joke at the
taxpayer's expense. This I can live with, but the broadsheets and the TV arts
programmes cover the Turner Prize artists as if they come from another planet;
there is a bemused, jokey approach to the whole thing. Every year, they ask:
``But is it art?'' Of course it is. What else would it be? The question is:
``Is it any good?''
All this, together with the bookmakers' odds and all the hoopla, means work
which could get through to people - to individual people, not ``the public'' -
is overwhelmed. I went to see House twice in the year Rachel Whiteread won the
prize. It was a strange and remarkable piece, standing there in isolation like
so many houses briefly left over from demolition in wastelands all over London.
It struck a chord. People brought their children.
This year Damien Hirst won, of course. Children like his work, too. Not the dot
paintings, which are a part of a coherent but restricted, very restricted,
internal debate about painting and the nature of painting - I don't like them
much myself, because they haven't anything new to say; but certainly the
infamous work, the shark in formaldehyde and everything that followed it - art
as natural history, as spectacle.
Hirst is a showman. Advertisers nick his ideas; he nicks ideas from
advertisers. He makes it very clear the problem most people have with art is
not so much any individual art work, but the word ``art'' itself. Every day we
all process very sophisticated visual material without a moment's thought. But
when the word ``art'' precedes it, there is a terrible defensiveness.
Brian Eno began to address this in his speech at the award ceremony. A lot of
the blame lies with the art world - not necessarily artists - and this partly
because the art world often does not need a public. What matters to the dealer
is not the equivalent of bums on seats - feet on floors? - but cheques in
banks. If mystification sells, or if it helps writers and curators move on up
in academic circles, then it will not be overcome.
Mystification makes people feel stupid. But sometimes the response to
contemporary art is itself stupid, paranoid, insanely aggressive.
Artists cannot pretend the past 100 years have not happened. They cannot begin
to deal with criticism which suggests paintings and sculptures should look like
paintings and sculptures from 100 years ago, that they should not address our
lives now, seeking out new forms. Abstract painters must take 80 years of
abstraction for granted; they cannot begin to defend themselves from criticism
which dismisses abstraction out of hand. Artists must be met halfway.
Mark Wallinger was one of the short-listed artists. He is a neo-Dadaist, and
that is a pretty arid area, but he gives it a laddish twist. It is interesting
that he moves over into sport, though mostly into racing, to make points about
breeding - human as well as animal.
Sport, it has seemed to me for some time, is doing what art has been unable to
do in all honesty for some time - since the Renaissance even. Sport is defining
the heroic possibilities of the human - the human body and the human spirit.
Such talk has long since sounded phoney in art, and the notion of genius has
often been used only to stop us looking for ourselves or to put up prices. But
sporting achievements and sporting genius still mean something.
The two artists short-listed whose work means most to me are Mona Hatoum and
Callum Innes. Hatoum's installations - and you have to be with them, inside
them - are very simple, very minimal, and yet are also political parables: they
sum things up, often unforgettably. Innes makes very beautiful paintings. You
have to stand in front of them, with your eyes open.
n-Alan Woods is a lecturer at Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art, Dundee.
</TEXT>
