<HEADLINE>Rangers in court threat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS have warned the SFA that if their players are treated severely at
today's disciplinary meeting in Glasgow, the club will consider taking the
association to court. Vice-chairman Donald Findlay, confirming that the three
Ibrox players involved in controversial incidents during the 1-1 game with
Aberdeen at Ibrox would appear at Park Gardens, said last night that the club
had asked the SFA on a number of occasions the same question but had not
received a clear answer.
``We have asked why it seems to be that, because a supervisor in the stand
disagrees with the referee on the pitch, a player can be taken before the
committee,'' said the Ibrox vice-chairman, who also is a QC, ``but as yet we
have had no clear answer.''
The players concerned are Paul Gascoigne, John Brown, and Alan McLaren who,
along with Aberdeen's Billy Dodds, have been summoned to the committee hearing
as a consequence of a report by referee supervisor Don McVicar.
Although the incidents, none of which resulted in a sending-off by the referee,
John Rowbotham, were captured by TV cameras, that evidence is not allowed in
Scottish disciplinary meetings. That is expected to be changed when a motion to
permit its use as evidence will be put before the SFA Council in January.
Rangers' objection to the summons of their players is based on their belief
that the supervisor's report is not a valid base for disciplining players.
``They have not pointed to a rule which allows this to happen,'' said Findlay.
``We have been referred to various articles and general principles of the SFA,
but as a mere lawyer I can't work them out.''
The Ibrox trio will be represented by Players' Union secretary Tony Higgins,
who will speak on their behalf. However, it seems certain that the committee
will take action, irrespective of the club's position. The association believes
that, under its constitution, it is free to discipline players for misbehaviour
as it sees fit.
``If it becomes obvious that the SFA are looking at material that we have not
had notice of, for example press reports or television pictures,'' added
Findlay, ``that is not a fair way to go about business.
``It means that the way the committee works is not in accordance with the basic
principles of justice. If they do that we are not prepared to see our players
prejudiced by that kind of treatment, and we would certainly be looking to take
matters to law. And we have made our position plain to the SFA.''
The procurator fiscal is already considering taking action against one or more
of the players involved in the controversial incidents only a few weeks after
former Rangers player, Duncan Ferguson, was released from prison following a
sentence brought about when he was taken to court for assault by the fiscal.
The stance the club is taking makes it appear that a collision with the SFA is
inevitable.
Also appearing this afternoon in front of the SFA committee will be Alan
Lawrence, of Hearts, Sean Sweeney, of Airdrie, and Dumbarton's Ian McFarlane,
who are all expected to receive suspensions.
q INTER-Milan's Paul Ince has been banned for one match following his fourth
yellow card of the season.
The former Manchester United player, who has not been seen at his best since
his #7m summer transfer, picked up his fourth caution in the game against
Fiorentina at weekend.
</TEXT>
