<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Morrison was not to blame</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975126601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOXING:
KATHERINE Morrison, Scotland's only woman promoter, has been cleared by the
British Boxing Board of Control of any negligence for the ringside riot which
took place at the end of last month's ill-fated British bantamweight title
contest in Glasgow between Condorrat's Drew Docherty and James Murray, of
Newmains.
An inquiry by the board in London also found that no fault lay with co-promoter
Frank Warren, of London, nor the venue, the Hospitality Inn.
Murray, the challenger, was knocked out in the twelfth and final round of a
close contest. As he received medical assistance on the canvas, a section of
the crowd, believed to be latecomers who paid only for the boxing and not the
meal at the wine and dine show, caused a serious disturbance, with bottles,
chairs, and other objects thrown.
Murray died in hospital two days later, but yesterday's inquiry dealt only with
the trouble among the crowd.
The outcome of the meeting was that the boxing chiefs have banned ``mixed''
promotions. Only those clients who attend the actual dinner at such an event
will be allowed to view the boxing.
Katherine Morrison attended yesterday's inquiry with her father Alex. Board
secretary John Morris said: ``They were most helpful.'' Katherine will now go
ahead with a planned show at Glasgow's Moat House Hotel next month. She
recently announced that she would continue in boxing, and, prior to the board's
findings, vowed never to stage another ``mixed'' show, despite having
successfully staged them for five years.
The board stewards stressed promoters must liaise closely with security firms
and police, even if promotions have taken place successfully at the same venue
over a period of time.
They insisted that it is ``essential'' police be present whenever it is
considered necessary, confirming the board regulation that promoters should
always consult their local police force when a tournament is taking place.
Promoters will be told to keep a special watch on security in cases where a
boxer has a following which could produce problems.
Morris said: ``We had a long look into the many aspects of mixed boxing
evenings, which could be difficult to control.''
The board stewards concluded that the section of the audience who had purchased
tickets for boxing only had caused the disturbance, adding that the problem
appeared to have been exacerbated by alcohol.
q LENNOX Lewis's handlers are prepared to guarantee Riddick Bowe, the World
Boxing Organisation heavyweight champion, #6m for a showdown in March or April.
Lewis's promoter, Panos Eliades, will make the offer to Bowe's manager today.
q THE Mike Tyson-Buster Mathis Jr fight, scheduled to go ahead in Atlantic City
on Wednesday, has been moved to Philadelphia on December 16.
The New Jersey authorities ruled that staging the bout in their state would
violate a ban on casinos doing business with Don King, Tyson's promoter, who
has had his license suspended after he had been charged with fraud. The fight
will now take place in the Spectrum arena in Philadelphia.
q JOHNNY Armour retained the European bantamweight title last night when in the
York Hall, Bethnal Green, he stopped Frenchman Redha Abbas with two seconds
remaining of the fifth round.
</TEXT>
