<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Judge is
arrested
A JUDGE was arrested last night by the Metropolitan Police, in connection with
allegations of mortgage fraud between 1980 and 1989.
Judge Richard Gee, 53, a Crown Court judge who sits in London, was bailed to
return to Belgravia police station in January, pending further inquiries.
Woman robbed
TWO men, pretending to be water-board employees, stole a three-figure sum of
money on Tuesday from a 75-year-old woman who lives in Marmion Road,
Cumbernauld. Police said the incident was similar to one on Tuesday in
Shawlands, Glasgow.
Hotel man's post
THE Forte group has appointed Mr Jacques Ligne, 47, as general manager of
Edinburgh's Balmoral Hotel. Mr Ligne previously held a similar position at the
Meridien Hotel, Bangkok.
Hospital rise
EDINBURGH Royal Infirmary NHS Trust said yesterday it had agreed a 3% increase
for most of its clinical staff. The money will be backdated to April.
Centre plan axed
STRATHCLYDE councillors have rejected a plan for a mixed retail, leisure, and
industrial development at Newhouse. A report said the development might
indicate a #25m investment and the possible creation of 1000 jobs but this had
to be balanced against likely loss of employment and investment in surrounding
shopping centres.
Man found dead
A MAN was arrested in Edinburgh yesterday after the body of Mr John Clough, 33,
was found in a flat in Peffermill Road in the city. Police said the man would
appear in court today.
Green light
EUROPEAN Commission officials have decided that mushy peas can stay green after
all. They have dropped plans to ban the dye used to give frozen peas their
colour.
Job in store
THE head of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch is leaving the force to head
security at Sainsburys, the supermarket chain. Commander David Tucker, 53, will
retire as head of the anti-terrorist branch in January after three years in the
job.
Aids concern
MORE than 250 children contacted ChildLine over worries about Aids, a report
reveals today. Youngsters as young as nine rang the free helpline seeking
advice and help during 1994/5.
Fare deal
A HOLIDAY firm is offering reserved seats on flights to Canada next year for a
deposit of 99p. Bluebird Express is making the concession for bookings made
before December 31. Fares start at #199 for services to three Canadian cities
from Birmingham, Stansted, Gatwick, Manchester, and Glasgow.
Start date
WORK is to start on the #3.8m Roy Castle International Centre for lung cancer
research in Liverpool on January 10. Castle, who died aged 62 in September last
year, devoted his last few months to fundraising for the centre.
Father's victory
PETER Malkin, who served a prison sentence for abducting his son, Oliver, from
his former wife, has won his battle for the right to look after the boy. After
a private hearing in the High Court in London yesterday, a judge announced that
Oliver, 14, would be returning to live with his father following his mother's
death from cancer last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Battle of wills goes on in rail strike</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
STRIKING French rail unions said tonight they had decided to extend the
crippling protest over government austerity plans into a seventh day.
In Paris, Metro and bus workers also decided to continue their own separate
strike tomorrow.
``Service disruptions should be identical to today's,'' Paris transport chiefs
warned.
Bus and rail services were at a near stand-still in Paris today and motorists
faced massive traffic jams on all main roads into the capital.
Rail travel was virtually impossible across France as the strike continued to
grip in a protest against government plans to trim retirement packages and
encourage greater productivity on the state-owned railway.
The three main rail unions also said they would boycott tomorrow's planned
meeting with management.
Students, on strike at universities across the country amid claims that they
have inadequate resources and too few teachers, also planned more protests for
tomorrow.
Despite the continuing disruption French leaders today vowed to push ahead with
their austerity plans.
``The reforms will take place and the government must stick by the agreed
schedule,'' President Jacques Chirac told a Cabinet meeting.
Underlining the government's determination to cut the huge deficit in the
welfare budget, the Cabinet approved a draft Bill allowing Prime Minister Alain
Juppe to order changes by decree, pending later parliamentary ratification.
``The hour of true reforms has come for France. Putting them off, as we have
for 15 years, would mean accepting a decline,'' Juppe said as he launched a
committee to review retirement schemes.
Fears of changes in a pension scheme which allows retirement as early as 50 are
at the centre of the railway workers' strike.
Workers at the state utility giant Electricite de France-Gaz de France also
called for a strike today, raising the possibility of power cuts.
Manufacturing firms began scrambling for alternative transport, such as barges
and lorries, to keep plants open.
A Peugeot plant in Mulhouse announced that at least half its 11,860 employees
would be sent home on Friday because there was no more room to store the cars
being produced there and no way to ship them.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plan to hunt boar comes under fire</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILD boar could soon be roaming free in a Scottish wood, but only for the
hunter's gun.
The animals, which once shared the Caledonian Forest with wolves, lynx, and
beaver, became extinct in this country three centuries ago.
Now a Perthshire businessman intends to reintroduce them in a commercially run
boar forest, which he hopes will attract hunters from all over the world.
Animal rights campaigners are horrified at the scheme, describing it as
barbaric.
The project is the dream of Mr David Hendry, a former undertaker, who owns
Hendry, Ramsay &amp; Wilcox, one of Scotland's biggest hunting, shooting, and
fishing agents.
Next spring, he plans to spend a six-figure sum on 1000 acres of woodland at a
secret Perthshire location, then fence it off, fill it with 30 wild pigs and
hunt the boars for sport.
Mr Hendry sees no problem in reintroducing wild pigs to what was once their
native country and anticipates a great demand for boar hunting.
His wealthy clients are expected to pay thousands of pounds for every animal
they kill. They will sit with high-powered rifles in hides high in the trees
above tracks or feeding places and wait for a boar to wander by. The more
impatient hunters will be able to arrange for beaters to drive the beasts past
their perch.
Boar hunting is very popular in Germany and Poland, where the animal is still
common in places.
Mr Hendry said: ``They will find food where no other animal can so, once we
have bought the wood and fenced it in, they will be relatively inexpensive to
keep.
``The only time they are aggressive is if they are hurt. Then they can be very
fierce.''
Yesterday, Mr John Robins, of Glasgow charity Animal Concern, predicted
widespread opposition to the idea from local farmers and animal rights
activists.
He said: ``We totally oppose this ridiculous scheme. We agree, in principle,
with the reintroduction of some species to Scotland but we will not tolerate
this sort of exploitation.
``To let these animals free in the wild just so that some rich playboy from
abroad can get a kick out of shooting them is a perversion which should never
be accepted in any civilised society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Footballers caught in mid-air</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIGEL JONES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DUTCH KLM plane carrying some of the world's top footballers was forced to
circle over the Siberian border today when it was denied entry to Russian
airspace.
In a bizarre ending to Ajax Amsterdam's win of the World Club title, the
players and 200 Dutch supporters had to return to Tokyo before they were
permitted to resume their flight home to Amsterdam.
KLM officials said the problem was caused by a mix-up over flight numbers which
meant the Russian authorities were not expecting the plane.
The confusion brought the Ajax players back to earth after winning the title
last night in Tokyo, and it also spoiled a huge homecoming party prepared by
fans in Amsterdam.
To add insult to injury, while the winners were marooned on the ground at Tokyo
airport, the team they beat in a penalty shoot-out, Gremio of Brazil, flew home
over them without incident.
``It was all a misunderstanding,'' said a KLM spokesman. However, by the time
it was sorted out, the plane had used up too much fuel circling over the
Russian border to go on and had to return to Tokyo for refuelling.-Reuter.
Tokyo
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth confirms 6% water ceiling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday confirmed The Herald's exclusive
story earlier this week that water-charge increases levied by the three new
public authorities will not be allowed to rise by more than 6% on average next
year.
In a parliamentary written answer, Mr Forsyth said the rate of return the
authorities should earn on the net value of their assets should be 6!s%
annually.
He added that the financial arrangements meant that the average charges need
increase by no more than 6%.
``I invite the authorities to be guided accordingly in finalising their charges
schemes,'' he said.
He also gave details of the relief scheme to help householders with domestic
sewerage charges during the changeover from council control. The authorities
are due to present their schemes to the Scottish Water and Sewerage Customers
Council next month. If they cannot reach agreement, the matter goes to the
Scottish Secretary to be resolved.
Customers Council chairman Dick Douglas said yesterday that without wishing to
prejudge the issue, it seemed unlikely that Scottish customers on average would
face charges much above the rate of inflation.
The restrictions on charges are expected to cause problems for the three
authorities. The chairman of the West of Scotland Water Authority, Mr John
Jameson, has already said it would be ``very difficult'' to make cutbacks when
necessary spending increases had been calculated at 10% to 15%.
Making large reductions in the capital spending programme, he warned could
place the authority in breach of new Government and European Union regulations
to raise standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Watson chips in a winner</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEVE Watson proved that history can repeat itself with the stunning goal that
ripped the Coca-Cola Cup out of Liverpool's grasp last night and put Newcastle
through to the last eight for the first time in 20 years.
The England under-21 internationalist had scored the last-minute winner to
steal the points when the sides met at St James' Park at the start of the month
and last night he came off the bench for head injury victim Les Ferdinand to
chip home in magnificent style 13 minutes from time.
There seemed little on when Watson received Peter Beardsley's pass 30 yards out
with three Liverpool defenders in front of him. He took an age to ponder his
options as Mark Wright stood off, turning outside and then in before looking up
and spotting David James had strayed off his line.
But from then on it was sheer class, Watson's left-footer arching beyond the
despairing keeper to send the travelling Toon Army into ecstasy and Anfield
into despair.
Tomas Brolin made an impressive debut as Leeds reached the quarter-finals with
a 2-1 win over Blackburn at Elland Road.
The #4.5m Swedish internationalist, who made a brief substitute appearance in
Saturday's Premiership defeat at Newcastle, did enough before being replaced
after 78 minutes to help his new side into the last eight of this competition
for the first time in four years.
Brian Deane scored his third goal of the season and Tony Yeboah produced
another wonder strike to put Leeds firmly in control after just 29 minutes.
But a Gary Kelly own goal just six minutes into the second half condemned Leeds
to a nervous finale and it took a brilliant late save from goalkeeper John
Lukic to prevent Blackburn forcing a replay at Ewood Park.
