<HEADLINE>Craik moves ahead of field</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOMEN'S GOLF
SCOTLAND'S Tracey Craik made light work of the testing conditions when she
added a round of 72 to her opening 71 to lead the field after the second round
of the 72-hole American Express Tour qualifying school tournament at La Manga,
Spain, yesterday.
With a one-under-par aggregate of 143, Craik leads by one stroke from
Australian Anne-Marie Knight with Tracey Loveys, from Dorset, a stroke further
behind.
It is Craik's second appearance at the qualifying school after a disappointing
run since turning professional in 1989.
Her best year was 1990 when she finished seventh in the Haninge Open in Sweden.
Yesterday, the former Scottish girl champion played impressive golf. She holed
out from eight feet for a birdie at the third hole but missed the green at the
seventh to turn in 36.
Craik was twice in sand to lose a shot at the eleventh but struck a superb
No.6-iron to within a foot of the hole for a birdie at the short twelfth then a
wayward drive cost her the third bogey of the round at the fifteenth.
Once again, Craik bounced back with a birdie at the next hole only to miss a
putt of three feet for another birdie at the seventeenth on her way home in 36.
Leading second-round scores (British and Irish unless stated):
143 - T Craik 71, 72.
