<DOCNO>GH951130-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chancellor's dilemma</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke is forecasting that the economy will grow at 3% next
year, a little higher than the 2.75% he expects this year.
To validate this year's forecast it is necessary for the economy to start
picking up again in the current quarter from the slower growth of the spring
and summer quarters.
A 3.5% rise in consumer spending is to be the engine of next year's economic
growth. The City was sceptical about the strength of his forecasts. The cynics
are arguing that the only way they can be achieved is if Clarke cuts interest
rates aggressively.
The Chancellor defended his forecasts yesterday and denied that they were
dependent on rate cuts. The Governor of the Bank of England might adopt a
different perspective. If the economy is set to grow so strongly there is no
need to cut rates, Eddie George may well argue.
City eyebrows were also raised at the size of the Public Sector Borrowing
Requirement, especially the #22.5bn for the coming fiscal year. Most of the
deterioration in the public finances can be blamed on a #9000m shortfall in the
revenue projections, mainly from value added and corporation taxes. It is not
clear why this should be so if the economy is really set to grow at well above
its trend rate of 2.25% per annum.
James Capel's Adam Cole is suspicious that Clarke has been deliberately
cautious in his revenue forecasts so that he will be in a strong position to
deliver bigger tax cuts in next year's Budget, that is if the Government's
wafer-thin majority lasts that long.
The PSBR forecasts have made it difficult for the Chancellor to engineer a
pre-Christmas cut in interest rates. Sterling has reacted badly to the public
borrowing numbers. So maybe Clarke will have to stay his hand until the new
year. Weak data might be the trigger for lower rates.
Curiously the move by the Halifax Building Society to kick start the housing
market by cutting its mortgage rate by a quarter point could take some of the
heat off the Chancellor.
One suspicion in the foreign exchange markets is that Clarke is not averse to a
deterioration in the exchange rate which would boost activity and help validate
his growth forecasts.
All smiles
ARGYLL'S chief executive, Colin Smith, barely stopped smiling yesterday - and
with good reason. But that meant some deep anxiety elsewhere in the supermarket
sector as the industry increasingly sees dynamic movements that point to
substantial structural changes in market share.
Tesco is continuing to stretch its lead although Argyll's Safeway is now
demonstrably benefiting from the Safeway 2000 programme and Asda performing
much better than would ever seem likely even 18 months ago.
The losers have been J Sainsbury and Kwik Save in the quoted sector and also
the Co-op which has been a soft touch for the last three decades while
Somerfield is showing surprising resilience.
When the Safeway 2000 programme was first launched, there was some cynicism
that this was just a marketing ploy with more noise than substance. However,
there are already tangible results with the most apparent being the increase in
weekly sales per square foot of 7.6% to #13.84 and so well ahead of schedule of
arriving at #15 by 1997-98 even if Tesco and Sainbury have already left that
well behind them already.
The differing profiles of the stores is the major reason with Safeway having a
lower exposure to high-population areas such as the inner M25 orbit. But target
attainment points to an increase in annual profits of well over #50m.
The increase in like-for-like sales of 9.6%, of which 6.7% was volume, reflects
in part the success of the ABC loyalty card which now has a base load of 3.1
million customers. This is costing #7m in start-up costs which will be taken in
the current six months but it apparently requires an increase in sales of just
3% to cover its costs.
Significantly the losers in the volume battles, Sainsbury and Kwik Save, are at
best lacklustre in their enthusiasm for these marketing tools.
There is now the prospect that at long last after five years of flat earnings
in real terms, Argyll will begin to show some performance. An increase in
full-year profits from #375m to about #430m would leave the shares at 319p -
the same as they were six months ago and trading at 12.2 times likely earnings.
The 10% underperformance against the FTSE should now begin to be made up with
sentiment encouraged by a likely 5.1% yield.
Profits flow
GIVEN the public relations fiasco that was Yorkshire Water's handling of this
summer's drought one could have been forgiven for thinking that the financial
performance of the group would have been impaired. But no, taxable profits on
an FRS3 reporting basis actually rose by an impressive 48% to #99.5m.
It is perhaps not surprising that in the current highly-charged political
environment, the company prefers to concentrate on adjusted profit growth of a
lesser 10%.
Yorkshire believes that the profits are good news for customers because a large
chunk of cash is being used for improvement schemes to prevent drought next
summer. There is certainly no shortage of projects to spend the money on, for
instance plugging the pipes which leak a quarter of Yorkshire's water. However,
it is likely to be several years before leaks in the entire network are tackled.
While it is true that the spell of hot weather in the summer was unusually
prolonged it is just not good enough to blame the weather. It provokes the same
level of annoyance as British Rail's excuse of leaves on the line for the late
running of trains.
Yorkshire Water customers pay for a service not for excuses from the board as
to why they have failed to deliver. Its customers still face the possibility of
cuts to their water service on a rota basis from January next year.
It will be interesting to see whether a similar situation occurs if we have a
hot summer next year. In the meantime at least Yorkshire Water shareholders
have something to smile about, the 10% increase in the interim dividend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
