<DOCNO>GH951130-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dixon now ready to put Dundee on the market Finalists are given a #2.2m price tag</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE, the club who lost in the Coca-Cola Cup final against Aberdeen at
Hampden on Sunday, is up for sale with a price tag of #2.2m.
It is understood that millionaire chairman Ron Dixon, who bought the club
almost five years ago, is ready to walk away from his football investment after
having spent #600,000 to buy the club and adding another #1.5m of a personal
loan to wipe out the debts.
The mysterious Dixon was at Hampden for the final after having arrived back on
Tayside just 48 hours before the game following a near year-long absence. Since
his reappearance, the business community in Dundee has been alerted that he is
ready to sell. I believe that the Vancouver-based Dixon would prefer a deal
which would allow him to retain Dens Park and lease out the ground to whoever
buys the club.
That may be a stumbling block but the news that Dixon is ready to talk business
placed the future of the club in the melting pot once more.
Dixon bought Dundee from Angus Cook after he had become involved initially in
the city when he took over the Dundee Tigers ice hockey team as well as Dundee
ice rink.
The rink was later sold for a supermarket development at a #1.9m price and the
hockey club closed down.
The hopes were that an ice rink could be built at Dens Park and a multi-purpose
sports centre could have been operational. So far, however, all that has
happened is that dog racing has been introduced at Dens and the ice rink plans
have been shelved.
Last night one Dundee businessman said: ``The word is out that the club is
going on the market and the price of #2.2m is being talked about. This is not
the first time we have heard that the chairman would be ready to sell but this
time, with the price tag in place, it seems that he has made up his mind.''
Dixon has always maintained that he would review his own position as owner of
the club after five years in charge. That time limit has almost been reached
and it will be clear to the Canadian that money is not made running a football
club in Scotland.
He has been able to put the club on a reasonably strong financial foundation by
handing the local board members his personal interest-free loan of #1.5m. And,
the team's successful run to the Coca-Cola final has brought in more than
half-a-million pounds to ease the cash-flow problems which afflict Dundee and
so many other clubs around the country.
The Dundee manager, Jim Duffy, has been widely praised by his chairman and
there is little doubt that as well as the Hampden adventure - even though they
did suffer defeat there - the Dens Park side have a group of young players who
will be worth a lot of money in the transfer market, and who look good enough
to carry the team back into the premier division.
In that sense buying the club would look to be a good investment, although any
potential buyer will want to see the stadium as a part of the deal.
Already, of course, Dixon has floated the kite of ``amalgamation'' with local
rivals Dundee United. He did so in a Radio Scotland interview at the weekend,
maintaining, as he has done before, that there is no room in the city - far
less the same street - for the two senior teams to exist side by side.
That is not a view shared by the support of either team, but it gives a guide
as to how Dixon's mind may be working.
Whatever, there is little doubt now that Dixon would like to sell, recoup his
investment, and give himself more time to attend to his other business
interests scattered around the world from Canada to South America to the Far
East.
The problem he faces is trying to convince a buyer that the club, without the
stadium, is worth #2.2m.
</TEXT>
