<DOCNO>GH951130-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal threat to doctors in `right to die' case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTORS responsible for the care of a 52-year-old woman at the centre of
Scotland's first ``right to die'' case risk prosecution for murder or culpable
homicide if they withdraw her life-sustaining treatment.
That possibility emerged yesterday as Law Hospital NHS Trust went to court to
ask that Mrs Janet Johnstone, who has been in a coma since January 1992, should
be allowed to die peacefully, with dignity, and the least possible distress.
The Carluke hospital has decided to seek the guidance of the Court of Session
because the Lord Advocate, Mr Donald Mackay QC, has declined to give an
undertaking that he would not prosecute medical staff if her treatment was
stopped.
The action by the hospital is supported by Mrs Johnstone's family but is being
challenged as incompetent by the Lord Advocate.
It is also being opposed by the guardian appointed by the court to look after
Mrs Johnstone's interests, who says that her condition is stable, that she is
not suffering pain, and that he cannot consent to the proposals to end her life.
Lord Cameron is being asked at the Court of Session to declare that despite Mrs
Johnstone's inability to give valid consent, doctors can lawfully discontinue
all life-sustaining and medical treatment, including artificial feeding,
designed to keep her alive.
The judge was told yesterday that Mrs Johnstone, formerly of Houldsworth
Crescent, Allanton, Lanarkshire, was admitted to Law Hospital in January 1992
after taking a drugs overdose.
She suffered convulsions which caused brain damage and failed to regain
consciousness. She is being fed through a nasal tube and her condition has
remained unchanged, consistent with a persistent vegetative state, although she
does not need help with her breathing.
Five doctors, including Dr Iain O'Brien, the consultant in charge of her case,
agree that there is no realistic hope of recovery or improvement, that
medication should be withdrawn, and she should receive treatment only for the
purpose of allowing her to die peacefully and with dignity.
That position is accepted by Mrs Johnstone's husband, Peter, her daughter,
Linda, and her two brothers.
Law Hospital says the Lord Advocate has not made public any policy he might
have about criminal proceedings against a doctor who withdraws life sustaining
treatment from a patient in a persistent vegatative state with no realistic
hope of recovery or improvement.
In the absence of a public policy statement, the hospital feels that a doctor
faced with a medical dilemma of this kind has no guidance about the risk of
public prosecution.
It says that despite being appraised of the issues raised by Mrs Johnstone's
case, the Lord Advocate has not given any undertaking to refrain from criminal
prosecution if life-sustaining treatment is withheld.
That is why it has felt it had to ask for the guidance of the Court of Session.
The hospital makes it clear that it has continued to provide Mrs Johnstone with
care and treatment for three and a half years, not for medical reasons, but
because of the uncertainty about the legal position.
In his answers to Law Hospital's case, the Lord Advocate accepts that he has
made no public statement relating to criminal proceedings in a case of this
kind.
He argues that the case involves consideration of the criminal law relating to
murder and culpable homicide and the Court of Session, a civil court, has no
jurisdiction to pronounce an order on the discontinuation of treatment.
The curator appointed by the court to look after Mrs Johnstone's interests
points out that when Mrs Johnstone was admitted to hospital in January 1992 she
was conscious and lucid. She was aware that attempts were being made to save
her life and co-operated with them.
He stresses that her condition is stable, that she is well looked after and not
suffering pain, and in these circumstances he does not consider the proposals
to end her life to be in her best interests.
He also takes the view that he cannot consent to anything which would
constitute a potentially wrongful act and might have criminal consequences.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tessa's secret Olympic dream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TESSA Sanderson yesterday surprised the athletics world by announcing her
intention to make a comeback - but the former Olympic javelin champion's
aspiration of representing Britain at a sixth Olympic Games is not an overnight
decision.
Sanderson, who retired in 1993, had decided as long ago as April 11, when she
requested her name be restored to the list of competitors available for
anti-doping measures. British Athletics Federation information officer Bill
Adcocks confirmed last night that she has been tested since.
``The rules are there to stop people taking a year out of the sport, off the
anti-doping list, and souping themselves up before coming back,'' he said.
Athletes must be on the register for 12 months prior to competing
internationally.
Sanderson, who will be 40 by the time of the Olympics, threw 55 metres without
training during the summer and, though well short of her best of 73.58m set a
year before she won gold in the Los Angeles Olympics, she believes she can win
again.
The spur is the possibility of raising #1m for the charity, Children in
Hospital. Having been approached by Sir Anthony Tippet, the charity's chairman,
she said: ``I will need the support of children around the country to reach our
target of #1m and bring back a gold medal for Britain.''
Thrice Commonwealth champion, and 10-times UK record-breaker, Sanderson has
already represented Britain in five Olympics, a UK record.
There is no prospect of a restoration of hostilities with arch-rival Fatima
Whitbread, who last year announced her intention to return but never went on
the doping register.
Former Sky TV presenter Sanderson lived with TV personality Mr Motivator for
five years, but they have split up. She will also miss the aid of her former
coaches. Wilf Paish, who helped her to Olympic gold, is now working in South
Africa and her other mentor is serving a jail sentence for embezzlement.
</TEXT>
