<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Terrorist trial is told of dum-dum bullets</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 23-year-old loyalist told a detective how peace talks negotiator Lindsay Robb
handed him two dum-dum bullets, a court heard yesterday.
Mr Alexander Davidson, whose father is a councillor from Broxburn, West
Lothian, claimed that Mr Robb then asked him to take the bullets back with him
to Northern Ireland.
The evidence came on the sixth day of the trial at the High Court in Glasgow of
Mr Robb and Mr Davidson.
They are in the dock with four other men, Mr John ``Jock'' Johnston, 49, from
Laurieston, Falkirk; Mr Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool; Mr William ``Spud''
McArthur, 41, of Bonnybridge; and Mr David White, 29, of Airdrie.
They deny conspiring to acquire guns and ammunition for the Ulster Volunteer
Force intending to endanger life in the UK and the Republic of Ireland.
Mr Robb, 28, who is from Lurgan, was also alleged to have been the organiser of
a consignment of two guns and ammunition from a Liverpool pub to Scotland.
It was also claimed that while he was a member of the Progressive Unionist
Party taking part in peace talks with Government Minister Michael Ancram at
Stormont earlier this year Mr Robb was also a member of the outlawed UVF.
The allegations about Mr Robb were made in statements alleged to have been
given to detectives by four of his co-accused while they were being detained in
a Glasgow police station under the Prevention of Terrorism Act.
The court has heard that Mr Johnston, Mr McArthur, and Mr White were arrested
by armed detectives after they had been shadowed in a car from the Market
public house in Liverpool to Airdrie last July.
In the back, it was alleged, were a machine pistol and a semi-automatic pistol.
In his alleged statement, read out in court by Detective Inspector Ian Watkins
of Strathclyde Police, Mr Davidson described getting the bullets from Mr Robb
in the Tam Bain pub in Laurieston.
His statement also revealed that Mr Johnston, who was present, talked about
getting two Uzi sub-machineguns for #1800 from Liverpool and having met a
gangster there during his previous visit.
Mr Davidson also claimed that Mr Johnston knew a man who would store them under
his floorboards and Mr Robb said they would go to Northern Ireland but he
didn't know how they would get there.
In his alleged statement, read out by Detective Inspector Douglas Brown
yesterday, Mr Hives, the manager of the Market pub, admitted he took a parcel
containing the guns from another Liverpool man who asked him to pass it to
``Jock''.
The guns were kept overnight in the cellar hidden between two kegs before being
taken taken back to Scotland.
Mr Hives told how Mr Johnston, Mr McArthur, and another man came down to the
cellar to view the weapons.
Earlier, the jury heard detectives reveal the contents of statements given by
Mr Johnston and Mr White.
Mr Johnston said he was a member of the UVF and claimed that Mr Robb asked him
if he could get guns.
Mr White's statement also named Mr Robb. In it, he claimed that as they drove
from Airdrie to Laurieston, Mr Robb told him he was going to ``organise a few
guns for purchase''.
The trial, before Lord Sutherland, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In search of more Dutch masters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALEX McLeish has returned to Holland to try and strengthen his injury-hit
squad. The Fir Park manager side's challenge has been undermined by the loss of
more than half the team in recent weeks.
McLeish, who was forced to pull on his boots two weeks ago against Kilmarnock,
said: ``The situation is so bad I cannot afford to wait for it to improve. For
instance, I had to play six juveniles in a reserve game because of the injury
crisis.
``We urgently need new players - particularly a striker - and I have had two
highly recommended to me in Holland. I assessed them both and they have the
quality needed.
``But negotiations are at a very early stage. I do not visualise any
developments before the weekend.''
q.PLANS by Scottish League newcomers Caledonian Thistle to build a 5000-seater
stadium have received a #480,000 boost.
Inverness and Nairn Enterprise yesterday announced the grant, which will go
towards an access road to the new park in the town's East Longman industrial
estate.
The club was formed following a merger between town rivals Caledonian and
Thistle, and a small section of fans are still against the union. But the
team's future hinges upon fulfilling a promise to the Scottish League that they
will be in a new ground by August.
The enterprise company is ready to augment the sum with a further #175,000 to
unlock a much more ambitious #6m development of the entire area, which could
create hundreds of new jobs by providing badly needed new space for businesses.
INE's funding package is conditional on the club securing a #900,000 grant from
Inverness District Council, which will help finance the #4.5m complex.
INE are also seeking incorporation of Inverness into the club's name. The
club's fans have voted in favour of that.
q.DUNDEE'S Morten Wieghorst could be on the way out of Dens Park, but not
necessarily in a move back to Denmark.
The Dane, who signed his latest monthly contract with the Tayside club so that
he would be eligible for last Sunday's Coca-Cola Cup final, has been linked
with a transfer to Brondby.
But there could be moves from several English clubs, including Southampton,
Bolton, Manchester City, and Nottingham Forest, who have watched the midfield
player this season.
Manager Jim Duffy said: ``I have had a couple of inquiries - one from abroad
and another from England - but it has gone no further.''
Meanwhile, Dundee striker Jim Hamilton's booking in the 2-0 defeat by Aberdeen
on Sunday has earned him a one-game SFA ban and he will miss the Tayside derby
against St Johnstone at Dens on December 16.
q. HEARTS goalkeeper Gary O'Connor was last night in signing talks with English
third-division club Doncaster Rovers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britain pulls out of Euro film fund</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN has unexpectedly pulled out of a Council of Europe programme providing
financial support for European film-making.
``During the more than 40 years that I have worked at the council, I cannot
recall a move of this type,'' said the fund's Italian president, Gaetano
Adinolfi.
``Those who will suffer the most from this will be the British producers who
will have a much harder time making co-productions with their European
partners. I love the British cinema and I am sorry they did this,'' Adinolfi
added.
Twenty-three European nations in addition to Britain have been participating in
the programme, Eurimages, which was set up in 1988. Britain joined in 1993.
The fund has paid out #106m to support the production of 422 full-length films
and documentaries. Britain has so far this year contributed about #2.6m.
A total of 56 British films have received subsidies, according to Barrie
Ellie-Jones, Eurimages executive secretary. Recent films supported by the fund
have included British film-maker Ken Loach's acclaimed Land and Freedom.-Reuter.
Strasbourg
</TEXT>
