<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Precision farming on horizon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY GREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPACE-AGE technology is on its way to help farmers combat weeds - by selecting
individual types and the herbicides needed to eliminate them, writes ROY GREGOR.
But until the new technology is cost effective, cereal growers are advised to
continue with conventional control methods and to watch out for cereal
varieties that become less resistant to diseases.
According to Dr Ken Davies, weed specialist at the Scottish Agricultural
College, precision farming is on the horizon. Farm and field plans relayed by
satellite through computers could already assist in management plans for the
application of fertilisers where they were needed, and related systems would
identify weed black spots that needed treatment and which herbicide or
combination would be required, he said.
``Machines are being developed that will distinguish between a crop and weeds
and even different weeds and will combat the problems,'' he said.
But he pointed out that, at present, the information needed for such
high-technology management required farm staff to cover the ground and identify
the trouble areas and the weeds involved. The day would come when machines
might do that - but not yet.
He also warned Scottish cereal growers that there had been isolated areas in
England where the pernicious wild oat weed had become herbicide resistant. ``I
am not panicking but if you have wild oats that you cannot control let us
know,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
