<HEADLINE>Consumers will decide on BST, says Minister Hormone issue one of public confidence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE use of hormones to improve milk yields or provide heavier carcases would in
the final analysis depend on the views of the consumer, Scottish Office
Agriculture Minister the Earl of Lindsay indicated yesterday.
During a visit to the Dairy Scot event at Ingliston, near Edinburgh, Lord
Lindsay said: ``If the use of Bovine Somato Trophin is allowed we must make
sure that consumers out there do not fear for their health.
``The whole industry suffers if we undermine people's confidence in
agricultural produce.''
The milk-boosting hormone BST, which has been licensed in Canada and America,
is not authorised for use in the European Union although the position is likely
to be reviewed next year.
America is considering using the most recent Gatt agreement to challenge the
European ban on imports of food products which include hormone boosters. The
Americans were of the view that the doubts expressed in Europe had no
scientific basis, said the Minister.
``Whatever the scientists say, and whatever the World Trade Organisation rules
and regulations say the reality none of us can avoid is what the consumer feels
is safe - or isn't safe.''
The use of naturally occurring hormones in beef was a challenge facing both
government and the industry, he said. Britain had opposed the European ban
because there was no scientific basis for it but there was a public perception
that hormones were not wanted.
If America won its case, the response of the industry might be to advertise the
fact that North American beef contained hormones but Scotch beef didn't.
Cautioning against such a policy the Minister said that a short-term gain could
be offset by a longer-term danger of casting doubt in the customer's mind about
beef in general. The shopper might decide to buy chicken or fish instead.
At the beginning of the week, however, Sir David Naish, president of the
National Farmers' Union of England and Wales, called for clear labelling of
food from hormone-induced sources so that the consumer had the opportunity to
make a choice.
Alex Brown, chairman of Dairy Scot's management committee and a prominent dairy
farmer, said there was no need to use hormones to boost yields. The dairy
industry had for years promoted milk as a fresh product and should not throw
that away. He was confident of what the consumer would prefer, given the choice.
Earlier Lord Lindsay announced plans for drawing up a code of practice for
specialist cheesemakers in Scotland.
The new code will include guidance on good hygiene practices for smaller
cheesemakers and sensible enforcement practices for local authority
environmental health officers.
The Minister said that the decision to draw up a code should not be regarded as
necessarily related to the case of Humphrey Errington, maker of Lanark Blue
cheese, who has been fighting against local authority attempts to condemn a
batch of cheese from his plant.
The cheesemakers' association had made a case for a more commonsense approach
to the enforcement of hygiene regulations, he said. ``But we know that food,
health and human safety cannot be seriously compromised.''
Some of the cheesemakers were using methods which were hundreds of years old
and there was a remarkably low incidence of human health problems. Some of the
regulations imposed might have been unnecessarily zealous and inappropriate
given the time-span over which these cheeses had been safely eaten.
</TEXT>
