<HEADLINE>Hospital delay for jail suicide victim Inquiry told how NHS reforms held up bed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NHS reforms delayed efforts to find a psychiatric bed for a troubled teenager
who hanged herself in Cornton Vale prison near Stirling, an inquiry heard
yesterday.
Prison medical officer Dr Alexander Stuart said a psychiatrist at the jail had
tried to get Miss Arlene Elliot, 17, admitted to Gartnavel Royal Hospital,
Glasgow, after she began hearing voices.
A consultant from Gartnavel travelled to the prison to assess Miss Elliot but
was turned away at the gates because he arrived at 5pm and the jail was closed
to visitors.
Dr Stuart said it was difficut to say what the consultant's judgment would have
been if he had been allowed to see her.
The inquiry heard that there was then a delay finding a bed.
Asked by Scottish Prison Service solicitor, Ms Lynda Towers, whether medical
staff could not have chosen any hospital in Scotland to send her to, Dr Stuart
said he understood their choice was now limited.
He said that, under prison rules, the Secretary of State had to approve the
transfer of mentally ill patients from jail to hospital. His understanding was
that, under the new NHS system, the fact that the majority of inmates at
Cornton Vale came from Glasgow limited prison doctors' choice of hospital.
He said: ``The way the system is operating at the moment restricts us to
Glasgow.''
He said the girl's mental state improved while she was waiting for a bed and
the attempt to have her transferred was cancelled after nine days. She hanged
herself a few weeks later.
Dr Stuart also called for a reform of the way suicide-risk inmates were treated
in jail, with a greater emphasis on therapy.
The hearing is a joint inquiry. Earlier, a prison nurse who failed to spot that
the other hanging victim, Miss Kelly Holland, 17, was a suicide risk despite
interviewing her just hours before she killed herself admitted he had been too
busy to check vital medical records.
Mr William Rock, 46, said he interviewed both girls on their admission to
decide what level of surveillance they should have been put on.
He placed neither on suicide watch but admitted that if he had had time to read
Miss Holland's medical notes he would have put her on strict supervision in a
bare cell with a sleeping bag instead of sheets and blankets.
Miss Holland, of Hamilton, hanged herself with a sheet only hours after Mr Rock
marked her card ``no suicide risk at present''.
Mr Rock, a prison nurse for 22 years, told the inquiry that the sheer pressure
of work when prisoners arrived at the jail every weekday evening made it
impossible to review their case histories. He had to rely on what the girls
themselves told him.
Procurator-fiscal John Miller, who is conducting the inquiry, asked him: ``Did
you have time to read the nurses' notes on Kelly? Did you have time to read the
medical officer's notes on Kelly? Did you have time to refer to anything in the
jail?'' To each question Mr Rock replied ``No''.
He admitted that if he had read the notes he would have discovered Miss Holland
had been placed in top suicide risk category ``SSS'' on three previous
jailings. He admitted that if he had known that, he would have placed her on
SSS again.
Mr Miller asked him: ``Does it come to this - that although the system may be
such that you can take the medical records with you to the screenings, you
don't have time to look at them?'' Mr Rock replied: ``It can come to that.
That's what it came to in Kelly's case.''
In Miss Elliot's case, despite the fact that her medical records revealed two
previous suicide bids, Mr Rock said he had not placed her on strict suicide
watch when she arrived at the jail on May 30.
She did not kill herself until nearly a month later, hanging herself with her
nightie four days after Miss Holland died.
Mr Rock said she had been placed on strict suicide watch because Miss Holland
had been her friend. The watch was taken off again on the orders of the jail
psychiatrist.
The inquiry, before Sheriff Principal John Maguire at Stirling Sheriff Court,
continues.
</TEXT>
