<HEADLINE>Kidnappers seek help for  `seriously ill' British hostage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar
GUERRILLAS have again sought medical help for four Western hostages in Kashmir,
including a Briton who may be seriously ill.
``The abductors have been trying to get medical aid in south Kashmir for the
last couple of days,'' said an Indian official.
Britons Keith Mangan and Paul Wells, American Donald Hutchings, and German Dirk
Hasert were captured by Al-Faran militants in July while on trekking holidays.
A fifth hostage, Norwegian Hans Christian Ostroe, was beheaded in August.
``We have reports that Hutchings and Wells are seriously ill, and Mangan and
Hasert are suffering from fever,'' said the official.
The Westerners are known to have suffered stomach and eye ailments, and
Hutchings is believed to have frostbitten feet. Al-Faran has sought medical aid
for the captives at least twice during the five-month-old ordeal.
Recently the militants and hostages have descended from high altitude towards
the Kashmir valley as snow has started to fall and temperatures have plunged,
officials said. Al-Faran, a shadowy outfit unknown before the kidnappings, has
demanded the release of 15 jailed separatists including three Pakistanis from
the Harkat-ul-Ansar militant group.
India has refused to bow to the militants' demands and ruled out a rescue raid
for fear of harming the hostages.
On Sunday Al-Faran reiterated its threat to kill all four tourists unless the
government bowed to its demands ``as soon as possible''.
But officials shrugged off the threat, saying it was probably a pressure
tactic.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
