<HEADLINE>Greek leader `stable'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Athens
GREEK Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou had another dialysis session today and
was still hooked up to a respirator but his condition was stable.
``In the six hours since the last medical bulletin, the Prime Minister had
another dialysis. His condition is stable and he is breathing through a
respirator,'' said a medical bulletin.
One of the doctors treating him said Papandreou, 76, who had open heart surgery
in 1988, was not suffering heart irregularities.
The Prime Minister was rushed to hospital with pneumonia nine days ago. He has
been breathing with the help of a respirator and a dialysis machine was
replacing his kidneys in filtering his blood.
Hundreds of supporters have gathered outside the Onassis Heart Centre while
dozens of socialist party officials have crowded hospital corridors for news of
his health.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
