<HEADLINE>No action over mercy killing claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROSECUTORS have decided against taking action over a father who claimed he
killed his brain-damaged baby to stop her suffering.
Mr Nigel Nelson, 42, of Bournemouth, Dorset, was arrested in August after
giving himself up at Poole police station. He was released on bail.
He had claimed in a newspaper article that he deliberately increased the dose
of diamorphine being given to his seven-week-old daughter, Naomi, as she lay
slowly dying at Poole General Hospital.
The Crown Prosecution Service said yesterday: ``Police have been advised there
was insufficient evidence for a realistic prospect of a conviction.''
Naomi, who was born by caesarean section in September, 1992, was blind,
probably deaf, could not move any part of her body voluntarily, and had a bowel
defect which meant she was unable to swallow.
Unemployed Mr Nelson, a former electricity meter reader, told the newspaper
that he increased the diamorphine dosage Naomi was receiving because he loved
her and could not bear to see her suffer.
``I helped her to rest in peace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
