<HEADLINE>ELECTRONICS US firm adds  third factory to  Scots network</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US electronics firm Jabil Circuit plans to build a #5m factory in Livingston
next year creating up to 120 new jobs, writes ROBERT POWELL.
Randon Haight, Jabil's vice-president for European business development,
revealed the move in an interview with the trade weekly Electronics Times.
Jabil came to Scotland in 1993, setting up two factories at Livingston and
Bathgate, now employing a total of 600 people making products for the
telecommunications, data transmission and automotive industries.
A rapid growth in sales has persuaded the company to set up a third 10,000
square foot plant in 1996. Two greenfield sites at Livingston have been
identified for the project and planning permission has already been granted at
one of them.
Some of the equipment presently installed at Jabil's existing Scottish plants
will be transferred to the new factory, which will offer increased automation.
Mr Haight said Jabil, which had total sales of $600m (#392m) last year, had
targeted the automotive sector as a fast growth market.
n.FACTORIES owned by foreign companies provided 83,000 jobs in Scotland last
year, more than a quarter of the country's total jobs in manufacturing.
The latest annual statistics on overseas ownership in manufacturing industry
published by the Scottish Office show that 56% of those jobs were provided by
companies based in the US.
There were 357 foreign-owned manufacturing plants in Scotland last year, but
the number of people they employed fell for the second year in a row from
85,000 in 1993 and 84,700 in 1992.
That downward trend looks likely to change, however, following the announcement
of several recent large investments by overseas electronics manufacturers.
The biggest of these was a #260m project to manufacture computer and television
screens in Lanarkshire, announced by the Taiwanese company Chunghwa earlier
this month. This is expected to create 3300 new jobs over the next four to five
years.
</TEXT>
