<HEADLINE>Offshore safety `improving'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Safety Case regulations introduced in the wake of the Piper Alpha disaster
are having a ``positive impact'' on the industry's approach to managing safety,
according to a report published yesterday by the Health and Safety Executive.
However, the report, based on five research studies, reveals thataround one
third of offshore safety representatives felt inadequately informed about
safety cases and ``an unexpectedly large minority lacked knowledge of certain
key areas of their rights in relation to safety cases''.
An HSE spokesman admitted this was a generic weakness which they were trying to
address. Last night, the OILC union, which is a constant campaigner for union
representation offshore, blamed lack of training.
The Offshore Installations (Safety Case) Regulations 1992 implement some of the
key recommendations made by Lord Cullen following his investigation into the
1988 Piper Alpha disaster which claimed 167 lives. They require operators or
owners to submit to the HSE a safety case for each installation. All 216 have
been submitted and approved before today's deadline.
The report said there was evidence of significant risk reduction but that it
was recognised the improvement was likely to be because of a combination of
factors. The report estimated that, by the end of this year, the industry would
have spent between #1200m and #1400m complying with the new regulations.
The report acknowledges industry concerns about the complexity of the Safety
Case preparation and assessment and the HSE is exploring with the industry what
can be done to minimise paperwork. It will also consider ways of encouraging
workforce participation.
Last night, Mr John McKinnell, Aberdeen director of the United Kingdom Offshore
Operators' Association, said the industry had made very significant attempts to
involve the workforce and, even before the Cullen Report and Piper Alpha, many
companies had set up safety representative systems.
``Through that experience, one has knowledge of the degree to which you can
involve people in safety discussions and some people are more interested and
more willing to be involved than others,'' he said.
OILC general secretary Ronnie MacDonald said: ``In 1992, in our Safety Case
submission, we said that, as things stood then, the offshore workforce would be
disenfranchised from full participation in the process because the training and
education provisions were wholly inadequate and remain so to this day.''
Oil record -- Page20
</TEXT>
