<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Celtic, Aberdeen make major strides this term What a difference a year makes to league positions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DECEMBER, according to Scottish football folklore, is when leagues are won and
lost, relegation is virtually settled, and all that is left is the minutiae of
prize-giving day.
That may be a touch exaggerated, but it is often the case that before the
chilly finale to the year is complete, positions have been secured or forsaken
which are confirmed at the end of the season.
For that reason it is interesting to note how the premier-division teams have
progressed or otherwise as they move into what might well be the decisive
period of the term as compared with their efforts at the same stage last year.
The interim report card makes fascinating reading and, in a general sense,
shows that the clubs are not only making great efforts to improve upon last
season, but succeeding.
The major strides have been made by Celtic and Aberdeen, who have left their
uncertain form of this time last year well behind and, in fact, are far higher
in the table now.
Celtic, after 15 games, were in an unsteady fifth place in the table in 1994,
having collected 20 points. Now, they are second after the same number of
matches, with an extra 12 points gathered.
A year ago, Celtic were 10 points behind the leaders, Rangers, and virtually
ruled out of the championship race.
This season they are in second place, four points adrift, but very much serious
contenders for the title they have not won since 1988.
The difference in the Parkhead side's fortunes to date, apart from the fact
that they have the assistance of new strikers Andreas Thom and Pierre van
Hooydonk and are obviously playing better, is that, for the time being at
least, they have left behind them the addiction to draws which hampered them
all through last season.
In their first 15 matches then, Celtic had drawn eight times, but this year are
in a little more imposing mood, having reduced that to five.
Aberdeen, whose transformation, or perhaps resurgence, was completed by their
success in the Coca-Cola Cup last Sunday, had been in miserable form at this
stage in 1994.
They had collected only 12 points from their opening 15 games and were
languishing in joint bottom place alongside Partick Thistle.
Oddly enough, both managed to survive, a rare event when in that position at
this stage.
The Dons, aided by the rejuvenation of Eoin Jess and the arrival of Paul
Bernard, have left that alarming time behind them now, having improved to the
20-point mark after only 14 games and fifth spot in the table which promises to
be a good deal better before the end of the competition.
Aberdeen, in fact, are second only to Celtic in the rate of their improvement a
year on but in third place are Rangers, who are six points better than they
were twelve months ago.
Considering that they were top of the table at that time, their progress, at
least on the domestic front, is not good news for their pursuers.
The champions have chalked   up an extra six points in their 15-game run, no
mean feat in a season when Champions' League involvement and injury setbacks
have conspired to make life more difficult.
The downside of the table is demonstrated harshly by Motherwell and Falkirk,
both of whom were going strong at this point last term but have found life hard
so far in the new season.
Motherwell were only two points behind Rangers at this stage last year, with 28
points from their 15 games, and were to go on to keep up that splendid form
almost to the finishing line.
They have been assailed by injury problems this term, with a whole host of
first-team men being ruled out at various stages, and their early hesitancy did
not help their cause.
The Fir Park team are 14 points worse off, with only 14 in their favour so far
and that ought to rule out any championship ambitions this year, but the
anticipated recovery, when the casualty list clears up, could see them in a
chase for a European place.
Falkirk at a late stage last season harboured precisely that ambition after
looking good bets to go down earlier.
Before that, however, they had made an impressive start, with 21 points from
their 15 matches, which compares starkly with the nine to date.
Falkirk, fourth in the table a year ago, now are bottom but they slid from that
lofty perch to become relegation candidates again before jumping back up the
table to the respectable zone.
This season, the change of manager, with all the trauma that surrounded Jim
Jefferies' departure to Hearts, as well as indifferent form to begin with, has
held up their progress but new manager John Lambie has started to get his
message across and there has been improvement.
The Edinburgh sides have made identical, if marginal, moves up the graph, with
each a point better off than last year.
In Hibs' case, that keeps them in the same third place as last season, while
Hearts are two places higher in the table in fifth spot.
Partick Thistle, who performed a memorable escape in the closing weeks of the
season, are three points better off at the moment than at this point last
season, while Kilmarnock, after 14 games, are three points behind their total
of last season.
We should not let this milestone pass without paying tribute to newcomers Raith
Rovers who have not only conducted themselves with some style in the UEFA Cup
but have reached fourth place in the division.
</TEXT>
