<TEXT>
WORKERS at the Clydeside warship builder Yarrow are holding a secret ballot on
whether to follow the recommendation of shop stewards and accept the company's
latest offer on redundancies.
Shop stewards - who have warned that industrial action could have grave
implications for the yard - recommended at a mass meeting yesterday that the
2500 manual workers accept a revised offer of enhanced redundancy terms. The
decision to hold a ballot was taken after a show of hands revealed workers were
divided on the issue.
The result of the ballot, which started yesterday, is expected to be known
today.
Shop stewards said yesterday they were confident that workers - most of whom
are members of the GMB and EEPTU trade unions - would accept the company's
offer but warned that the yard was on a ``knife-edge''.
Any industrial action could jeopardise the chances of securing a
multimillion-pound contract to build up to three Type 23 frigates for the Royal
Navy.
The company announced 415 redundancies in September because of a dearth of
naval orders. The future of about 315 workers still hangs in the balance as the
company waits to hear whether any new orders are in the pipeline.
The Minister for Defence Procurement, Mr James Arbuthnot, is expected to
announce who has won the contract for the latest round of Type 23 frigates in
the House of Commons within the next few weeks.
After yesterday's meeting, yard convener Dougie Conroy said he thought workers
would accept the offer but warned that the Type 23 order could be awarded to
the Southampton-based shipbuilder Vosper Thornycroft if they took strike action
and said such warnings were not scaremongering.
He said: ``Our message to the workers is clear. The shop stewards are
recommending that, in light of the current position the company finds itself
in, they accept the company's latest offer.
``Things are on a knife-edge. If we have industrial action, it is possible that
the Type 23s will go to Vosper rather than Yarrow. If that happens, then the
yard is down the tubes. That is the reality and the workers have to understand
that and we hope they make the right decision.''
A spokeswoman for the Ministry of Defence said yesterday the contract
announcement was due to be made before the end of the year.
Mr Murray Easton, managing director of Yarrow, was not available for comment
yesterday.
Workers vote on redundancies
KEITH SINCLAIR
</TEXT>
