<HEADLINE>Saltire awards for quality projects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lucy Lockhart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lucy Lockhart
reports on the latest round of awards for civil engineering schemes
THIS week saw the Saltire Award for Civil Engineering presented by Rear Admiral
Douglas Dow, director of the National Trust for Scotland, at a ceremony at the
Royal Society of Edinburgh.
The 200 guests were addressed by Professor Tony Ridley, newly appointed
President of the Institution of Civil Engineers (ICE) and the ceremony was
chaired by Mrs Margaret Street, chairman of the Council of the Saltire Society.
Founded in 1936 by a group of people who wanted to see Scotland restored to its
proper position as a cultural entity, the Saltire Society is concerned with all
things Scottish, past, present and future - its main criteria being the present
and the future.
An apolitical body, the society aims to preserve the best of Scottish
tradition, encouraging new development which can strengthen and enrich the
country's cultural life.
The Saltire Housing Award was begun in 1938, while the idea of introducing an
award for civil engineering in Scotland came from the two local associations of
the ICE.
In response to their request for advice on the mechanics of running an awards
scheme, the society offered to sponsor a Saltire Award for Civil Engineering,
in conjunction with two local associations of the ICE. The purpose of the award
is to recognise and encourage excellence in civil engineering in Scotland, and
an important aspect in judging the entries is the extent to which the projects
advance the art of civil engineering, with separate awards being made for
design and construction.
In 1993, an additional category was added to the awards scheme specifically for
conservation.
Since the competition was first instituted in 1981, and up to and including
last year, nine design and 14 construction awards and two joint
design/construction commendations have been made.
Saltire Awards for Civil
Engineering 1995
Design Award: A74(M) Cleuchbrae to Ecclefechan. Commissioning Authority:
Scottish Office Industry Department Roads Directorate. Designer: Scott Wilson
Kirkpatrick.
Design Award: North Berwick Sewage Disposal Scheme. Commissioning Authority:
Lothian Regional Council. Designer: Department of Water and Drainage Lothian
Regional Council.
Design Commendation: BP Harding Gravity Base Structure. Commissioning
Authority: Britoil Plc. Designer: Taywood Engineering Limited.
Design Commendation: A944 Bridge of Newe Reconstruction. Commissioning
Authority: Grampian Regional Council. Designer: Grampian Regional Council
Department of Roads.
Design Commendation: A74(M) Water of Milk to Ecclefechan. Cowdens Railway
Bridge Commissioning Authority: Scottish Office Industry Department Roads
Directorate. Designer: Robert Benaim &amp; Associates.
Construction Award: A74(M) Water of Milk to Ecclefechan. Cowdens Railway
Bridge: Commissioning Authority: Scottish Office Industry Department Roads
Directorate. Contractor: Balfour Beatty Construction (Scotland) Ltd.
Construction Commendation: A830 Morar Bypass. Commissioning Authority: Scottish
Office Industry Department  Roads Directorate. Contractor: Morrison
Construction Ltd.
Construction Commendation: BP Harding Gravity Base Structure. Commissioning
Authority: Britoil Plc. Contractor: Costain Taylor Woodrow Joint Venture.
Construction Commendation: A74(M) Cleuchbrae to Ecclefechan. Commissioning
Authority: Scottish Office Industry Department Roads Directorate. Contractors:
Balfour Beatty Construction (Scotland) Ltd, Barr Limited, Miller Civil
Engineering.
Conservation Commendation: A73 Cartland Bridge. Commissioning Authority:
Strathclyde Regional Council. Designer: Babtie Group.
