<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UEFA ban Le Saux and Batty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BLACKBURN'S Graeme Le Saux and David Batty, already heavily fined by the club,
were yesterday suspended for two matches by UEFA for their punch-up in the
Champions' League match against Spartak Moscow.
The European governing body had announced earlier that they would take no
action against the England internationalists and Le Saux and Batty were stunned
by a fax which arrived at Ewood notifying them of a dramatic about-turn.
``The news has come as a bit of a shock,'' said chairman Robert Coar. ``All the
statements we had seen said UEFA were not going to take further action.''
The English FA, which had urged UEFA to act against such a bad high-profile
incident, were surprised, but pleased, with the decision.
``We asked UEFA to consider taking action and they have now done so. We
consider this to be the end of the matter,'' said a spokesman.
UEFA spokesman Peter Limacher had said: ``We will respect the referee's opinion
that it is not worthy of further action.'' But then they received the Fair Play
report, compiled by a UEFA official, and quietly signalled that they were
reopening their investigations because of ``new facts.''
</TEXT>
