<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BANKING TSB shareholders approve merger</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TSB Group chief executive Peter Ellwood pledged no branches would be axed in
Scotland next year, as shareholders approved the bank's #16bn merger with
Lloyds.
His assurance follows TSB's closure of some 35 of its Scottish branches this
year.
Addressing an extraordinary meeting in Glasgow, Mr Ellwood said: ``I am very
happy to tell you there will be no branch closures in Scotland in 1996.''
He did not envisage any reduction in the new Lloyds-TSB Group's Scottish
workforce, made up of 3200 employees from TSB and 100 from the ``big four''
bank.
More specifically, he revealed there were no plans to cut the combined
450-strong workforce at TSB's international banking operation in Edinburgh and
mortgage processing centre in Glasgow.
He said the merged operation would retain the commitment to create another 700
jobs at its #17m telephone banking operation in Glasgow, which opened this
year. This currently employs 200 people.
Scotland looks likely to escape most of the #350m of annual cost savings
envisaged by Lloyds TSB by 1999.
However, when pressed by the Banking Insurance and Finance Union (BIFU), Mr
Ellwood was unable to guarantee that there would be no compulsory redundancies
among the banks' UK workforces after the merger.
Earlier, in a carefully phrased statement, he told the meeting he envisaged
``reductions being achieved without the need for any large-scale compulsory
redundancies''.
However, responding to a question from BIFU, he said: ``You ask for an
assurance of no compulsory redundancies. I can't give you that assurance but we
have said many times that, if there is to be a reduction in the number of
staff, we anticipate this will be achieved largely on a voluntary basis and
through natural staff turnover.''
BIFU, which yesterday issued shareholders with leaflets urging them to reject
the merger, claims 10,000 of 90,000 jobs could be axed and 650 High Street
branches could disappear as a result of the link-up.
There was a large security presence yesterday, after a similar meeting held by
Lloyds on Monday was disrupted by environmental protestors.
Lloyds shareholders will receive 2.704 shares in Lloyds-TSB Group for every
Lloyds share currently held. TSB shareholders will own the same number of
shares in the enlarged group as they do in TSB but will also receive a one-off
payout.
However, analysts believe the merger deal is worth less, certainly to private
TSB shareholders, than the current market price per TSB share.
Individuals will receive a special dividend net, at 68.3p. However, TSB's
institutional shareholders, because of their tax position, will receive an
extra 17p per share.
Shares in TSB have rocketed by 48% since the banks announced they were in talks
last month.
Although TSB shareholders could, by selling their shares now, realise more in
cash than the apparent value of their resultant holding in Lloyds-TSB plus the
special dividend, the TSB share price indicates a conviction that the enlarged
operation has good prospects.
The merger, effectively a reverse takeover, requires the approval of the Bank
of England and the High Court, which should have been obtained by December 18.
It should become effective on December 28 and TSB shareholders will receive
their special dividend 21 days later.
</TEXT>
