<HEADLINE>Shelter attack on Scottish Homes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE housing agency Scottish Homes was accused of glossing over Scotland's
housing crisis in its annual report published yesterday.
Shelter Scotland, the housing charity, claimed the agency was doing ``a major
disservice'' to the case for new housing investment by the self congratulatory
tone of its report.
Summing up the year, Scottish Homes said it had exceeded its housing target
and, with a record level of investment of #565m, had provided more than 9000
houses. Around 3000 of these homes had been made possible as a result of the
#184m levered into the agency's own development programme from banks and
building societies.
Scottish Homes also calculated around 3000 jobs were created or sustained each
year as a result of their joint investment activity. In addition, the agency
had helped provide around 2400 houses for homeless people and spent more than
#1m in helping improve the quality of information and advice available to the
homeless.
However, Shelter depute director Kate Caskie said the agency's achievements
should be judged against the scale of housing need in Scotland, not against its
own targets. At least 13,000 affordable rented homes were needed in each of the
next five years in Scotland. Scottish Homes had not even met half of that
target.
So far as homelessness was concerned, Shelter said Scottish Homes had fallen
short of its own target of 2500 homes and had come nowhere near meeting the
real need.
Shelter suggested the agency should re-direct its public-relations efforts into
convincing the Scottish Secretary of the reality of housing problems.
</TEXT>
