<HEADLINE>Nato sends in peace vanguard as Bosnians prepare to seal Dayton pact Date set for Paris signing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo
BALKAN leaders plan to sign a Bosnia peace package in Paris on December 14 as
Nato was preparing to move quickly to send an advance force of around 2600
troops into the country to police it.
The French Foreign Ministry confirmed the signing date today, adding: ``France
hopes that the former Yugoslav republics will use the occasion formally to
extend diplomatic relations to one another.''
The peace deal, initialled on November 21 in Dayton, Ohio, by the leaders of
Serbia, Bosnia, and Croatia, would create a unified Bosnian republic with two
constituent states, one Muslim-Croat and the other Serb.
Thousands of Serbs in the Sarajevo suburb of Ilidza rallied in protest against
the Dayton accord, which would force the former besiegers to loosen their grip
on the Bosnian capital.
In Brussels, Nato diplomats said the Alliance's top policy-making body would
give final approval tomorrow or on Friday for sending in 2600 troops early next
week at the start of the most dangerous mission Nato has yet undertaken.
The body, the North Atlantic Council, would also formally approve deploying a
multi-national force of 60,000 well-armed troops, one-third of them American,
to enforce the peace.
The chief architect of the deal, US Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Holbrooke, said today that the risk to the 20,000 US troops involved was
manageable. ``This is not war. This is not Vietnam. It is not Somalia. It is
not Lebanon,'' he said.
Holbrooke said the presidents of Bosnia, Serbia, and Croatia all ``sent
assurances to President Bill Clinton in writing guaranteeing the safety and
security of American and Nato forces''.
The Republican-led Congress opposes sending troops into what many US
politicians see as a Balkan quagmire.
A top US general said earlier that the rest of the peace force, which would
start moving in after the signing of the accord, should be in place at former
front lines within 30 days.
A 10-member US military team to pave the way for the American contingent
arrived today in the central Bosnian town of Tuzla, the future US contigent
headquarters.
However, as the world rushed to help implement peace, protesting Serbs vowed to
resist the handover of their Sarajevo suburb to Muslim and Croat rule.
Demonstrators strung banners across the road. One five-year-old carried a
placard saying: ``I live here, I was born here, help me please.''
Speakers denounced the peace deal as a betrayal and individual protesters named
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, who negotiated it on behalf of the
Bosnian Serbs, as the principal traitor.
It was the latest in a series of angry but orderly demonstrations encouraged by
hard-line Serb officials, who backed Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic's
demand that the future status of Sarajevo be renegotiated.
The Dayton agreement calls for the Bosnian capital, including the mainly Serb
suburbs, to be unified under the control of the Muslim-Croat Federation.
Karadzic has demanded in vain a Berlin-style ethnic division.
In a letter to US President Bill Clinton today, French President Jacques Chirac
called for guarantees to be given to Serbs in Sarajevo.
``It is out of the question to renegotiate the terms of the agreement
concerning Sarajevo as the Bosnian Serbs want, but it is absolutely essential
that we give the Bosnian Serb population there the guarantees they quite
rightly expect,'' Chirac wrote.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
