<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spooks see no future for Pentagon psychics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE spooks took over the fortune-tellers from the boffins last summer, and
concluded it was all hocus-pocus.
For 20 years or so, the Pentagon had employed a team of psychics, costing #7m
over the past decade, to use their paranormal senses to find missing Americans
and divine what secrets were hidden in suspicious foreign buildings.
Then the CIA took over the programme, and soon concluded that it was a complete
waste of money. This is Washington, however, and the Pentagon insists that the
mystics were occasionally useful as sources of valuable military tips.
One participant claimed that the clairvoyants detected a Soviet submarine
programme in 1979 and had also divined the purposes of key buildings in foreign
cities. They were asked to explain the purpose of a suspicious Soviet radar
station in Central Asia and the true function of a Libyan training facility for
the PLO.
The US Coast Guard asked them to locate ships smuggling drugs and the National
Security Council asked them to divine the design of a new Soviet submarine.
Evidently these were not obscure fortune-tellers in a distant corner of the
military establishment, but a proper intelligence-gathering operation in the
heart of it.
There was also a more conventional scientific research project, conducted by
the DIA which usually concerns itself with spy satellites. The clairvoyants
were given offices in a military installation near the Pentagon, and there
exercised their skills at ```remote viewing''. Each psychic would be isolated
in a room and would be asked to select one of four photographs displayed in
another room and decide which was the correct target.
They ought to have guessed right 25% of the time, but some of them managed a
30% accuracy rate. According to the Washington Post, which obtain a copy of the
subsequent CIA report, one of the assessors found that the research showed a
statistically significant success rate. She said it was ``definitely
worthwhile: there is convincing evidence of a real phenomenon here.''
The other assessor was not impressed, however, and the CIA wants to close down
the programme. Eventually it will probably succeed.
Washington
</TEXT>
