<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>JobCentre staff to strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN's 1300 JobCentres face disruption today as thousands of staff take the
day off in protest at an imposed pay increase of 2.3%.
Talks aimed at resolving the dispute broke down yesterday and the main union
involved, the Civil and Public Services Association, said JobCentres across the
country would be hit along with unemployment benefit offices.
General secretary Barry Reamsbottom accused the Employment Service of being
``hard nosed'' by refusing to pay performance-related increases he said had
been promised to staff.
``Workers feel they have been cheated out of a rise they are entitled to
receive,'' he said, adding that he had left no stone unturned in trying to
avoid the strike, which could have been settled with a small amount of money.
Mr Reamsbottom said despite the involvement of the conciliation service Acas
and an appeal to Education and Employment Secretary Gillian Shephard to
intervene, talks had broken down.
He predicted that the ``vast majority'' of the country's 1300 JobCentres would
close but managers insisted that most would remain open and operate ``as normal
a service as possible''.
A spokeswoman for the Education and Employment Department said:
``We expect the vast majority of JobCentres to stay open. The strike will
achieve nothing as we have already allocated all funds available this year for
paying staff.
``A strike will impact mainly on clients, particularly unemployed people.''
The Employment Service's Scottish director, Mr Alan Brown, said he hoped all
148 offices would be open, with the payment of unemployment benefits given
priority.
The one-day action follows a dispute over new pay levels for clerical and
junior executive staff.
</TEXT>
