<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOOD PRODUCER Life is sweet for Tate &amp; Lyle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRONG growth in North America has underpinned a good performance from Tate &amp;
Lyle which is busily expanding its international interests in sugar and other
sweeteners.
Profits rose 23% to #374m before exceptionals in the year to September and
dividends are increased by 11% to 16p after a final of 11p.
The corn sweeteners and starch business in North America saw a 16% increase in
operating profits to #171m, representing just under half the total of #365m
after charging #25.5m of exceptionals. These included #7m of provisions to
cover the closure of the Greenock sugar refinery in two to three years.
Production is to be concentrated at the London site.
Margins of the main company, Staley, were down as a result of a surge in maize
prices but volumes were up and costs reduced. Cane sugar margins were also
lower.
North American profits stood still in the second half and margin pressure is
continuing. Raw material costs have risen by 50% and the industry is waiting to
see if higher prices for sweeteners stick.
Tate &amp; Lyle chairman Sir Neil Shaw believes current year margins overall will
be lower as a result. But he is confident volumes will continue to move ahead
as the US market for sweeteners is expanding by some 5% a year.
Europe made more modest progress, with trading profits up 6% at #144m. The
domestic market was helped by the hot summer and export demand was good,
reflecting a world shortage of quality white sugar. Productivity rose by 4%,
helped by a modernisation programme.
Tate &amp; Lyle is investing heavily in widening its geographical scope,
particularly in developing countries where there is great long-term growth
potential. Investments totalling #142m in the year included cane mills in
China, Mexico, Zambia and the Ukraine, a starch glucose plant in Turkey and a
beet processing plant in the Czech Republic. It has also taken an interest in a
large glutamate factory in China.
Since 1990 a total of #539m has been invested in new projects, of which #129m
has been in developing markets. These have made only a modest contribution to
profits so far, but Sir Neil projects a quarter could be coming from emerging
markets in developing countries and eastern Europe in three years.
In-fill acquisitions are also being made in traditional markets, such as in
cane refining and packing and distribution in the US.
Tate &amp; Lyle shares rose 10p to 454p where they look modestly rated selling at
under 10 times earnings and yielding 4.4%, but the City believes current year
growth could be much less impressive because of the margin pressure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Torrance chases title</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEFENDING champion Nick Faldo heads a 12-man field at the Sun City Million
Dollar Challenge, with fellow Britons Colin Montgomerie and Sam Torrance also
chasing the huge rewards on offer at the tournament, which starts today.
Six of the world's top 10 players line up in the Johannesburg event, set to be
the most fiercely contested yet in its fifteen years.
But Nick Price, champion in 1993, believes the reason Sun City keeps attracting
excellent fields is less about money - last place is guaranteed #66,000 - than
the quality of the Gary Player Country Club course.
``Sun City is one of the best all-round tests of golf we play world-wide. It
demands straight driving, precise iron shots, and a nerveless short game,''
said Price, who won the Zimbabwe Open last Sunday.
``If you're going to shoot a low round you have to be aggressive with your
irons, and, with the way the course is set up, that means you're going to miss
a few greens.
``For that reason you have to have utter confidence in your sand wedge and
putter.''
One man happy with his putter at the moment is Torrance. His broomstick secured
second place in the European order of merit this season and, at 42, he is
playing the best golf of his life.
Torrance is a first-time player at the tournament, but has reason to remember
the Gary Player Country Club. In 1981, he walked off the course in contention
after two rounds of the Sun City Classic. He then jumped fully clothed into one
of the resort's swimming pools and did not tee up for the third round. Heat
stroke was the official explanation and the elements remain a factor on a
course where temperatures above 35 degrees are commonplace.
Most of the local money will be bet on South Africa's Ernie Els. Els let Faldo
in by double-bogeying the fifteenth in last year's final round and finished
tied for third.
By his own exacting standards, Faldo has had a modest year - his first as a
full-time player on the US PGA Tour. But he still won the Doral Ryder Open and
finished five times in the top 10, so he cannot be discounted.
Three-times winner David Frost has slipped down the rankings this year. But
Bernhard Langer, champion in 1985 and 1991, has enjoyed another successful
season and has every facet of the game Price says the course requires.
Good summer rains have toughened up the rough and there seems little prospect
of any player challenging Price's remarkable 1993 total of 264, 24 under par.
The field is:
N Faldo (England), N Price (Zimbabwe), E Els (S Africa), P Mickelson (USA), D
Frost (S Africa), C Rocca (Italy), C Montgomerie (Scotland), S Torrance
(Scotland), B Langer (Germany), C Pavin (USA), T Lehman (USA), V Singh (Fiji).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
