<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firms are falling short on value creation - another nettle which must be grasped, says Morag MacFarlane of KPMG Management Consulting Creating a tradition where none exists</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Morag MacFarlane</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES fail to manage for value. A new European research survey published by
KPMG Management Consulting highlights the large gap which exists between
organisations being aware of the powerful Value Based Management tool (VBM) and
implementing it.
While 70% of those surveyed were aware of the concept of economic value, only
8% claimed to have implemented it fully.
VBM influences an organisation's behaviour and decisions. It ultimately acts as
a catalyst in changing traditional attitudes. It can enable management to
transform the organisation into a value based one by:
n.Establishing economic value creation as the governing objective, that is -
and this is one for finance directors - the net present value of its future
free cash-flows discounted at the weighted average cost of capital.
n.Implementing strategies which provide the highest potential value creation.
n.Designing performance measurement systems to monitor value creation (or
destruction) and value drivers.
n.Aligning all management and decision-making processes with value creation,
including, for example, strategic planning, resource allocation, performance
management and employees' remuneration.
The creation of value, together with managing for value, will increasingly
become a principal objective for successful European organisations wanting to
grow in a competitive global market. More and more European organisations claim
to be managing for value but without a clear definition of what it is or how to
implement it.
As a leading proponent of VBM, KPMG carried out research by polling directors
and executives in leading European organisations in a variety of sectors to
establish:
1.To what extent do they manage for value?
2.How do they implement the concept of VBM?
3.What are the results?
Based on responses from more than 450 of Europe's leading companies, the
findings show that in the UK 12% of respondents are true users. This compares
with the European low of only 3% recorded in Germany. The most significant use
of VBM is in the energy, water and construction sectors. The lowest is in the
hotel and catering industry.
Awareness of VBM is high at 70%. But when it comes to implementation only half
(35%) claim to use it at all and less than 10% use it for key business
decisions. This low level of implementation was surprising given the high
recognition of shareholder satisfaction as a key goal.
Of those that had implemented the process 83% claimed that          it had
added value to their organisations. The major bene-fits were enhanced market
value, improved strategic decisions, improved management performance and better
understanding of market forces.
However, a general misunderstanding of how financial markets work emerged. Many
were unaware of how the financial markets value their organisation and still
more were unable to say whether the financial markets fairly valued their
organisation.
Our conclusion was that there is a depressing lack of implementation of VBM and
of those who claim to have implemented it many still do not claim to measure
actual value creation within their organisation.
Until an organisation grasps the nettle of measurement any other actions are
largely irrelevant.
What does this mean for Scottish business? Are you managing for value? What are
the key objectives for your organisation? Those in the survey considered
customer satisfaction the most important objective, with shareholder
satisfaction second. However, those which used real VBM rated shareholder
satisfaction higher than those which did not.
How well defined and implemented are your strategies which demonstrate the
highest potential value? Of those asked 84% said that concentrating on core
activities to maintain profitability fits well with their corporate strategy.
What performance measures do you have to monitor value creation and value
drivers? Organisations use a variety of (often conflicting) tools to measure
performance. At the corporate level profit is the most commonly used measure,
together with cash flow and returns on capital and equity measures. At the
business unit level market share and sales growth are considered more important.
How do you align other management processes, such as executive remuneration,
with value creation? Having a reward structure in place that supports the
philosophy of VBM is important. The long-term perspective of value creation is
not often taken into account in current remuneration schemes.
It is also important to look at how you communicate throughout the
organisation. Have employees at all levels been advised of your priorities and
understand the role they have to play in their achievement?
Clear communication on where your business is going and how you expect it to
get there, linked to well defined roles, are essential in harnessing employees'
understanding and commitment to value creation.
How do you measure up?
VBM cannot be implemented overnight. Implementing it is about value at all
levels in the organisation, about being aware of and aligning conflicting
objectives towards value creation, designing strategies which create value,
regularly measuring value at all levels, educating and motivating staff to
become accustomed to the concept, and rewarding creation of value.
It is the combination of these processes and the education and training of
employees which makes value-based management successful
</TEXT>
