<HEADLINE>Treatment could keep woman alive for 10 years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bruce McKain</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The doctors say their patient should have the right to die. A QC says her right
is to live. Bruce McKain reports on proceedings.
JANET Johnstone could survive for up to a decade if she continued to receive
her present treatment, according to the consultant in charge of her case.
Another doctor told the court that, in his opinion, to prolong her life
artificially would be a form of cruelty to her relatives.
Dr Iain O'Brien, the consultant physician treating Mrs Johnstone, said she was
not in pain and was well looked after by nursing staff.
Mr Colin McEachran QC, appearing on Mrs Johnstone's behalf, asked from whom the
proposal to withdraw treatment had come.
The doctor thought it had been initiated not by relatives but from the clinical
team, probably himself.
Asked whether there had been any input from the hospital administration, Dr
O'Brien replied that this had happened only latterly in dealing with the legal
aspects of the case.
He explained that although Mrs Johnstone was receiving medication, for example
to prevent seizures, the most important aspect would be the removal of food and
water which she was receiving through a nasal tube.
He believed the effect of that would be that she would die from dehydration
within 10 to 14 days.
``Would this cause distress to her?'' asked Mr McEachran. ``I do not believe it
would,'' replied Dr O'Brien.
Mr McEachran then asked why medical treatment should be withdrawn. The doctor
replied: ``From the medical point of view, it has been established that this
lady has no prospects of recovery. She is not aware of her surroundings.
``The medical treatment is sustaining a state of affairs which, I think it is
reasonable to suggest, is not in her best interests and her best interests
would be best served by withdrawing the treatment and allowing her to die.''
It was not known how long she might survive if she continued to be fed
artificially. It could be anything from a month to 10 years.
Dr Richard Metcalfe, a consultant neurologist at Glasgow's Southern General
Hospital, told the court he had been called in to give a second opinion on Mrs
Johnstone.
He had no doubt she was in a persistent vegetative state and, generally in such
cases, if there was no improvement within a year of receiving appropriate
treatment, the prospects of progress were virtually nil.
He was not aware of anyone showing any sign of improvement after almost four
years and supported Dr O'Brien's proposal to withdraw nutrition and hydration.
On the basis that Mrs Johnstone had been in her present condition for a long
period, during which her family saw no prospect of her improving to lead any
useful form of life, he felt that prolongation of life would be a form of
cruelty to her relatives.
Asked about Mrs Johnstone's own interests, Dr Metcalfe replied: ``All one can
go on is one's personal view; what I would want for myself and members of my
family.
``I certainly would not want my own life or the life of relatives to be
prolonged artificially.''
</TEXT>
