<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Income from tuck shop buys 940 pupils a jumper</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
AN inner-city secondary is celebrating St Andrew's Day by giving each of its
940 pupils a school jumper to extend the wearing of school uniform.
The near #6000 cost has been met out of the proceeds from the school's tuck
shop, which means that the pupils of St Andrew's Secondary in the East End of
Glasgow have received an unexpected bonus from buying food and drinks.
Based on yesterday's reaction, the gift - which has coincided with the school's
as well as Scotland's patron saint's day - has been popular with pupils.
They said it would take the pressure off pupils and parents to conform with the
fashion to wear expensive sweatshirts with branded logos along with the
standard uniform of white shirt and tie and grey trousers and skirts.
The school's catchment includes disadvantaged areas and pupils said the jumper
- or the cardigan which girls could choose - meant that no-one would stand out
because they could not afford a sweatshirt or a school jumper.
Fifth-year pupil Letitia Mclaughlin said: ``It is a good idea. I think everyone
is quite happy with it.''
Mr Bruce Malone, who has been head teacher for four years, believes that school
uniform is one of the marks of an effective school.
He said: ``The school has always had a uniform policy, but it was effective to
varying degrees. Over the past few years it has been worn quite extensively,
although there have been debates about what constitutes full uniform.
``Parents, pupils, and staff generally thought that if there was an appropriate
school jumper it should be worn.''
Uniform promoted uniformity, the identity of the school, pride in it, and
enabled its young people to be seen in the community as pupils of St Andrew's,
said the head.
Providing each pupil with a jumper or cardigan removed the fashion mentality
prompted by the wearing of sweatshirts, and gave parents and young people the
confidence to wear the new top, because they would know that it would be
commonplace throughout school.
Mr Malone continued: ``Putting the whole school in uniform gives pupils
confidence in themselves. It boosts morale and self-esteem. They are coming to
school dressed in a professional way for their work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tutu to head
truth commission
PRETORIA: Nobel peace laureate Archbishop Desmond Tutu will head South Africa's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission looking into apartheid-era political crimes
and human rights violations.
The Cabinet approved the 17-member commission, which will have 18 months to
investigate the human rights record of the former apartheid government. It will
have the power to award compensation to victims and grant amnesty to penitent
offenders.
Trial delayed
BANGKOK: The drug trial in Thailand of Britons Sandra Gregory and Robert Lock
failed to go ahead for the tenth time yesterday after an airline witness failed
to appear despite a summons for his arrest. The latest delay means that Miss
Gregory, who has admitted trafficking in heroin, and Mr Lock, who denies the
charge, have been on trial for two-and-a-half years.
Incest pair jailed
OXFORD: A woman and her grandfather who had a 20-year incestuous relationship
were jailed for five years for plotting to kill her husband. The judge in
Oxford, Mississippi, told Teresa Hutcheson, 30, and William Hinson, 71, that it
was ``the most sordid case I've seen, where the great-grandfather is also the
father of his great-grandchildren''.
Four die at polls
CAIRO: Four people, including two elderly women, were killed and scores injured
yesterday as Egyptians voted for a new Parliament. The opposition reported
electoral abuses by police and the ruling party.
Dingo baby plea
SYDNEY: The couple cleared in Australia's notorious ``dingo baby'' case,
Michael and Lindy Chamberlain, are asking the Northern Territory coroner to
rule that a wild dog caused the death of their baby Azaria 15 years ago.
Coroner John Lowndes will give his ruling on December 13.
#45m win
ST CHARLES: A 64-year-old woman who has worked in a McDonnell Douglas aircraft
factory for 29 years has won #45m in America's multi-state Powerball lottery.
Jerry Sue Huellweig, of Missouri, was the single winner of the state's biggest
ever jackpot. She plans to stop work immediately, buy a new house and car, and
share the rest with her family.
Blood taint trial
HANOVER: The co-owner of a German pharmaceutical laboratory went on trial
yesterday facing almost 6000 counts of murder or attempted murder for selling
blood products tainted with the deadly HIV virus. Dr Gnter Kurt Eckert, 55, is
accused of distributing blood plasma which his Aprath laboratory failed to test
for the virus which causes Aids.
Nuclear pact
WASHINGTON: The US has won the agreement of its allies and Russia for a
co-operative programme to prevent the smuggling of nuclear materials. The
programme will be adopted at a Moscow summit in April of the Group of Seven
industrial nations, plus Russia and Ukraine.
Ale and hearty
MOSCOW: Russia's Beer Lovers predicted yesterday that they could pull off a
serious upset in next month's parliamentary election. The party is counting on
widespread disenchantment to win the 5% needed to take up seats in the State
Duma. However party leader Yuri Milyukov feared apathy. ``People might wake up
on election day and ask themselves if they should go to vote or drink beer. I
fear they will choose to drink beer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
