<DOCNO>GH951130-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Walter Alexander and Volvo hand over 60 new buses to SB Holdings On the road to joint success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REPRESENTATIVES of Walter Alexander yesterday handed over 60 ``all-Scottish''
buses to SB Holdings, the seventh-largest bus operating group in the UK, writes
KRISTY DORSEY.
The single-deck buses are part of #21m of orders placed with Walter Alexander
by SB Holdings, operator of Strathclyde Transport, GCT and Kelvin Central
Buses.
Walter Alexander will supply another 150 double-deck buses to SB Holdings in
1996.
The Falkirk-based company builds the bus bodies and installs engines supplied
by    the Volvo Bus plant in Irvine. The total order value of     #21m will be
split fifty-fifty between Walter Alexander and Volvo.
Handing over the buses at Hampden Park, Bill Cameron, managing director of
Walter Alexander, said the SB Holdings orders represented an important part of
the bus manufacturer's business.
``It's obviously a substantial order, and we're grateful they have placed the
order with us here in Scotland,'' he said. ``Our business has grown over the
last couple of years in line with the rest of the industry, and this ensures
current levels of employment, certainly through 1996.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BUSINESS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126645</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Railtrack on
whistlestop tour
RAILTRACK directors are visiting Edinburgh and Glasgow this morning to meet
institutions as part of the programme to build up support for the privatisation
the Government plans for next spring.
Privatisation director Richard Aitken-Davies said it would be the most
complicated privatisation to date. At least 51% of the shares will be sold off
- both a UK retail offering and an international book-building exercise are
intended - although the Treasury seems certain to press for a 100% disposal if
that is possible.
Scottish institutions so far have shown only muted interest in Railtrack
because of the paucity of information. Spelling out the future investment
programme, including that for the West Coast main line, and the precise
arrangements with the train operating companies will be major tasks.
Low seals deals
INTERNATIONAL packaging and materials group Low &amp; Bonar yesterday announced a
#3m acquisition in the UK and #7.5m of new investment in Canada. The
Dundee-based group has purchased Ex-Press Plastics, a plastic components
manufacturer, for #3m cash. It will make a further payment of up to #1.3m
according to profits made by the Norfolk firm in the year to November 30, 1996.
The board also approved a C$16.3m (#7.5m) capital expenditure investment to
modernise its production of multi-layered plastic bags in Canada.
Bandt in black
BANDT, formerly Brown &amp; Tawse, returned to profit in the first six months of
the year. It made a pre-tax profit of #1m compared with a previous loss of
#1.2m. Group turnover was #55.7m against #38m last time. There was a useful
#1.6m profit contribution from Kwikform UK, acquired from GKN in July. There is
no interim dividend but barring unforeseen circumstances the board intends to
pay a final dividend.
Directors on mat
RECORD numbers of directors are being disqualified from office, with the
Department of Trade and Industry's Insolvency Service taking action against 258
in the third quarter, a 77% increase on the same period last year. Misleading
creditors, misapplying assets, unauthorised payments to associates, excessive
remuneration or benefits and failure to co-operate with the authorities were
some of the reasons for disqualification.
</TEXT>
