<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth's plan for Scottish Grand Committee receives a St Andrew's Day rebuff. Where's the beef, opponents ask</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126647</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rabbit failed to appear from the Scottish Secretary's hat yesterday,
prompting scorn from his constitutional critics surprised by the lack of the
unexpected.
``I must say, I said to myself: `Is that it? Is that all?' Obviously, he must
have something more substantial tomorrow. He surely must, mustn't he?''
This was the reaction of Canon Kenyon Wright of the Scottish Constitutional
Convention, whose celebration of home rule plans today on St Andrew's Day in
Edinburgh has now become a three-way political bun-fight between
devolutionists, Unionists, and nationalists.
But Scottish Tories liked the idea of a beefed-up Scottish Grand Committee and
felt this gave them a defensible position on the Union which they could rally
round. ``I am very pleased,'' said party chairman Sir Michael Hirst. ``I think
it is a very useful development of a committee that includes every Scottish MP.
``It is fully elected and fully democratically accountable, with the power to
bring to Scotland key Ministers to talk about exclusively Scottish matters.
``When the people see the Prime Minister and Chancellor of the Exchequer coming
to Scotland to speak on Scottish issues, they will realise that under
Conservative proposals we have the means to ensure that Scottish affairs get
proper consideration at the highest level.''
Sir Michael delivered a broad hint that there would be no dramatic further
revelations by the Secretary of State today other than the widely flagged
suggestion of a beefed-up Scottish Economic Council to discuss issues and make
recommendations for legislation.
In particular, he dismissed the rumour that a multiple choice constitutional
referendum might be called, saying such a move would be inappropriate.
``I would imagine that the Scottish Economic Council would have the opportunity
to meet and talk about things in advance of them coming to the Scottish Grand
Committee.
``Within such a framework this body of Scottish MPs will be given unique powers
and this confirms that Michael Forsyth has had a very firm claim to be
Scotland's man in the Cabinet - enhancing our place in the Union without a
single penny of the `Tartan Tax' being levied or a single job being risked.''
Despite Sir Michael's enthusiasm, Opposition politicians were jubilant,
convinced that Mr Forsyth had raised expectation far beyond anything he could
deliver.
Apart from Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson's jibe - ``First we had
Taking Stock, now we have Taking the Michael'' - there was a widespread feeling
that Mr Forsyth had overplayed his hand.
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said: ``I thought he lost heart
halfway through delivering it, as if even he wasn't convinced. I don't think he
expected the hoots of derision he got. The mood was of disbelief bordering on
ridicule. There was just nothing there.
``If anything, he has made things worse by admitting that a democratic deficit
exists. Far from stabilising the Union, he has demonstrated that Scotland is
lumbered with undemocratic structures. There were a lot of hostages to fortune
in that speech.''
STUC general secretary Campbell Christie said his general council had discussed
its suggestions for an enhanced Scottish Economic Council yesterday but he
stressed: ``We see this as sitting alongside a Scottish parliament as a
consultative body. It is not a substitute for a parliament.
``If this damp squib of an announcement is really the best that Forsyth can
come up with then the Government is even more tired and worn-out than we
thought. The people of Scotland don't want more visits by Cabinet Ministers,
they want real constitutional change.''
Canon Wright said: ``The very fact that Michael Forsyth is talking about the
constitution at all is a tribute to the work of the Convention. We have set the
agenda - everything else is a reaction, and nothing at all would have been
offered without us.
``Imitation is the most sincere form of tribute, if not flattery. What was
offered today was a pretty poor imitation. The acid test is whether it proposes
giving real power to the people of Scotland, and his ideas fail this test.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
