<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Body to defuse terror of arms</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126649</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Q: What is the international arms decommission body?
A: The body which will advise the British and Irish Governments on arrangements
necessary for the handing in of IRA and all other illegally held weapons in
Northern Ireland.
Q: Who will be involved?
A: Three members will sit. It will be chaired by Mr George Mitchell, a former
US Senator and President Clinton's special economic adviser on Northern
Ireland. Two other ``eminent persons'' are expected to be chosen next week.
Q: What do they have to do?
A: The British and Irish Governments have asked them to submit a report by
mid-January. That will follow a series of consultations which will involve
inviting ``relevant parties'' to make submissions on how best to deal with the
issue of decommissioning.
Q: Will it be difficult?
A: Extremely. The IRA and the loyalist paramilitary organisations like the
Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) and Ulster Freedom Fighters (UFF) will NOT be
helping with inquiries. It effectively means the commission turning to the
likes of Sinn Fein and the small loyalist pressure groups - The Progressive
Unionist Party (PUP) and the Ulster Democratic Party (UDP) to help them.
Sources close to those organisations insisted last night there will be NO
handing over of weapons in advance of any overall political settlement.
Q: How many illegal guns are there?
A: Impossible to estimate. The IRA remains the best armed, with up to 1500
rifles and handguns. They have also some heavy machine guns, rockets, and other
missiles - all hidden in bunkers on both sides of the Irish border.
The loyalists have supplies of high-powered rifles smuggled in from South
Africa. Police believe they have access to Russian-made RPG-7 rockets.
Q: Will the commission consider guns held by the RUC and soldiers?
A: No. Downing Street refused Irish and Sinn Fein demands for ALL weapons to
come under review. There are around 130,000 legitimately held firearms in
Northern Ireland.
Q: Will the commission have any powers?
A: No. It's purely advisory but will make recommendations.
Q: Will the British and Irish Governments have to accept them?
A: No. They will consider them and ``give them due weight on their merits''.
Q: Will it work?
A: The commission has six weeks to come up with a report and recommendations
for the two Governments to consider while preparatory talks continue between
the various political parties.
Those talks are due to finish at the end of February before all sides move into
substantive dialogue on the future of Northern Ireland but only if the IRA
makes a move and some sort of decommissioning gesture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
