<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brown attacks Budget `failure'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126651</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHADOW Chancellor Gordon Brown rounded on the Chancellor last night, accusing
him of taking pounds away in tax rises and giving back only pennies in tax cuts.
Opening the second day's debate on the Budget in the Commons, Mr Brown branded
Kenneth Clarke not a prudent Chancellor but a ``prisoner of the Government's
economic failure''.
Mr Brown said that despite the 1p cut in income tax, people in total were
nearly #700 a year worse off after the 21 tax rises of recent years.
All the tax changes announced on Tuesday were worth little more than #2 a week
to the ordinary family - the price of two or three packets of peanuts.
With rises in prescription charges, rail fares, dental charges and the council
tax ``very few people are better of in any real terms.
Treasury Chief Secretary William Waldegrave said the Budget kept spending down,
kept borrowing on a downward path and protected high priority programmes.
It was ``plausible'' that the average family would gain some #450 a year in
personal disposable income.
Mr Waldegrave warned: ``If we were to find ourselves in this country with a
Labour Government elected on a basis of having promised lower taxes, higher
spending, no theory or ideology of any kind to guide them, no consistency or
plan, they would find themselves in a world where the sound-bite would avail
them nothing.
``It's called the real world. They would be a broken-backed government within
six months, as they always have been before.
For the Liberal Democrats, Malcolm Bruce said: ``This is a cautious Budget
because it had to be.
``The Chancellor knows very well that the economy is very sluggish at the
moment and that the most important thing that is needed is a drop in interest
rates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bruton fails to shift Major on arms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN COONEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dublin,
THERE is more of John Major than John Bruton in the twin track policy on
disarmament and political talks in Northern Ireland, according to independent
analysts in Dublin.
With the status of the International Body on decommissioning of arms merely
advisory, Mr Bruton is perceived as having so far failed to persuade Mr Major
to shift from his Washington demand for a handover of some IRA weapons before
political talks can begin.
A phone call from Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams to a television programme in
Dublin saying that he had not been briefed on the deal before Mr Bruton's
dramatic late-night visit to London on Tuesday also has created uncertainty in
staunch republican circles.
The speed with which Ulster Unionists poured cold water on the joint communique
- and their continued demands for a handover of weapons by the IRA ahead of
agreeing to talk to Sinn Fein - did little to inspire confidence that the
communique will meet its aim of all-party talks on Northern Ireland by the end
of February.
The negative Unionist reaction and the muted response from Sinn Fein have
contributed to a public verdict that the communique is more a fudge than a
breakthrough.
In the Dail yesterday, Mr Bruton and his Foreign Minister, Mr Dick Spring, did
not receive the glory and adulation that were heaped upon them earlier this
year after the launch of the Framework Document.
Nor was yesterday a ceremonial day of the kind which greeted former Taoiseach
Albert Reynolds two years ago when he returned from London after signing the
Downing Street Declaration.
There was relief, however, the stalemate had been broken and that Northern
Ireland should be able to enjoy its second violence-free Christmas. The next
three months are seen as either breaking or making the peace process.
If there is an immediate political beneficiary from Tuesday's deal it is the
week's star visitor to the two islands, President Bill Clinton, with both Mr
Major and Mr Bruton basking in the shadow of his lavish praise of them as
risk-takers for peace.
Mr Reynolds, now a parliamentary back bencher since his loss of power almost a
year ago, is in no doubt that the deal was a command performance for Mr Clinton.
While welcoming the need for ``something which will inject new life in a
process which had been flagging for some time'', Mr Reynolds was surprisingly
critical of his former counterpart, Mr Major.
He noted that Mr Major's insistence of a handover of some IRA arms as a
precondition of talks was ``unacceptable and unobtainable''.
Mr Major was looking for surrender and was pursuing a militaristic rather than
a political approach, he said.
According to Mr Reynolds, the American president had never accepted that arms
should be decommissioned in advance of talks.
Mr Reynolds suggested that President Clinton's ``own man'' - former senator
George Mitchell who will chair the international body - might come up with a
set of proposals to let the British Government off the hook on the arms issue.
Mr Reynolds said he was sure President Clinton realised that the British
Government's attitude on this was the stumbling block for the last nine months.
In a spirited defence of the communique as providing a new political dynamic in
the peace process, the Justice Minister, Mrs Nora Owens, claimed that the Irish
government had secured more than it would have if the British-Irish summit had
gone ahead in September.
The main difference, she argued, is that the international body examining the
issue of decommissioning will be able to make an independent assessment of the
situation.
Long after President Clinton's visit, the paramilitary arms question will
continue to be what Mr Reynolds calls the stumbling block.
Newspaper coverage in the Irish Republic was generally favourable to the
initiative, which was seen as adding to the political stock of both Mr Bruton
and Mr Spring.
Giving the statement ``a hearty but cautious welcome'', the Irish Times
identified the co-operation of Dublin and London as its core principle.
``Without it, the many uncertainties lying ahead have no solution,'' it said,
summing up the mood in Ireland.
</TEXT>
