<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flying White House has gifts for city at peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Belfast,
THAT air of blase irritation which so often hangs around great events has
already settled on Belfast, as the city anticipates the first visit in history
of an American president.
Opposite City Hall, a stranger up from Dublin approaches a newsvendor with a
question: ``What night does your man switch on the Christmas lights?''
With a look of feigned wonder and fatigue, the vendor demands clarification
before entering substantive talks: ``What man do you mean, exactly?''
The stranger considers his position and replies: ``Your man, Big Bill, of
course.''
And the vendor answers: ``Och, that man! Sure, it's tomorrow night around tea
time. But you haven't a chance of meeting him because they'll be 70,000 lining
up in Donegall Square to do the same. And not a bus or taxi to be had in the
town.''
Traffic chaos is a mandatory consequence of all US presidential tours, and
given Northern Ireland's long experience of sealed-off streets and body
searches, the Province should be better able than most places to cope with such
annoyance. But 15 months of peace can play remarkable tricks with memory. As
soon as ordinary folk really began to believe that the ceasefire was no
mischievous ploy, it seemed the Troubles had ripped apart some far-off planet.
In contrast to the predictable rant of politicians, the people of Belfast and
Derry have revelled, this past year, in a social rebirth as bombs have given
way to boom.
``The people are actually ahead of the politicians on this one'', says a
shopkeeper on the Ormeau Road, where Hillary Clinton visits a community centre
today. ``You won't find us talking about the nuts and bolts of the latest
proposal because we're all far more interested in the reconstruction package
Bill Clinton will be bringing with him.''
Nevertheless, that Christmas booty, estimated to be in the region of $200m,
remains dependant on an overall peace settlement which partly accounts for the
high drama telephone calls and late-night dashing between Dublin and London
this week.
At the Europa Hotel, the advance party of the Flying White House are already
installed. So, too, is a shoeshine stand, the first of its kind in Northern
Ireland, which is situated just inside the foyer, a prime photo opportunity
site.
A few streets away workmen complete the presidential podium outside City Hall,
its shield of bulletproof glass having been specially flown in from Washington,
as if Belfast knew nothing about protection.
It will be from this vantage-point that Bill Clinton will illuminate the city's
festive decorations, an entourage of curious, razzmatazz diversity arranged
about him. Paul Newman will be there in his role of philanthropic
internationalist. So will some of America's key industrialists and Belfast's
own great unifier, the rock musician, Van Morrison.
Meanwhile guests will be taking up their positions inside the Whitla Hall of
Queen's University. The Secretary of State's reception could be the trickiest
event of the visit, as Northern Ireland's leading politicians desire to be
present but some nurse stern pledges about never being seen in the same room
together.
So, will David Trimble, leader of the Unionists, find himself reaching towards
the same tray of canapes as Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams?
Will President Clinton finally shake Adams by the hand? If he does, it is
likely to be well out of sight of the media. But the fact is the two pressed
the flesh some time ago at a St Patrick's Day party.
Clinton's gesture then was a gamble. In many ways it is still a gamble today,
but despite that blase irritation, Northern Ireland will rise to the occasion
and give its American visitor some special hoopla of its own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
