<DOCNO>GH951130-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Civil Service unions fear more Scottish Office redundancies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126655</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CIVIL Service unions claimed yesterday that Scottish Office staff are facing a
further 400 redundancies, on top of 1000 jobs already expected to be lost over
the next three years.
They said the deeper cuts - which could include compulsory losses - were the
price of Tuesday's Budget announcement, in which Chancellor Kenneth Clarke
outlined the Government's determination to reduce public expenditure.
Details of a 5% cut in running costs were given yesterday to the leaders of the
Civil and Public Services Association, the National Union of Civil and Public
Servants, and the Institute of Professionals, Managers and Specialists.
All staff also received a letter from Sir Russell Hillhouse, permanent
secretary at the Scottish Office, in which he says: ``The policy of having to
cover cost increases through efficiency savings will continue.''
He admits the Scottish Office's 5% cut will mean, after inflation is added, an
8% reduction in costs.
In his letter, Sir Russell says: ``Savings of this order cannot be achieved
without further reductions in total staff numbers. It is very much hoped that
these will be achieved through voluntary means, though there are specific areas
where this may not be possible.''
Final details of the redundancies are likely to emerge early in the new year.
The Scottish Prison Service has been exempted from any cuts.
Mr Michael McCann, Scottish officer of the CPSA, said the unions had estimated
about 1000 jobs would be lost because of the previous cutback, which was 14% of
running costs. The new reduction would mean at least a further 400 lost posts
out of the total complement of 5500 staff.
He warned the figure could rise even higher if non-staff savings could not be
made in Scottish Office expenditure.
Labour Employment spokesman John McFall said the decision to cut more jobs was
further evidence of Mr Forsyth's ``callous disregard for employment in
Scotland''.
THREE thousand temporary jobs in the voluntary sector will be lost as a result
of the Government's decision to cut the Community Action programme for
long-term unemployed adults, according to the Scottish Council for Voluntary
Organisations. (writes Elizabeth Buie).
Community Action, introduced in 1993, is delivered through the Employment
Service and offers temporary work opportunities to adults unemployed for more
than six months.
The move, announced on Tuesday, has angered voluntary organisations which
deliver Community Action, particularly as the Chancellor did not refer to the
move in his Budget statement.
Mr Ian Brown, enterprise and training officer with SCVO, said: ``Kenneth Clarke
barely referred to unemployment in his statement, but Employment Service
officials were press-releasing Community Action's obituary before he had even
sat down.''
Community Action providers said the programme was popular with long-term
participants and that its wide range of projects benefited the community.
</TEXT>
