<DOCNO>GH951130-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clinton sees joint role on world peace Parliament warms to President's speech emphasising the special relationship with Britain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126656</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton hailed the ``extraordinary relationship'' between
Britain and the United States yesterday as he made a historic address to both
Houses of Parliament.
Mr Clinton and his wife Hillary were welcomed amid pomp and pageantry to
Westminster by the Prime Minister and Commons Speaker Betty Boothroyd.
Arriving to a fanfare of trumpets he addressed a packed Royal Gallery in the
House of Lords, where the guests included former Prime Ministers Lady Thatcher
and Lord Callaghan.
After being formally welcomed by the Lord Chancellor Lord Mackay of Clashfern,
Mr Clinton said to laughter: ``I look out and see so many of your distinguished
leaders in the House of Lords and I think it might not be a bad place to be
after a long and troublesome political career.
``I have been here to Westminster many times before. As a student I visited
often and over the last 20 years I have often returned.
``Always I have felt the power of this place, where the voices of free people
who love liberty believe in reason and struggle for truth, have for centuries
kept your great nation a beacon of hope for all the world.''
Mr Clinton described Parliament as a ``monument to liberty'' and recalled its
role in opposing the tyrannies of earlier times.
``As one whose ancestors came from these isles, I cherish this opportunity.
``For a long time, I thought if my forebears had not left this country perhaps
I might have gotten here on my own, at least to the House of Commons.
``But now our American television carries your question time and I have seen
Prime Minister Major and Mr Blair and other Members slicing each other up face
to face with such great wit and skill against the din of cheers and jeers, I am
now convinced my forebears did me a great favour,'' he said to laughter.
President Clinton said that in this century, Britain and America had overcome
their differences, rediscovering their common heritage and shared values.
This month's remembrance of the two world wars had recalled how the two nations
had fought together.
In the Second World War, the troops had neither failed nor faltered, he said:
``In the greatest struggle for freedom in all of history, they saved the
world.''
Now the countries together were preparing the way for peace in Bosnia, ``where
your peace keepers have performed heroically and saved the lives of so many
innocent people.
``I thank the British nation for its strength and its sacrifice through all
these struggles and I am proud to stand here on behalf of the American people
to salute you.''
He continued: ``In this new era, we must rise not in a call to arms but in a
call to peace.''
This time was full of possibilities . The ``chasm of ideology'' had
disappeared. Much more of the world now shared the ideals that the US and
Britain had fought for.
In Europe and many other nations, long-suffering peoples at last controlled
their own destinies, and economic freedom was spreading with political freedom,
bringing renewed hope for a better life, rooted in ``honourable and healthy
competition of effort and ideas'', he said.
President Clinton said: ``America is determined to maintain our alliance for
freedom and peace with you, and determined to seek the partnership of all
like-minded nations to confront the threats still before us.''
The President turned to the end of the Cold War, claiming that the world had
``stepped back from the nuclear precipice'' with the extension of the Nuclear
Non-proliferation Treaty and next year's expected Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
``For the first time in a generation, parents in Los Angeles and Manchester
and, yes, in Moscow, can now turn out the lights at night knowing that there
are no nuclear weapons pointed at their children.''
On Northern Ireland, Mr Clinton said that the American people felt ``a special
gratitude for your efforts'' in the Province.
President Clinton said: ``With every passing month more people walk the streets
and live their lives safely, people who would otherwise have been added to the
toll of the troubles.''
He said that today he would ``have the privilege of being the first American
President to visit Northern Ireland''.
He added that it was ``a Northern Ireland where the guns are quiet and the
children play without fear''.
President Clinton said he applauded the work of Mr Major and Irish Prime
Minister John Bruton in setting up the new twin-track peace initiative, ``an
initiative which provides an opportunity to begin a dialogue in which all views
are represented and all views can be heard''.
President Clinton declared: ``This is a bold step forward for peace. I applaud
the Prime Minister for taking this risk for peace.
``It is always a hard choice, the choice for peace, for success is far from
guaranteed and even if you fail there will be those who resent you for trying.''
To loud applause, he insisted: ``But it is the right thing to do and in the end
the right will win.''
Mr Major, sitting next to Mrs Clinton in the front row, was seen to mouth the
words: ``Thank you.''
President Clinton went on to dismiss those who argued that the West could relax
now that the Cold War and other troubles were over.
He urged vigilance, saying: ``These are the siren songs of myth.''
President Clinton referred to movement towards isolationism in the US after the
First World War and the supporters of appeasement in the run-up to the Second
World War.
``We have gone down that road before, we must never go down that road again,''
he said. To applause, he added: ``We will never go down that road.''
President Clinton said: ``We must help peace to take hold in Bosnia, because so
long as that fire rages at the heart of the European continent, so long as the
emerging democracies and our allies are threatened by fighting in Bosnia, there
will be no stable, undivided, free Europe.''
Britain and America had a responsibility to answer the request of warring
parties in Bosnia to secure peace.
``Without our leadership and without the presence of Nato there will be no
peace in Bosnia.
``I thank the United Kingdom that has already sacrificed so much for its swift
agreement to play a central role in the peace implementation.
``With this act Britain holds true to its history and to its values. And I
pledge to you that America will live up to its history and its ideals as well.''
President Clinton then declared, to warm applause: ``Friends, we have stood
together in the darkest moments of our century. Let us now resolve to stand
together with the bright and shining prospect of the next century.
``It can be the age of possibility and the age of peace. Our forebears won the
war, let us now win the peace.''
`Our American television carries your question time and I have seen Prime
Minister Major and Mr Blair and other Members slicing each other up face to
face with such great wit and skill . . .'
`For the first time in a generation, parents in Los Angeles and Manchester and,
yes, in Moscow, can now turn out the lights at night knowing that there are no
nuclear weapons pointed at their children.'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concern for young over changes in benefits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOUSING benefit changes affecting young people would have ``malign
consequences'' with some driven into ``inadequate, unregulated and potentially
dangerous multiple- occupancy dwellings'', Labour spokesman Chris Smith said in
the Commons yesterday.
He was questioning Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley on welfare changes
announced in the Budget.
Mr Lilley angrily rounded on Labour MP Dennis Skinner (Bolsover), who said
reducing the level of benefit available to under-25s would increase the number
of young people on the streets who could be preyed on like the victims of Fred
and Rosemary West.
The Minister said that even by Mr Skinner's usual standards, that was ``a
distaseful attempt to exploit a ghastly tragedy for party political ends.''
He said benefit would be limited to the average cost of shared accomodation in
each locality. It would discourage unemployed younger people from leaving home
before they could afford to do so. It would also reduce the attraction to some
of moving to seaside resorts.
Mr Lilley also told the Commons that the Government is to devote extra
resources to fighting benefit fraud.
An additional #134m will be invested in sophisticated computer systems and
other checks to counter false claims.
Mr Lilley said that the reforms he had introduced to the social security system
would deliver a saving of #3.5bn next year - #500m from the current package -
which would grow to #5bn by the end of the century and save #15bn in the next
millennium. The expansion of the anti-fraud campaign should save #2.5bn by
1998-99, he added.
Mr Smith attacked the decision for the second year running to increase the
non-dependent part of housing benefit which he said would encourage families to
eject adult children from the family home. ``And this is the party which is
supposed to be in favour of keeping families together,'' he said.
The freezing of one-parent benefit hit at one of the few remaining benefits
which provided ``a genuine bridge into work,'' he said. The raising of
thresholds for people seeking long-term residential care was welcome but would
still leave most elderly people fearing they would have to sell the family home
to meet care costs.
When he sat down, Mr Lilley said ``You have just chalked up a bill of #1bn in
savings forgone.'' He told Mr Simon Hughes, for the Liberal Democrats, who
complained that the pensioners' #10 bonus had not been increased for 23 years:
``We are in serious government and we cannot afford to hand money out like
confetti.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dalyell questions findings of inquiry officer on Lockerbie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126658</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was urged by Labour MP Tam Dalyell last night to question the
reported findings of a key FBI officer in the Lockerbie bombing inquiry who,
the MP said, was currently under investigation for allegedly falsifying
evidence in another case.
Mr Dalyell (Linlithgow) named the officer as Thomas Thurman in the Commons as
he referred to the case against two Libyan suspects wanted for the bomb attack
on PanAm Flight 103 which resulted in the deaths of 270 people in December 1988.
Claiming that the credibility of the Government's case was in doubt, he said it
focused on a timing device which allegedly linked the Libyans with the bomb.
However, Mr Dalyell said he did not believe the timing device existed and there
was now doubt over the evidence of the FBI officer said to have identified it.
He told the House: ``Thomas Thurman, the FBI officer who has claimed to have
identified the timing device, is under investigation by the US Justice
Department into allegations by a fellow FBI officer, Frederic Whitehurst, that
he fabricated the evidence and committed perjury in a murder trial in the US.''
Mr Dalyell called for the case against the two Libyans to be heard in the Hague
before a Scottish judge and under Scottish rules of evidence.
However, Home Office Minister of State Jeremy Hanley ruled out a trial for the
Libyan suspects in a third country as ``unacceptable and unworkable''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Historic day is clouded by doubt Clinton's visit a great occasion but will it change anything?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUSSELL EDMUND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126659</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Belfast,
IT will be a day to remember for the people of Northern Ireland but will
anything have really changed when it is over? That is the question which looms
over the historic visit of President Bill Clinton to Belfast and Londonderry.
This morning, Air Force One will touch down at Aldergrove Airport and Mr and
Mrs Clinton will step out into a Province that has never before had a visit
from a serving United States President. The ramifications of 24 hours in
Northern Ireland are central to political stability as well as the prospects of
foreign investment n a part of Europe with an unenviable economic record.
Until the eleventh hour, it appeared the President's day in Northern Ireland
would be clouded by political deadlock. But somehow in the darkness of Tuesday
night, Prime Ministers John Major and John Bruton came to what has been
described as an agreement to differ.
One word dominated political debate yesterday - fudge. Once again, as has
happened in the past, the British and Irish Governments have composed a
document which is far from clear-cut in its meaning and has won both support
and criticism from Unionists and Nationalists alike.
In Belfast yesterday, Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble and the Sinn Fein
president Gerry Adams appeared to have something in common at last. Both shared
a degree of suspicion about what Mr Major and Mr Bruton had produced. Indeed,
of Northern Ireland's five major political parties, only two - the moderate
Alliance and the nationalist SDLP - seem prepared to take a positive,
enthusiastic line.
For most people, however, the fact that anything had been cobbled together in
advance of President Clinton's visit was enough to make today's great occasions
in Belfast and Londonderry all the more memorable.
After 15 months of peace, Mr Clinton will find that Northern Ireland has barely
left base camp in terms of making any political progress towards a permanent
settlement of its divisions. The communique issued this week from Downing
Street is not seen so much as a breakthrough as simply a means of moving a road
block further along the torturous path towards any settlement.
The crucial question of what to do about terrorist arms and explosives remained
unanswered and simply postponed for another day. This week's agreement between
London and Dublin on a way forward looks to be based more on hope than on any
realistic prospect of the log-jam being broken.
The Northern Ireland peace process, which began with the euphoria of IRA and
Loyalist ceasefires, has slowed over the months and is now set in limbo until
well into the new year.
The Unionist demand that IRA weapons be handed over remains unanswered. Sinn
Fein's demand that the British Government sets up round-    table talks is also
set aside.     Instead, the latest Downing Street-Dublin formula offers another
breathing space during which it is hoped such vital issues can be addressed
again.
The Americans' involvement deepens, not only through the President's visit
today, but even more so in the appointment of former Senator George Mitchell to
chair the international body which will examine the decommissioning of
terrorist weapons.
Mr Mitchell has an unenviable task of consulting all the parties about how they
see the decommissioning question and of also producing a report by mid-January
for the British and Irish Governments. Somehow, he has to indicate convincingly
that there is a clear commitment on the part of those in possession of arms,
the IRA and Loyalists, to permanent peaceful means of attaining their political
ends.
Realistically, many people in Ulster are starting to doubt whether arms and
explosives will ever be handed over by terrorists. Indeed, the best London and
Dublin may hope for is that by next year the issue will not loom as large in
the minds of Unionists as it does today and that they may be more willing to
sit down to talks with Sinn Fein.
As of now, there is nothing to suggest that will be the case with Mr Trimble
saying Mr Major and Mr Bruton had failed to deal properly with the arms issue,
and the Rev Ian Paisley even more sweeping in his condemnation.
But, if Unionists are unhappy and suspicious, so too are the followers of Mr
Adams. Yesterday, he, too, expressed his suspicions about the new proposals
which clearly do not meet Sinn Fein's key demand for round-table talks now.
Observers in Belfast feel Mr Adams is under increasing pressure from rank and
file republicans who claim that 15 months of the IRA ceasefire have won
insufficient concessions from the British Government and who threaten a return
to violence if a breakthrough is not achieved soon.
A restraining influence on their tempers must be the attitude of the US and,
significantly, President Clinton is placing great emphasis on getting Sinn Fein
and the IRA to support the new decommissioning approach.
Two hundred years ago, many founding fathers of the US hailed from
Ulster-Scottish origins and carried across the Atlantic the mark of defiant
independence. In Belfast today, Mr Clinton could well feel that history has
come full circle. Despite his plea for peace, he will find that the Ulstermen
of today still have a mind of their own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
