<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126661</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EIS begins
fight against
funding cuts
SCOTLAND'S biggest teachers' union yesterday launched a campaign against
underfunding in education which, it said, was the Number One issue facing
schools, colleges, and universities.
Mr Ronnie Smith, general secretary of the Educational Institute of Scotland,
said the fact that 5000 teachers had signed a petition for a special union
conference about the impact of funding cuts indicated there was growing
resentment about the direction the service was taking.
The meeting, which is to be held next month, is expected to hear calls from the
hard left for the EIS to take industrial action against underfunding generally
or, as seems more likely, to support lecturers facing compulsory redundancy in
further education colleges.
Mr Smith, whose union represents eight out of 10 teachers, further education
lecturers, and academics in the new universities, said resources would be a key
issue in the General Election campaign.
The union said underfunding underpinned many of the problems confronting
education: crumbling schools, bigger class sizes, curriculum innovations,
attending to the individual needs of pupils, and the drive to improve standards.
The EIS said there was growing evidence that teachers were coming under
pressure to take classes with more pupils than the legal limit: 33 from primary
one to second year in the secondary sector; 25 for composite classes comprising
different age groups; 30 for third to sixth years; and 20 for practical
subjects.
However, more teachers were finding themselves on the ``slippery slope'' of
bigger classes because of the greater use of emergency provisions which
increased the limit to up to 39 pupils.
The EIS is commissioning research to establish the scale of underfunding. It
said the new unitary councils would have to find more than #200m in savings,
and #40m for education alone, to maintain services at present levels.
The union predicted that more than 600 teaching posts would disappear in the
current financial year.
Mr Smith has asked Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth whether any of the
additional #878m earmarked for schools in the Budget would come to Scotland.
The Scottish Office Minister for Education, Mr Raymond Robertson, said local
authority current expenditure had been treated very favourably. ``I do not
therefore believe there should be any need for cuts in essential services such
as education as a result of next year's settlement.
``There is undoubtedly some scope to make efficiency savings but if there are
to be cuts in education services, they will be as a result of decisions at the
local-authority level,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greetings from an American cousin</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE President of the most powerful nation on earth spoke unto the Parliament of
a quaint, slightly dotty great-aunt yesterday. He wore a suit; she wore a very
big wig, lots of gold leaf and waved a number of funny sticks about. He spoke
of peace and destiny; she listened politely and offered him tea with the Queen.
By the strict standards of the Clinton White House, the Royal Gallery of the
Palace of Westminster is not a politically correct place. Although smoking is
not permitted, the glorification of dead, white, imperialist males certainly
is.
A panorama scene of the death of Nelson faces a mural of Wellington at
Waterloo. The whole is framed by acres of gilt paper of the Royal Tandoori
Gallery school of interiors.
The strict timetable detailing when to enter, when to stand, and when to blow
trumpets required peers, MPs, and other witnesses to this footnote of history
to turn up an hour before the Clintons .
Most arrived in identifiable batches - out-of-favour Shadow Cabinet,
second-rank Unionists, old Liberal Democrats, young Labour on the make. Those
who arrived singly were either disgraced Tory ex-Ministers, Michael Howard, or
Margaret Ewing, in a painfully obvious yellow jacket.
We stood to allow the Speaker and the Lord Chancellor to advance into the room,
preceded and followed by their various rods, caps, chaplains and other
hangers-on in skirts. We all sat down again, except for Lord Mackay and Miss
Boothroyd, who chatted away about problem students and where to get cheap gold
braid.
A fanfare announced the arrival of the President, escorted by men in tights,
men in anoraks, and the High Keeper of the Saxophone. He was introduced to Mr
Major, which must have puzzled him as only moments before he had emerged from
two hours of meetings with a man who looked suspiciously like the Prime
Minister.
The Lord Chancellor welcomed him and tried to interest him in a cloak and wig
for his Vice-President. Mr Clinton had more selfish ambitions. All that ushing,
rodding and privying of the House of Lords had made an impression. How he
wished the United States could boast a similar institution: ``It might not be a
bad place to be after a long career''.
Out of concern for the sensitivities of our Yankee cousins, the large portrait
of George III has been discreetly hidden behind a photographers' perch. But not
the enormous painting of gorgeous George IV: throughout his address, Mr Clinton
was faced by a man of many mistresses, who inhaled at every opportunity.
Mr Clinton's speech was a reminder of the skill that made his candidacy in 1992
a triumph of style over substance. There was nothing new in what he said, but
my, how he said it.
The generous words flowed, warm and comforting like a sea of stickiest Arkansas
molasses. Mr Major lapped them up, relieved that that awkward misunderstanding
over Tory help for the George Bush campaign three years ago was apparently
forgotten.
Here instead was Mr Clinton praising his management of the Ulster peace process.
Mr Clinton received an enthusiastic sitting ovation. He was thanked by Miss
Boothroyd, who quoted Thomas Jefferson's spine-tingling words of the
Declaration of Independence, that ``all men are created equal'', as a model for
modern democracies. And, with a flick of her gold trim in Hillary's direction,
she added: ``I only have one criticism to address across the centuries to Mr
Jefferson: all men?''
</TEXT>
