<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>President's Irish-American adviser was obvious choice</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126663</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE choice of Mr George Mitchell to chair the International Commission seems,
in hindsight, almost inevitable.
For a start, giving the job of chairing the commission to one of President Bill
Clinton's key advisers ties the White House firmly into the peace process.
There are differences between London and Washington, as the President made
clear yesterday when he refused to back the British position that the IRA must
start to hand over weapons before Sinn Fein can join all party talks.
But that is no surprise and does not mean he will not exert pressure in private
on the IRA and Sinn Fein.
The President, who was energetically reasserting the existence of the special
relationship yesterday when he spoke to both Houses of Parliament, is desperate
for diplomatic triumphs.
Given the strength of the Irish-American vote in the United States, the
temptation to meddle in Northern Ireland has always been overwhelming and his
Irish visit, to Belfast today and Dublin on Friday, was regarded with deep
suspicion in London.
But the agreement announced late on Tuesday by Mr John Major and Irish Prime
Minister John Bruton has changed all that. The President now goes not to meddle
but to urge the case for peace and the international commission. He has
something to ``sell'' which both London and Dublin are behind.
Mr Mitchell's suitability for his new job is beyond question. His personal and
career credentials are impeccable.
He is of Irish origin and a Catholic. His father, who was adopted by a family
called Mitchell, was a Kilroy.
Considered in the US as being ``Irish to the core'', he has vast political and
legal experience.
As President Clinton's special adviser on ``economic initiatives in Ireland'',
he already knows everyone who matters there, is aware of what the problems are,
and has been to see the situation for himself. The learning curve for the new
commission will, therefore, be short.
His appointment should also help silence some of the more militant, and all too
often ignorant, Irish American voices which back the IRA and Sinn Fein
regardless.
The other two members have yet to be appointed but it is pretty clear where the
Government will be looking. What is needed are a former Commonwealth statesman
and a leading European figure, genuine outsiders, probably politicians although
not necessarily, who have an interest in peace in Northern Ireland. The
important thing is that they are not seen as having anything to do with the
British Government.
During his 14 years in the Senate, Mr Mitchell took a deep interest in Irish
affairs and was associated with the so-called Friends of Ireland, although not
so prominently as Senator Edward Kennedy. In December 1993, he was one of the
signatories, along with Senators Kennedy, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and
Clairborne Pell, of a solemn appeal to ``all those who have relied on bullets
and bombs in the past - lay down your arms''.
He also made a point of meeting Irish political leaders as well as
representatives of smaller Irish interest groups, and was a leading supporter
of the American Ireland Fund.
Ironically, while in Belfast earlier this year when he had talks with a
cross-section of political opinion, both Unionist and nationalist, he said he
had no intention of becoming involved in the political aspects of the current
negotiations. In a sense, he now has become involved, because what the
commission achieves is vital to progress.
</TEXT>
