<HEADLINE>Picketing row closes mail office</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126664</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Mail yesterday closed a strike-hit delivery office because of
``unruly and violent'' picketing.
The office at Hamilton is the only one in Scotland where staff remain on strike
after last week's walkouts by 5000 postal workers crippled services.
The other postal workers called off their unofficial action after a peace deal
on Sunday.
Hamilton had been the only office where the strike had been official. However,
the 70 staff there remain out in a local row over a newly promoted line
manager, Mr Gordon Johnson.
As part of the peace deal, union officials at Hamilton claim they were told
that Mr Johnson would be moved. They believe him strongly linked with
management's drive to change working practices and ultimately cut jobs.
When the nightshift arrived for work at midnight on Monday they found Mr
Johnson was still there.
However, if there had been any violence it had to be laid at the door of a
Royal Mail manager who had nearly run over two strikers on the picket line,
according to Mr Tam McHugh, the local representative of the Communication
Workers' Union.
Mr McHugh said: ``Only yesterday one postman was struck by a van driven by a
manager.''
The Royal Mail said it had been forced by picketing to close the office until
further notice.
Mr Alex Gibb, delivery director for Scotland, said: ``The intimidation of staff
and managers who are merely trying to maintain a modicum of service for
customers in extremely difficult circumstances is unacceptable.
``We will no longer be able to open the inquiry office for customers coming in
to collect their mail.''
CWU divisional representative George Robertson said: ``There has been no
violence. This is typical Royal Mail; they are overreacting.''
Meanwhile, Royal Mail chiefs were accused of trying to ``strangle in red tape''
attempts to give short-term loans to postal workers suffering financial
hardship caused by the recent strike.
The CWU claims that a #25,000 benevolent fund run by the workers and management
in East and Central Scotland should be used to pay out cash to struggling
postmen.
Management said any recommendations on pay-outs should be made by experienced
and trained welfare officers who also give debt counselling. It was this
procedure which could cause some delays.
Not delivered 14
</TEXT>
