<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP eyed up men in gay pub, libel case jury is told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER parliamentary reporter saw Tory MP David Ashby eyeing up young men in
a gay pub, a libel case jury heard yesterday.
Mr Andrew Pierce, a journalist from the Times, saw Mr Ashby, 55, in the Queens
Head in Tryon Street, Chelsea, on the evening of December 14, 1991, Mr Richard
Hartley QC, told the High Court in London.
Mr Hartley, for the Sunday Times, said Mr Pierce would say in evidence that Mr
Ashby, MP for North West Leicestershire, was in one of London's ``oldest and
best-known gay pubs'' between 8.30 and 9.30 that night.
His statement included the comment that Mr Ashby was having ``as little success
in the bar as he did in the House''.
Mr Ashby is suing the Sunday Times and its former editor, Mr Andrew Neil, for
libel over an allegation that he was homosexual.
The MP said it was perfectly clear to him from Mr Pierce's statement that the
journalist was a ``particularly cruel and unpleasant man''. He had the
``misfortune'' of having met Mr Pierce last month at the publication party for
Matthew Parris's book, Great Parliamentary Scandals, in which Mr Ashby featured
as a result of the current court case.
The MP said he was in his constituency that Saturday night, having travelled up
to Ravenstone on the Friday and returning on the Sunday.
He denied that he and his wife were leading ``very separate lives'' in 1991 and
that he told her to mind her own business when she asked where he was going.
Mr Hartley produced Mr Ashby's Members' car allowance document - used by MPs to
claim mileage for journeys to their constituencies and back to Westminster -
which he said recorded a claim for a journey by Mr Ashby and his wife from
London to his constituency on the weekend of December 6-9, 1991.
Mr Hartley alleged that not only was this entry false but also the entry for
the following weekend was also false, because Mr Ashby's wife's diary showed
she was abroad for that entire period.
Mr Ashby is claiming damages over a story published in January 1994, which said
he shared a double bed with a man friend during a holiday in Goa in 1993.
He says the article alleged that he was a homosexual who had misled his wife,
Silvana, from whom he is now estranged, about the nature of his sexuality; that
he had lied to the public about having an affair with a Dr Ciaran Kilduff; and
that he was a hypocrite in emphasising the importance of the family in his last
election address.
Times Newspapers and Mr Neil deny libel, although they accept that Mr Ashby did
not holiday with a man in Goa. They assert that he was and is having an affair
with 32-year-old Dr Kilduff.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
