<HEADLINE>News digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Museum in drive
to keep pistols
ABERDEEN University's Marischal Museum is trying to prevent two rare
seventeenth-century Scottish snaphaunce belt pistols being sold abroad.
The museum has raised #76,000 so far towards the price of #88,000. Fine art
dealer Peter Finer, of Shipston-on-Stour, Warwickshire, has put the sale of the
pistols on hold while the museum tries to raise the remaining cash.
Emu venue
A POULTRY farmer is to bring emus to Scotland. The flightless native Australian
birds, along with other exotic species including kiwis and ostriches, are
expected to attract tourists to Collessie Farm Park, in Fife, which is due to
open in spring.
Drugs charges
A MAN has been reported to the procurator-fiscal after cannabis plants were
found at a farm on Islay. Meanwhile, six men have been arrested at a house in
Coatbridge in which controlled drugs were found.
Dry dock plan
A NEW #1.5m dry dock for Macduff harbour is the most expensive item on the new
Aberdeenshire council's wish list for the seven north-east ports.
Church assault
AN 85-YEAR-OLD woman was recovering yesterday after being indecently assaulted
and hit in the face as she knelt to pray in a church at Tooting Bec, south
London.
Girls found
BEST friends Natasha Jones, nine, and Louise Dixon, 10, who went missing in
Leicester on Sunday, were found by police last night. The girls were in good
spirits and were reunited with their parents. Police said a man had been
arrested.
Waste go-ahead
COUNCILLORS in Shetland gave planning permission yesterday for a #17m waste
incinerator and district heating scheme. The council plans to import waste from
Orkney and the offshore oilfields, for burning in Lerwick.
Minister's move
THE Rev.Donald Maclean, 63, Free Church minister at Ardelve, near Kyle, for 14
years, is to be inducted to the charge at Scalpay, in Harris, on December 22.
Tourism boost
THE Scottish Borders Tourist Board announced yesterday that it has been awarded
more than #1.8m in European cash, which is expected to generate more than #10m
worth of visitors' spending over the next four years.
</TEXT>
