<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>President on Parade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126668</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
He first arrived as a student, returned as a Governor, and yesterday visited
Britain as the most powerful man on earth. Elizabeth Buie traces the itinerary
of Bill Clinton as he rubs shoulders with royalty and commoners.
BILL Clinton has returned to Britain many times since his student days at
Oxford, but his first presidential visit was marked by formal pomp and ceremony
and meetings with commoners and the Queen.
The presidential flight, Air Force One, carrying the world's most powerful man,
touched down at Heathrow at 7.05am, marking the beginning of a three-day State
visit to London, Belfast and Dublin.
From then on it was red carpet treatment all the way.
The president's first official duty was the laying of a wreath on the tomb of
the Unknown Soldier, in Westminster Abbey.
To shouts of ``Hi, Bill'' from a group of a dozen American tourists holding up
signs declaring ``We love Clinton'', and ``California loves Clinton'', his
cavalcade swept into the Abbey.
Then, thanks partly to the new-found climate of security engendered by the
peace process, Mr Clinton and Mr Major braved the drizzle to walk from
Westminster Abbey to Downing Street.
They were accompanied by an entourage of around 80 security men, some 100
American journalists, and a horde of British reporters. A helicopter whirred
above them.
As he entered Downing Street, Mr Clinton was met by a crowd of around 300
schoolchildren from three London schools. He shook almost every child's hand.
One onlooker, Colette O'Hart from Ireland, seized the opportunity to ask Mr
Clinton if he planned to play any golf.
``I asked if he was going to Ballybunion in County Kerry to play golf,'' she
said.
``He said he was very sorry and that because of the Bosnian situation, he could
not.''
Shortly before, Mr Clinton had picked out a group of Jubilee Line construction
workers for a chat.
Paul Wydenbach, 28, from Swansea, said: ``I just shouted out `Hi there Bill,
how are you doing' and he came over and shook my hand and said `How are you?'.
He had a good firm handshake as well.''
America's First Lady, Hillary Clinton, met a group of prominent British women
at the US ambassador's residence, among them Education and Employment Secretary
Gillian Shephard and Baroness Tessa Blackstone, the Labour spokeswoman on
foreign affairs in the House of Lords.
In a curiously-worded list of those attending issued by the US Embassy, it was
noted that local government official Sarah Ebanja came from south of the Thames
``where most persons of color live''.
Meanwhile, Mr Clinton was engaged in two hours of intensive talks in Downing
Street, before telling a news conference of his appreciation and admiration for
John Major's courage in taking a ``risk for peace'' in Northern Ireland.
Shortly after midday, Mr Clinton, accompanied by his wife, addressed both
Houses of Parliament in the Royal Gallery of the Palace of Westminster amid
images and reminders of Britain's past power and pageantry. Among the listeners
was the former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
At 2pm, a secret serviceman touched his ear and spoke into his sleeve. The
President of the United States was about to arrive at Buckingham Palace to meet
the Queen.
From a black armour-plated Cadillac limousine, Bill and Hillary Clinton stepped
on to the steps of the Grand Entrance. The Queen and Duke of Edinburgh
exchanged handshakes with their guests.
Originally, the president was to have had lunch at the Palace, but that had to
be cancelled. So it was an ``audience'' in the classical splendour of the 18th
Century Room, with a view over the palace gardens.
The Queen, the Duke of Edinburgh, and the Clintons sat on a settee and chairs
upholstered in matching French silk, overlooked by three-quarter length
portraits of King George III and Queen Charlotte, and paintings by Canaletto
and Gainsborough.
Members of the White House press corps, bussed into the Palace in two coaches,
looked on, snapping pictures and scribbling notes for consumption back home.
By 4pm, it was time to return to politics - this time a meeting with Labour
leader Tony Blair at the US ambassador's residence.
The pair discussed Northern Ireland and Bosnia and the role of ``progressive''
political parties in bringing about change.
Hillary Clinton also met Mr Blair briefly, after reportedly asking to see him.
By evening, the president and his wife had changed into evening dress for a
formal dinner and reception at No 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forecourt war looms as petrol prices pegged</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORISTS in the more populated areas of Scotland could benefit from a petrol
price war which is set to flare with the announcement yesterday that some
retailers plan to hold fuel at pre-Budget prices.
However, as the battle continues to dominate the petrol forecourts in urban
Scotland, it appears that, once again, rural drivers will be the losers as the
3.5p a litre (15.9p a gallon) duty increase imposed by Chancellor Kenneth
Clarke on petrol and diesel will almost certainly become effective in their
area.
Shell, the UK's second largest petrol retailer, confirmed yesterday that it was
setting no time limit on its price freeze. Tesco and Sainsburys said they would
not raise prices until Monday. Asda has also confirmed it will sell off
existing stocks of petrol before deciding on its next move.
Shell, which says it sells unleaded for as little as 48.9p in places, says it
will monitor the reaction of rivals and raise prices only if necessary.
Meanwhile, Esso, the UK's largest petrol retailer with 2100 service stations,
said it would remain competitive with rivals who choose not to implement the
Budget increase.
A spokesman said: ``Where local competing petrol stations throughout the
country keep petrol at pre-Budget prices we will remain competitive with them.''
A spokesman for BP, the third largest petrol retailer in the UK, said it
planned to implement the increased duty at midnight last night but insisted
that its prices would remain competitive.
The Office of Fair Trading confirmed that it had received a complaint from the
Petrol Retailers' Association, which alleged that Esso had acted in a predatory
manner by selling petrol at ``possibly below cost price'' as part of its
Pricewatch campaign in parts of Scotland and north-east England.
The association has expressed fears that Esso's practice could force some
smaller petrol retailers out of business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lothian police find `bug' in HQ</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTHIAN and Borders Police, embarrassed by a break-in at their headquarters
three years ago, yesterday were investigating a listening device found
broadcasting from their control room.
Last night, however - with the incident being described as ``Fettesgate Two'' -
a senior police official said: ``This is not a case of breach of security.''
He denied there was any danger of sensitive material being received by possible
listeners but admitted: ``We are aware of the matter and it is still being
investigated.
``It appears that this could result from part of our own equipment left in the
control room.''
The incident is thought to have been detected earlier this month, with senior
police officials immediately ordering an investigation.
They moved in swiftly to set up the inquiry, following increased surveillance,
installed after a break-in at their headquarters at Fettes when confidential
documents were said to have been stolen.
It was claimed yesterday that police officers had picked up messages from
colleagues in their operations room, where telephone calls were being taken and
radio messages were being relayed.
q.During a murder inquiry interview in Fife several years ago, police launched
a similar investigation, in which it was alleged that details were picked up by
a radio ``ham'' when a police radio was left switched on.
</TEXT>
