<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tip-off `payment for policeman'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126671</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUGS dealer promised to pay a detective thousands of pounds if the policeman
passed on information about him, it was claimed in court yesterday.
The High Court in Aberdeen was told Ronald Cormack offered Constable Neil
Cooper a one-off payment of #4000, plus a further #200 a week.
Mr Cooper, 36, of Springdale Road, Bieldside, denies corruptly accepting #6000
and other unspecified sums of money from Cormack in return for providing him
with police intelligence and movements.
He also denies two charges of defeating the ends of justice, including tipping
off Cormack and an associate, Mr Ian Smith, about police interest in them.
Mr Smith, 32, a former barman, told the court he had been approached by Cormack
to see if he could arrange a meeting with Mr Cooper.
``He wanted Cooper to watch his back, to tell him if there was any mention of
his name at the police station,'' said Mr Smith.
The court has already heard that Cormack was jailed in May for 17 years on
drugs-dealing and firearms charges.
Mr Smith said Mr Cooper agreed to the meeting, and the two were then picked up
by Cormack in his car in Union Street. This was in 1993.
Mr Smith said Cormack asked if Mr Cooper would give him information about his
name being mentioned at police headquarters in connection with drugs activities.
Mr Cooper, he said, asked Cormack how much the information would be worth.
He claimed Cormack replied: ``#4000 and #200 a week.''
He told the court the men agreed the deal and Cormack then gave Cooper a white
plastic carrier bag which Mr Smith thought contained money.
He said later that day Cooper had come to his house and handed him #1100.
``He gave me the money and said, `There you go,' then left. I was expecting
something for setting up the meeting,'' said Mr Smith.
Mr Smith said his involvement as an intermediary came to an end when he failed
to pass on the first payment of #200 to Cooper.
Under cross-examination, Mr Smith admitted he had given Cormack false
information, saying his phone was tapped, claiming it had come from Mr Cooper,
in order to get money.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>President to put pressure on Adams Praise for speech but the serious talking begins today</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126672</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINN Fein leader Gerry Adams will be told by President Clinton in Belfast today
that it is now his turn to take a ``risk for peace''. This follows two hours of
talks with Mr Major yesterday and a combined will to put pressure on the IRA.
The president said in Downing Street yesterday after congratulating Mr Major
and the Irish Premier John Bruton on their new peace initiative: ``My message
to the IRA is that the twin-track process has provided a mechanism for all the
parties honourably now to bring their concerns to the table and be heard. In
the end, peace means peace and we are all going to have to support that.''
Mr Clinton had praised Mr Major and Mr Bruton warmly. ``I can't say enough to
the British people how much I appreciate and admire the Prime Minister in
taking this kind of risk for peace. This is not an easy action for him to take,
not an easy action for Prime Minister Bruton to take.''
The late-night deal struck on Tuesday by Mr Major and Mr Bruton seems to have
caught the Sinn Fein leader off guard.
He complained that he had not been consulted but throughout the day yesterday
he seemed to be softening his attitude after the tripartite solidarity of
London, Washington, and Dublin. He declared that the agreement was a ``fudge''
but added that his party would approach it in a positive way.
There was no sign, however, that he would enter talks with the pre-condition
the IRA must make a start to handing over weapons.
Today in Belfast, the British and Irish Governments are looking to the
President to pressurise Mr Adams.
The excitement for his visit was rising last night, heightened by a bomb alert
which closed part of the street in Belfast where Mr Clinton will stay in the
Europa Hotel tonight.
Army bomb disposal experts were sent in after a passer-by spotted a suspicious
package close to a Shell filling station.
Such excitement aside, Mr Clinton is expected to meet all the party leaders
during his historic visit.
The Ulster Unionists are still deeply suspicious of the deal done with Dublin.
Mr David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, at one point described
Mr Major's behaviour as ``shameful''. The deal meant only that the
decommissioning of arms issue was not resolved but simply delayed. ``The
essential issue is that there must be decommissioning and there will be no
talks with Sinn Fein until that happens.''
Mr Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionist Party, said: ``We
don't want to be packaged along with Sinn Fein in a twin-track process.''
However, there were signs last night that the Ulster Unionists may change their
attitude after the Prime Minister's statement in the Commons. Neither Mr Bruton
nor
himself could make peace in Northern Ireland: only the political leaders there
could do that, he said.
``If the people of Northern Ireland, who have shown great courage, can find a
similar courage in all their political leaders - courage and determination to
banish the old enmities - then I believe, in joining in these discussions, they
can provide a more secure future for Northern Ireland than it has ever known in
the past.''
The Unionists are calling for an election in Ulster for an assembly to
establish democratic authoritity for the various parties in the sure knowledge
that they can out-gun Sinn Fein easily in any vote.
The Prime Minister pleased them in the Commons yesterday by seeming to give
this idea encouragement: ``Negotiating a constitution will not be easy. I am
open minded . . . I can see the advantage for some political parties in this
idea; I can see an elected assembly, not to govern Northern Ireland but to
produce nominees to negotiate constitutional matters for Northern Ireland.''
Throughout the day, Mr Clinton was lavish in his praise for the Prime Minister
and Mr Bruton, who had taken this ``risk for peace'' in agreeing a three-strong
international body headed by US Senator George Mitchell to explore how the
paramilitaries might hand over their weapons and the timing of their doing so.
The twin-track proposal approved by the Irish Parliament yesterday and all
sides in the Commons allows for Sinn Fein to be involved in exploratory talks
while this process is going on. Senator Mitchell is asked to report to both
Governments by mid-February.
Mr Major and Mr Bruton still disagree on a vital point. Mr Major insists that
Sinn Fein cannot be involved in constitutional talks until some significant
move has been taken by the IRA to decommission its explosives and heavy weapons.
The Irish Premier believes this condition is not attainable but the two have
agreed to let the new initiative go forward.
The big risk for Mr Major is that the independent body will come down on
Dublin's side of this argument.
Mr Major insisted yesterday that Senator Mitchell's recommendations were only
advisory.
The president emphasised that the role of the US is to promote peace but not
get involved in detail. ``The United States, whether in the Middle East, Bosnia
or Northern Ireland, is trying to support reasonable peace processes, not to
dictate terms or make decisions.''
Privately, he backs Mr Major's line that the IRA must start to hand over their
guns.
Today in Belfast and later in Dublin, Mr Clinton is nevertheless expected to
tell Mr Adams and his supporters in the Dublin administration that Sinn Fein
must now make up its mind to support this new initiative and impress upon the
IRA that if it fails the blame will fall on them.
The president is known to be impatient with Mr Adams and the IRA since he
defied his own state department and the British Government in granting Mr Adams
a visa for the US and permission to raise funds there again.
Meanwhile, Northern Ireland is bracing itself for chaos today during Mr
Clinton's visit.
Roads will be closed, schools shut, some offices empty for the day, and Belfast
city centre jammed when tens of thousands of people are expected to flock to
the City Hall to watch the president turn on the Christmas tree lights.
A security operation involving almost 3000 members of the RUC and more than 100
American Secret Service agents has been set up to protect Mr Clinton during the
24-hour trip.
</TEXT>
