<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ex-patients endured months of abuse. Refuge shut by campaign of terror</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REFUGE for mentally handicapped people run by the Roman Catholic Church has
been forced to close after a ``campaign of terror'' against residents and
staff, it was claimed yesterday.
Bricks were thrown through refuge windows and residents suffered persistent
physical and verbal abuse, including threats ofrape and stabbing.
All 10 residents of the refuge in Whitelaw Street, Maryhill, Glasgow - who were
rehoused from Lennox Castle Hospital north of Glasgow about five years ago -
have been temporarily accommodated in other parts of the city after the
Archdiocese of Glasgow decided on closure.
The archdiocese, which operates a number of refuges in the city, said residents
and staff had been ``under siege'' for several weeks and were moved for their
own safety last month when the situation became intolerable.
It is believed to be the first incident of its kind in Scotland since the
Government introduced the Care in the Community scheme in the late 1980s.
The archdiocese said yesterday that residents and staff had suffered the
attacks over a six-month period. The refuge was closed on October 10 as the
trouble escalated.
The worst incidents included:
q A knife being pulled on a voluntary worker at the refuge.
q A female member of staff being threatened with rape.
q Residents having stones thrown at them and being called derogatory names
relating to their condition.
q Stones and bricks being hurled through windows.
q A break-in with a sledgehammer to the refuge's office and the back door to
its communal close being kicked in.
A public meeting was called two months ago when church officials and the police
outlined the crisis and urged local residents to support a campaign to stop the
harassment, but to no avail. The archdiocese said police increased their
surveillance of the area after several complaints but it was not aware of
anyone being charged.
Glasgow district councillors were told yesterday that the situation
deteriorated to the extent that two members of staff were required to accompany
one resident to nearby shops.
A full report was ordered by Councillor Madge O'Neill, the authority's housing
convener, who said she wished the unit to remain operational as a care project.
``Otherwise,'' she warned a housing sub-committee yesterday, ``this could have
a snowball effect on projects in other parts of our city. I am not having
that.''
The residents, six women and four men aged between 40 and 60, had all
previously been in long-term institutional care and were discharged from Lennox
Castle to give them the opportunity of living semi-independent lives in the
community. A caretaker provided 24-hour cover at the six-flat complex and seven
other members of staff helped by teaching residents life skills such as cooking
and house-keeping. One flat was used as a communal area and the other five
served as bedsits.
Miss Agnes Malone, the archdiocese's director of social services, said that the
residents had been temporarily rehoused in similar projects in Clydebank and
Pollok after discussions with the district council and Strathclyde region's
social work department.
She added: ``We had no choice but to move them out because the residents and
staff were very frightened and very angry about the appalling way they were
being treated. It is no exaggeration to call it a campaign of terror. They were
literally under siege.
``Even the day the whole management team helped them move out of the flats was
horrendous. We were putting furniture and clothes into vans but they were being
whipped out and thrown on to the street. It was quite unbelievable.''
Scotland's Roman Catholic leader, Cardinal Thomas Winning, said yesterday that
he was shocked and disgusted by the outrage at the refuge.
Strathclyde Police made no comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
