<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU President rethinks comments about outspoken Commissioner. Santer softens view of Kinnock</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126675</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Neil Kinnock was putting on a brave face yesterday after being publicly
denounced for lacking strength of personality by his boss in the European
Commission, Mr Jacques Santer.
Mr Santer's cutting remarks - made at a major news conference in Brussels -
were apparently Mr Kinnock's punishment for stepping out of line last week at a
business seminar in England.
However, in a bizarre about-turn after seeing his comments being reported
throughout Europe, last night Mr Santer issued another statement softening his
remarks. Observers suspect Mr Santer's partial retraction followed a blazing
behind-the-scenes row.
In a speech not made public by his press service until it was leaked to a news
agency, Mr Kinnock said last week he believed the timetable for a European
single currency was unrealistic and that the EU's policy for granting
membership to ex-Communist countries needed revision.
The former Labour leader broke the convention of Commissioners speaking with
one voice on all policies and exposed the deep divisions on the issue which
observers have long suspected exist, despite frequent denials.
The Maastricht timetable for economic and monetary union leading to a single
currency by 1999 is regarded as an immutable truth in the Commission which is
also adamant, in public, that the Community can afford to take in up to 15
economically desperate former Eastern Bloc states early next century.
Before astonished reporters yesterday, the mild-mannered Mr Santer responded to
a question about Mr Kinnock's comments by saying his transport Commissioner was
``not enough of a strong personality'' to win arguments about the single
currency and enlargement.
Mr Santer said: ``I am the one who is entitled to present Commission policy -
that is something which happens in any government in the same fashion. I would
say that it is the Commission which defines policy as a college.
``If there is one member of the same college who hesitates, or continues to
express some scepticism on certain points, I can only say that he may not have
enough of a strong personality to convince his colleagues in the college.''
Mr Santer insisted the timetable for monetary union was irreversible and
predicted there would be a reinforced commitment to enlargement from the Madrid
EU summit next month.
Later, he seemed to have second thoughts about his attack. He issued a formal
statement confirming his opinion that Mr Kinnock had damaged the Commission's
collegiate approach. However, he continued: ``I do not consider, however, that
Neil Kinnock has a weak personality.''
Mr Santer said: ``Clearly, no words of mine should be construed in this way. In
fact, I consider Neil Kinnock as a very active, co-operative, efficient
Commissioner.'' He concluded by saying he looked forward to working with Mr
Kinnock.
The presidential put-down was more pointed than the censure suffered by Sir
Leon Brittan, who stepped out of line on an earlier occasion. His rebuke was
delivered privately after he suggested eastwards enlargement of the EU should
be carried out more quickly than is planned.
In recent times, Mr Santer has had to cope with rebellious behaviour from the
Danish Commissioner, Mrs Ritt Bjerregaard, who kept a diary of her observations
of Commission colleagues - some unflattering - and who had to order its
withdrawal. She was also prevented from accepting royalties.
As Mrs Bjerregaard was making waves, the Commission was trying to brush aside
the effects of a book entitled The Rotten Heart of Europe by Mr Bernard
Connolly, a British Commission official who was later suspended for claiming
monetary union amounted to a Franco-German plot against sterling.
Mr Santer said the Madrid meeting would give the lie to those predicting doom
for the EU and added that the Community should now ``talk less and do more''.
Mr Kinnock's spokesman said last night: ``This matter is now closed.''
q.No name for the proposed single currency has been agreed so far. France is
now alone in wanting it called the Ecu. Spanish premier Felipe Gonzalez
yesterday ruled out an Italian suggestion, made apparently in jest, that it
could be called the franco. The ``Euro'' is still favourite. A decision will be
made in Madrid.
</TEXT>
