<DOCNO>GH951130-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Undrawn swords at least disguise the rust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126677</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
More bite, without a taxing after-taste. Political correspondent Stuart Trotter
chews over Michael Forsyth's argument.
MR Michael Forsyth's thesis underlying the ingenious proposals revealed
yesterday is that in the dire event, as he sees it, of a Labour government
being elected, his plans are better for Scotland than the Labour Party's.
The revamped Grand Committee would be able to legislate, debate, and scrutinise
Scottish Ministers. Do everything the Convention parliament could do except tax
Scots more than the rest of the Kingdom. It could actually do more, he argued.
It could bend the Chancellor of the Exchequer's ear before he decided on the
amount of the block grant that would fund a Scottish parliament and that is
more than the Scottish parliament could do. It could quiz the UK Minister on
how social security policy operates in Scotland.
The Grand Committee could have the UK Prime Minister to speak and be questioned
in its debates. So in some respects, Mr Forsyth was arguing to MPs,
journalists, and the Scottish public, the committee would carry more weight
than the parliament, its activities would range more widely, and its operations
would cost very much less.
Mr Forsyth brandished a weapon which was not so much rusty with disuse as never
drawn from its scabbard. The Commons Standing Orders provided for the setting
up of an English Grand Committee.
If some Scots Labour MPs are saying - and the Secretary of State clearly senses
the possibility of a split here - the wishes of Scottish voters should
determine the actions in Scotland of a Westminster government whoever is in
power, the same must apply for England.
If Mr Blair comes to power with a Commons majority provided by Scots and Welsh
MPs it will not be long before English Tories demand the setting up of the
English Grand Committee. If it had the powers which the Scottish Grand
Committee is criticised for not having, Mr Blair would be unable to rule
England.
He could vote the Tories down but only by using Scots and Welsh votes. That
would precipitate a storm in which the Union would be in danger.
It is implicit in being a unionist, Mr Forsyth argues, that your particular
part of the Union may be governed by a party for which that part did not vote.
That is a consequence of being in a Union.
The Secretary of State also pointed out that the West Lothian question was
entering its seventeenth year unanswered and the Constitutional Convention did
not propose to answer it today. Scots voters may not mind their Westminster MPs
voting on English health, education, and so on without the English Westminster
MPs being able to reciprocate, but English voters could become quite heated
about it.
The Opposition had easy jokes yesterday about the ``travelling circus'' but Mr
Forsyth's statement clearly sharpened the debate about the nature of the Union
and that, he believed, rightly or wrongly, could only be to his advantage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unions in university contracts battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126678</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Robert Gordon University in Aberdeen could become the battleground for a
union attempt to end national negotiations on lecturers' pay and conditions.
The Educational Institute of Scotland, which through its University Lecturers
Association represents the majority of teaching staff at the new universities,
and the white collar union MSF are seeking legal advice on new contracts
proposed for new staff which, they claim, mean a 25% increase in lecturers'
workloads.
The unions demanded yesterday that the university withdraw the contracts which
they claim are being imposed without proper negotiations. They say that if they
do not make a stand at RGU there could be major repercussions for higher
education in Scotland.
``This is the worst contract in any sector in higher education in Scotland or
England,'' Dr Alastair McLeish, EIS RGU branch secretary, said yesterday after
a meeting of its members.
This meeting produced a condemnation of the RGU management ``for its intention
to unilaterally impose contracts for academic staff which have not been
negotiated through the recognised national negotiating machinery''.
The meeting also demanded that the issue of the contracts be suspended and
regretted ``the effect this unilateral action will have on staff morale and
staff retention since the proposed new contract conditions are significantly
worse than those provided both in traditional universities and in the
nationally negotiated contracts in new universities in England''.
The meeting was attended by EIS national official Marian Healy, who said: ``If
we don't make a stand here, Robert Gordon University will have set a pattern
for local negotiations elsewhere.
``It is changing conditions by the back door because it is an untenable
position to have two different types of contract working in an organisation.''
The contracts affect only new staff at the moment but Dr McLeish said
management hoped to get school heads to sign the contracts by next summer and
anyone promoted would have to sign before taking up their new post.
Anyone on a fixed-term contract moving on to a new one also would automatically
have to sign one of the new contracts.
Ms Healy and other union officials will meet university management on Monday
but she urged it to withdraw the contracts in the meantime.
``If they don't withdraw the contracts, we will be hoping to organise a
national campaign to isolate this university,'' she said.
Mr Jim Cowan of the MSF said the new contracts involved meant a 25% increase in
workload during the year including an increase in hours from 32 to 37 a week
and a reduction in holidays from 50 to 30 days.''
RGU said in a statement last night: ``Discussions are on-going concerning
conditions for new staff and proposals will be put to the governors.
``The proposed conditions are comparable to those in the majority of higher
education institutions throughout the UK. The conditions of existing staff will
not be affected by these proposals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
