<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Way clear for Europe to tighten ferry safety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN and other Western European nations are poised to agree tough new safety
standards for roll-on, roll-off ferries operating between their ports, even
though maritime nations worldwide refuse to endorse such a move.
An agreement was reached in London yesterday, at a meeting of the International
Maritime Organisation, to phase out ferries with only one compartment and
modify others to ensure they can remain stable even with two compartments
flooded - a quality that must apply to all new ferries. However, the meeting
could not agree on the stricter safety regulations suggested by an IMO panel in
the wake of the Estonia tragedy which claimed 900 lives last year.
The panel had recommended the fitting of watertight compartment bulkheads to
keep vessels afloat for as long as possible if water entered the car deck. This
would have meant much costly structural work for virtually all ferries and
would have gone far beyond the survivability standards set by the 1990 Safety
of Lives at Sea convention.
Largely because of opposition from Mediterranean ferry operators, who argued
that the conditions they faced did not warrant such drastic action, the IMO
failed to endorse these tougher regulations and merely agreed that all ships,
rather than just those built since 1990, should meet the lesser 1990 standards.
The UK is now set to bring in these stronger stability regulations, thanks to a
regional agreement it has reached with France and other Western European
countries which will be the subject of a separate conference of European and
Scandinavian maritime nations arranged for next week in Stockholm.
This follows an agreement by the UK, together with France, Italy, Spain,
Norway, and Sweden, and accepted by the IMO, that when two, or three, countries
in a region agreed there was a need to have higher standards, they could impose
them.
Mr William O'Neil, IMO director-general, had supported strongly the tougher
standards proposed. These sought to introduce stability and passenger
survivability regulations which would have been met even with 50cm of water on
the car deck.
Despite the failure to have such standards accepted internationally, Mr O'Neil
told a news conference that it had been a quite successful meeting.
q.A key report on ferry safety, being taken to Brussels on Tuesday by East Kent
Euro-MP Mark Watts, arrived late after being held up at Calais by a strike by
French transport workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Argyll group enjoys fruit of brand loyalty</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126680</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE strength of sales in recent weeks at Safeway took the City by surprise
yesterday. Indications are that the combination of the Safeway 2000 strategic
programme and the success of the ABC loyalty card, after an uninspiring start,
are working more quickly than expected. So shares of the Argyll parent rose 7p
to 312p in response.
In the 28 weeks to October 14, sales increased 7.8% in like-for-like terms with
volume accounting for 4.7% of the gain, inflation the remaining 3.1%.
The expectation is that food prices will show this level of increase for the
remainder of the year although an unknown is the volatility of fresh produce
prices. Safeway has been forced to sell bananas at 19p and tomatoes at 27p to
match the competition.
Overall group turnover was little changed but the previous year included 20
uneconomic Presto stores now sold off.
The Scottish operations outperformed the group average despite the impact Tesco
has had on its Wm Low acquisition.
The pre-tax total improved 4% to #214m, while operating margins increased 0.3%
to 6.9% at the pre-interest level. That conceals a fall of 0.2% at Safeway to
6.9% and a 1.1% jump to 7.1% at the 100 or so Presto outlets to boost its
divisional profits 3.7% to #17m.
The Safeway downturn was due to the price competition in fresh produce and
petrol and generally competitive conditions.
Chairman Sir Alistair Grant does not now expect the margin recovery postulated
at the annual meeting in July to occur and it will now be slightly below that
of last year.
Safeway has been successfully targeting the big spenders with its share of the
ABC1 sector laying out more than #40 a shop rising 2.1% to 21.3%. The group
overall market share is just 7.5% although it claims now to be clearly number
three.
The 2000 programme inevitably caused disruption with 4800 jobs going but 7500
being created and with many employees reassigned to new responsibilities. The
store opening programme is currently running at 17 new outlets for this year
and next and there is also a hefty programme of refits. The revitalised stores
have seen sales rise by a fifth over similar refurbishments in 1994.
Self-scanning has been introduced in 24 stores. This means Safeway is world
leader in trials of this development which should speed up the checkout
procedures - only four stores elsewhere in the world are involved. Chief
executive Colin Smith said the preliminary indications had been encouraging.
The interim dividend has been raised 3.8% to to 4.05p.
</TEXT>
