<DOCNO>GH951130-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Video clue to abandoned baby</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE searching for the mother of a new-born baby girl found on the steps of
Glasgow Royal Maternity Hospital in Rottenrow last week, yesterday released
video pictures of the woman they suspect abandoned her.
The baby, named Amy by nurses, was discovered by hospital staff at 4am on
Tuesday, November 21, after they had been alerted by a female caller. The baby
was thought to be only a few hours old.
The video, taken by a private security camera at 3.37am on the same day, shows
a woman carrying a bundle walking up Montrose Street near the hospital.
At 2.01am, the video captured her without the bundle walking along the same
route, apparently checking the surrounding area.
Police do not believe the woman on camera is the baby's mother, considering the
estimated time of birth which doctors put at between one and two hours before
the baby was discovered.
Leading the inquiry, Detective Chief Inspector Nanette Pollock said: ``I do not
think it is the mother herself but I do think it is someone connected with the
mother. She did not look as if she had just given birth.''
She said she wanted to interview the mother before deciding if the law had been
broken but stressed: ``At this point in time, our main aim is to re-unite her
with her baby.''
Ms Pollock described the woman on camera as being in her 40s, medium build and
height, light blonde, collar- length hair, glasses and wearing a strong pink
thigh-length jacket, dark leggings, and white training shoes.
On the same day the baby was found, the hospital received a telephone call from
a woman calling herself Karen who said she was a friend of the baby's mother
and would bring her into the hospital. This did not happen.
A second call was received on Sunday by a woman claiming to be the mother but
she hung up when questioned.
A hospital spokesman confirmed yesterday that the baby, who was well wrapped up
and in good health when found, was ``doing very well'' and would be released
into temporary foster care within the next few days.
Anyone with information should contact Ms Pollock on 0141 532 3000 or
Strathclyde social services on 0141 227 6029.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burns festival hit by more setbacks Dame Kiri pulls out and satellite supper is axed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126682</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTHE troubled Burns International Festival has been hit by a further blow, with
the news that two major events will not now take place.
It had been planned to host the world's biggest Burns Supper on January 25,
with Ayr being linked by satellite to a variety of world centres. That has been
shelved.
Dame Kiri Te Kanawa was to have given an open-air recital next summer for
thousands of fans at Rugby Park, Kilmarnock. Talks with the singer's management
have broken down.
The disclosure that these two key events are now off the agenda comes days
after the management teams of both comedian Billy Connolly and the pop group
Runrig made it clear that they had no agreement with the festival company,
despite claims to the contrary.
It is now certain that Billy Connolly will not be performing, although the
Runrig management team says that the group will take part if certain guarantees
about the Centrum arena being ready can be obtained.
The Centrum poses another problem for the organisers, as they had been led to
understand that Barr Ltd, with a controversial injection of National Lottery
cash, would be ready to fit out the arena in time to take 5000 eager fans for
festival events.
Thus far there has been no such guarantee.
The Herald disclosed in August that the festival was running into difficulties
and that Enterprise Ayrshire was seconding a senior official and PR and
marketing agency Barkers were being brought in to assist festival director John
Struthers and his small team.
Since then, the news has seldom been good and in an unconnected but
embarrassing departure, festival chairman Councillor Eric Rowe left his wife
and family to take up residence with a new partner in Essex.
One glimmer of hope, however, is that Westsound Radio, which has staged the
world's biggest Burns Supper for many years, has agreed to allow the festival
to become associated.
Managing director Joe Campbell said: ``We were approached by the festival after
it became clear that their ambitious and elaborate plans for satellite links
and the like were not going to come off.
``We were delighted to let them have a number of tickets and for them to become
involved in a small way in an event which has become established as the leader
in its field over a number of years.''
It is unlikely there will be any replacement for Dame Kiri, however, and the
festival will continue with what is left of its existing programme.
A festival spokesman said: ``It is true that talks are no longer going on with
Dame Kiri's management, as there were some aspects of the event they were not
satisfied with.
``As far as the Burns Supper is concerned, the logistics became unworkable and
we are happy to be associated with the Westsound event in mid-January.
``It may be that publicity was given to some of our events a little too early
and that is something we will be aware of in future. Many events are in place
and there will be anouncements about others in due course.''
Mr Struthers said: ``Obviously it is a disappointment that two such prestigious
events will not now be part of next year's programme.
``What I would say, however, is that in the coming days and weeks we will be
announcing events which will fill the gaps which have been left by the
unfortunate failure of some events to come to fruition.''
He added: ``In each of the cases there have been logistical and contractual
difficulties involving either the performers or the venues. There was nothing
we could have done to foresee these.
``We are continuing our efforts to ensure that the festival is a success.''
The year-long festival is being staged to mark the bicentenary of the death of
Burns.
It is also expected that before the end of next month, when the festival is due
to begin, sponsors will be identified for festival events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Check-up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n DOROTHY PAUL is among the artists taking part in a charity gala at Glasgow's
Mitchell Theatre tomorrow evening as part of the city's contribution to World
Aids Day. The performance is entitled Touched by Torchsong - In Loving Memory
Of All Departed Friends.
Earlier, at 6.30pm, a memorial service will be held in the Lord Todd Hall,
Strathclyde University.
Organised by the newly formed Strathclyde branch of Body Positive, World Aids
Day celebrates the lives of people affected by the virus, and aims to create
awareness of HIV/Aids.
Tickets for the Torchsong charity gala at #5, and #2.50 for the unwaged, are
available from the Mitchell Theatre or at the usual TicketLink outlets.
Meanwhile in Edinburgh, Crew 2000, the drugs information centre, will be
holding an open day at 32 Cockburn Street, with a variety of events.
n FATHERS who keep in contact with their children after divorce are more likely
to suffer depression than those who no longer keep in touch, according to new
research carried out at Newcastle University. The men saw regular contact as a
continual reminder of failure on their part, says the study reported in the
recent issue of GP, the doctor's weekly magazine.
n AMONG the more unusual people who turn up at hospital casualty departments
are young people crowing like cockerels. For they are the victims of stage
hypnotists who have failed to come out of their hypnotic state.
Doctors called on late at night to deal with such cases are only too well aware
how easily an evening out can turn into a disaster. That's why many would like
to see much tighter control governing stage hypnotists.
It now looks as though their campaign will be successful, as Home Office
experts, following evidence submitted to them by doctors, are recommending that
hypnotism should be licensed and operate under strict guidelines.
They examined case histories from doctors showing what can happen to people who
participate in stage hypnotism and it goes badly wrong. These range from minor
problems like headaches and dizziness to deep-seated psychological problems,
personal injury, and even death.
</TEXT>
