<HEADLINE>Police join classroom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126684</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PIONEERING educational package which will help provide children throughout
Britain with the social skills required to tackle issues like drug abuse and
bullying has been launched in Grampian.
``The Police Box - Learning for Life'' has been jointly developed by Grampian
Police and Grampian region's education department over more than two years and
is attracting interest from all over Britain.
Grampian Police is investing up to #300,000 a year in the programme, which will
help provide young people with the skills to cope with life today, and a number
of officers are undergoing a condensed teacher training course at Aberdeen's
Northern College to help them present it.
Chief Constable Dr Ian Oliver said: ``The philosophy of Grampian Police is
that, whenever possible, an appropriate education is more valuable than
enforcement. The preferred education approach is to develop a well-rounded
individual within society with the skills necessary for living a good and
useful life.
``This is a skills for living package to educate today's children and
tomorrow's responsible adults to be good citizens.
``It incorporates a whole range of skills including how to develop self-esteem
and to handle the problems of peer pressure and a whole range of ideas that are
integrated into the education system.
``It is a long-term investment and a selfish one from our point of view because
it will arguably make our job easier in 10 or 15 years than it would otherwise
be.''
</TEXT>
