<HEADLINE>Company that grew with success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Currie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126685</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Currie reports on a family firm that has grown by using its expertise to
expand into related business areas
ONE of the great strengths of the Scottish commercial base has traditionally
been our ability to identify markets and operate within set parameters, all the
while fine tuning along the way.
In other words, many Scottish companies still provide their clients with
exactly the services they require, rather than establishing themselves in one
field of activity and then drifting off, often ill-prepared, into others.
Which is why we still have a very high proportion of successful concerns
controlled by the families who founded them, who can offer the expertise and
experience lacking in those operating on a broader canvas.
One such business is John Gardiner Environmental Services Limited, of Larkhall,
Lanarkshire, which also operates from offices in Edinburgh and Wakefield, West
Yorkshire.
Earlier this year it was assessed and registered by National Quality Assurance
Limited against the provisions of BS EN ISO 9002 and the Certificate of
Registration is now displayed in the company's headquarters in Broadway House,
after being presented to Gardiners by Dr Morton Fyfe, the deacon convener at
the Trades House of Glasgow.
Now recognised as one of the country's leading authorities in several complex
activities, including asbestos removal and encapsulating, the company was
formed in 1952.
That was when Mr L J Broadway bought an existing Hamilton-based haulage firm,
John Gardiner (Contractors) Limited.
Its principal field of operation was switched from haulage to civil
engineering, and this formed the core of the business from 1953 to 1985,
providing the base from which to launch its asbestos removal and re-insulation
divisions over 20 years ago.
From fairly small beginnings, this side of the business has grown to the extent
that the company now covers an area from Orkney to Somerset, with the
occasional flying diversions to the outer Western Isles.
Mr L J Broadway and Ms L D Broadway acted as managing director and company
secretary until they retired a few years ago, although their interest is
maintained in the roles of consultant and company director.
The present managing director is Anthony J W Broadway and his wife, Sandra
Broadway, has taken over as company secretary. Mrs Broadway's sister, Sheena
McCallum, is office administrator, so if anything, the family influence is
stronger than ever.
``Our activities now take in a number of related activities,'' said Anthony
Broadway. ``We handle asbestos removal and encapsulating, asbestos cement sheet
roofing, thermal/acoustic insulation, fire protection, cold stores,
contaminated land clearance, environmental cleaning of ducting and water
treatment.
``On the fire stopping side, our men are specially trained to deal with both
new build projects and the restoration of older properties, nowadays a vitally
important aspect of industry.
``Clearing and restoring contaminated land sites is also an area where
experience is essential, and our role is to remove the contamination to an
approved tip and safely reclaim the original land area, using a bottoming of
blaes and then a topsoil surface.''
On the asbestos removal aspect the company has been handling material on behalf
of local authorities, health boards and the private sector since 1976.
Clients have included the Royal Bank of Scotland, British Home Stores,
Lanarkshire Health Board, hotels (including the Balmoral, Edinburgh), and the
Royal Mail in Orkney.
This type of contract generally involves the removal of old asbestos insulation
and its replacement with newer, safe materials.
It has been some time since the problems with asbestos were first recognised
and steps taken to deal with it, but there is still a lot of it about, said Mr
Broadway. After all, it took a couple of hundred years to put it all in.
``Our move into this field has come about as a result of the expertise gained
over the years in dealing with asbestos, supplying and installing alternative
products is a natural progression,'' said Mr Broadway.
</TEXT>
