<DOCNO>GH951130-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Please don't eat your heart out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dr David Delvin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126686</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Q. WHAT actually should a man's cholesterol be?
I was in America this summer and had my level checked by a doctor there. She
said it was a bit up. But when I came back to Scotland and saw my GP, he did it
again and said that at 5.2 it was ``perfectly okay''.
So what are the facts?
A. As I'm sure you know, the level of blood cholesterol is very important -
because high figures are associated with heart disease.
But doctors differ a bit on what exactly constitutes ``high''. An additional
source of misunderstanding is the fact that the Americans use a totally
different system of units from ourselves.
However, in the UK there's general agreement that if your level's anything more
than about five units, then you should at least have a chat with your doc about
it, and consider modifying your lifestyle.
Being a bit more specific, a leading Glasgow physician has just issued these
very useful ``cholesterol guidelines'':
q Fewer than 5.2 units: no action needed.
q 5.2 to 7.8 units: consider cholesterol-lowering diet or treatment, depending
on whether there are any other risk factors for heart disease.
q More than 7.8 units: definitely see hospital specialist.
Q. TO settle an argument, can you tell me this: does a man really need to wash
his ``personal parts'' every day?
A. It's certainly a good idea - partly because of the fact that carcinoma of
the penis (which generally develops under the foreskin) is almost entirely seen
among those who haven't made a habit of washing themselves regularly.
Q. WHAT'S a healthy blood pressure for a young man, please? I had mine done at
a sports clinic, and it was 120 over 70. Is that good?
A. Yes, it's fine. I'll be explaining a bit more about blood pressure in a
couple of weeks' time, but in a young chap the first figure shouldn't be much
more than about (100 + your age in years).
And for teenagers and young adults, the second figure shouldn't be more than
about 80. So you're fine.
Q. I'M only a modest drinker, but I'm having a wee bit of trouble with my
waistline. To what extent does alcohol actually put on weight?
A. It's quite a significant factor, because it contains a lot of calories.
There are three main classes of foods; carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.
Carbohydrates and proteins aren't very fattening, because they contain only
about four calories per gramme. Fat (as the name implies) is very fattening
indeed, because it has more than nine calories per gramme.
Alcohol has around seven calories per gramme. So you can see immediately that
it's nearly as bad as fat when you're trying to shift a bit of weight!
Q. CAN you put my mind at rest, doctor? I'm a salesman, travelling a lot. Last
week, in a bout of stupidity fuelled by alcohol, I had a ``one-night stand''
with a young lady who I met at a hotel in the West Highlands.
At least I had the sense to use a condom. But I am frightened by the idea that
I might have caught HIV. Should I go for a blood test?
A. Well, I think that - like many men - you've probably over-estimated the risk
of HIV for heterosexual people in Scotland.
The early publicity about Aids which was put out by the authorities was, of
course, well meaning, but it did give the impression that the danger of getting
HIV from ``straight'' sex was very high. Thank heavens, that just isn't so - at
least, not yet!
Admittedly, there are a few very small areas of the country - like those
infamous drug-ridden estates, I'm afraid - where having casual sex would be
very dodgy indeed. But if you look at the national statistics, the truth is
that the number of Scotswomen who have ever been found to be HIV positive is
fewer than 600.
This means that the proportion of known HIV-positive females in Scotland is
round about one in every 4500. When you compare this with other countries,
that's a remarkably low level. There are all sorts of reasons why it's low -
one of them being Scotland's relative ``insulation'' from the Continent, where
Aids rates can be frighteningly high these days.
Anyway, the point is that an unwise spot of ``hochmagandy'' in rural Scotland
is at present very unlikely to lead to HIV transmission - particularly when (as
in your case) a condom is used.
Nevertheless, if you want a reassuring blood test then go ahead and have it.
But there's no point in doing it for three months - because the test does not
become positive immediately.
Q. FOR some time I have felt that my career would go better if I could
``ditch'' my spectacles and get myself some contact lenses. But are there any
risks in wearing them?
A. Absolutely! I speak as a contact lens wearer of some 30 years' standing -
during which time I've had quite a few minor complications (like
conjunctivitis) myself.
What many people don't realise is that occasionally contact lens wearing can
lead to really serious trouble, like devastating eye infection. I'm sorry to
say that in my experience, some contact lens practitioners don't draw
sufficient attention to these dangers.
In particular, users of soft contact lenses aren't always warned that they are
at risk of a vicious little parasite called acanthamoeba. Acanthamoeba lives in
water - including, slightly unbelievably, tap water - and if it gets on to
lenses it can cause appalling eye damage.
If you genuinely feel that ``contacts'' would benefit your career, my advice is
to go ahead. But please make sure that you understand the risks first. And
follow your practitioner's instruction about cleaning and disinfecting the
lenses to the letter. Your sight may depend on it.
Q. SAD to say, I am beginning to go pretty bald. I have some money saved up,
and I really wonder whether it would be worth lashing out on a hair transplant.
What do you think?
A. You'd be saying goodbye to several thousand pounds. And I'm afraid you'd
have no guarantee that the transplant would be successful.
The usual procedure in ``male pattern baldness'' is to remove hair from the
back of the head, and to try to ``implant'' it across the bald scalp at the
front. This is moderately painful, and there's also a fairly small risk of
bleeding or infection.
The big gamble is whether the implants will ``take'' or not. You will not get
your money back if they don't. So only go ahead if it's money that you can well
afford to lose.
n If you have a query about your health, write to Dr David Delvin at The
Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow G1 1QP. Dr D cannot reply in person, but
will try to respond in this column. Your name will not be published.
</TEXT>
