<DOCNO>GH951130-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Loan company report received with interest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126687</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALWAYS look, as they say, on the bright side. Such at least would appear to be
the philosophical attitude adopted by the Student Loans Company, that asset to
Glasgow's Bothwell Street, in the face of adversity.
Writing in the firm's annual report, chairman Kenneth Young says: ``1994/95 was
in many respects a successful year for the company but . . .'' - ``but''? -
``there were also serious problems'' - oh, yes? - ``arising from a new system
for second and subsequent loan applications'' - dear, dear - ``and from an
investigation into alleged impropriety in earlier years within the company.''
Ah.
To wit: ``A full independent investigation, as a result of which it became
necessary, inter alia, to dismiss the chief executive and secure his
resignation as a director.''
If this is what Mr Young calls ``in many respects a successful year'' we await
a bad one with any amount of trepidation.
Technical note: of the 147,459 ``customers'' in hock to the Student Loans
Company for the sake of their educations, 10% were in arrears on their
repayments last year. Directors' remuneration rose between 1994 and 1995,
meanwhile, from #111,000 to #226,000.
Slick operator
ANOTHER example of rose-tinted (or perhaps green-tinted) optimism arrives with
the annual report from Greenpeace, the environmental action group which gave
Shell such bother over the Brent Spar oil storage platform earlier in the year.
Giving his account of events, Peter Melchet, executive director, recalls
Greenpeace's action as ``a logistical masterpiece'', that ``outwitted and
outnerved Shell''.
Melchet was, meanwhile, ``personally shocked'' (yes, personally) by press
reactions to the fact that Greenpeace was completely wrong in claiming that the
Spar was toxic. ``No-one'', he adds gnomically, ``said that breaking into the
establishment would be easy . . .''
The TV companies who believe they were spun an environmentally-friendly line in
Greenpeace-supplied footage of the dispute might just agree with that.
Heart of gold
A TALE to warm the heart, sort of. Residents at the Edinburgh Nursing Home in
the east of the city were more than a little upset when, in the early hours of
Tuesday, two masked intruders broke in looking for drugs but made off with
#1000 which had been set aside to pay for the old folk's Christmas party and a
trip to the panto.
``When I heard about what had happened,'' said Mr Tommy Robertson, ``I couldn't
bear to think of those old folks having their Christmas taken away from them.''
He added: ``I wanted to prove that there is goodness in the world at
Christmas.''
For the record, Mr Robertson, of The Hatman Karaoke, is known as a ``karaoke
king''. While convinced that the old folks have suffered enough, he intends to
dress up as Santa Claus, serenade them, and put ``a smile'' back on their
faces. The sooner someone stops this crime wave, we feel, the better.
Just to complete the treat, residents have been invited to lunch at Hibs
football ground. The Diary understands there is no obligation to watch the
team. One turkey is enough for anyone.
Radio revolution
FROM Shanghai comes the latest news of Brian Anderson, the man, you may just
remember, who back in 1988 launched himself on the airwaves of China from a
cottage in Cawdor. No, it's true.
To be strictly accurate, Anderson asked the Chinese government if it needed
some shows for state radio, bought the air-time, and returned to the Highlands
to put together a demo Chinese ``prog'', as irritating radio types might say,
with a Chinese student supplying the chatter between the songs.
Since then, the huddled masses yearning to be Madonna haven't been able to get
enough of Anderson's output of politically uncontroversial from the likes of
the Carpenters and the Beatles (``Revolution'', comrade?).
The Man from Cawdor, aided by his wife, Maggie, now produces 25 hours of
material a week to 10 cities, including Beijing, Shanghai itself, and Wuhan.
Such is his popularity, indeed, that he even has his own, self-invented
catchphrase. We don't know how it sounds in Mandarin, but in English the snappy
slogan is, ``It's the fool from Britain, Brian Anderson, and Maggie!''
Somehow, we judge, he's nobody's fool.
All red-letter days
WE COME across an advertisement for a product celebrating yet another glorious
moment in Scotland's story. ``April 1996 is the 250th anniversary of the Battle
of Culloden,'' it says, as the heart sinks, ``and this splendid calendar
depicts in glorious full colour 12 of the estimated 33 clans who fought for
Bonnie Prince Charlie.''
Something to hang on the wall, then: January - slaughter; February - genocide;
March - annihilation; April - wipe-out; May - abject defeat . . .
Exemption to
the yule
SOMEONE's not in the mood. From the classified ads of the Inverness Courier:
``7ft Tulsa pine luxury artificial Christmas tree, boxed, brand new, #25.''
Cheaper nonsense
STILL with Christmas, the PNC Bank of Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, has just
released its annual Christmas Price Index. This is a modern price guide for
anyone who actually wants to saddle their true love with all the items
mentioned in The 12 Days of Christmas - partridges, pear trees, and so forth.
Encouragingly, the price of nonsense is going down, with the whole shooting
match - 12 partridges, 36 calling birds, 24 turtle doves, and so forth -
setting you back a modest $51,764.94. Allegedly, this is a 29.4% drop compared
with last year.
What we still can't work out is how anyone arrived at an hourly rate of $34 for
eight maids a-milking (cows not included).
JAMES WESTRAN has ``been cleared at Stranraer Sheriff Court of stealing 120
dozen eggs from a shed at Broadstone Road, Stranraer, on March 15 or 16 while
acting with another person'' (Galloway Gazette).
No, police still haven't cracked the case.
Fuel for thought
WASTE not, want not: the Holy Cross Lutheran Church in Kalmar, Sweden, has
applied for a permit to connect the crematorium in its memorial park with its
other buildings. The church wants to use the cheap, indeed free, heat from the
crematorium to warm the other places the spirit may not reach.
Thought for the day
LOOK at it this way: isn't it just as well the Royal Mail strike ended before
someone called for a postal ballot?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wait till egos have landed on Labour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126688</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS hate-figures of the Conservative Party go I reckon Jeremy Paxman of
Newsnight and the entire Radio Four Today team would be much higher on the hit
list than, say, John Prescott and certainly Tony Blair. My lot are absolutely
convinced they receive the rawest of deals from the media.
There is, if Mr Soames will forgive me, a hint of paranoia about this feeling,
though it is not entirely unjustified. I am amused at the chorus of complaints
about the Budget, many of them born out of the fact that the Chancellor refused
to follow the course which had been charted for him by the ``experts''.
As a small example I put forward the interrogation on television by John
Humphrys of Ian Lang last Sunday. Mr Humphrys was seized of the idea that Ken
Clarke was about to steal Labour's clothes and install a windfall tax.
In vain did Mr Lang try calmly to suggest that this was most unlikely; the hare
had been set to run and we even had Gordon Brown rubbing his hands not exactly
in glee, that is a word which will never apply to the Shadow Chancellor, but in
anticipation of being able to say ``I told you so''.
It never happened, of course, but why let the facts spoil a good story? I
suspect there were two sets of headlines ready for the moment Mr Clarke sat
down on Tuesday. One lot would have accused him of threatening the economic
life of the country by cutting tax and public expenditure too severely, the
alternative was to cry that he had done too little, too late. We live in a win,
lose world, subtlety is not to be applauded.
Yet for all that I do not subscribe to the theory that the media is
fundamentally biased against the Tories. The egos of Jeremy, John, and Jim are
far bigger than any one party.
They would like a change of government, mainly because they are fed up with the
old faces. They would like a new set of politicians to ridicule. If and when
the Blair boy comes to power they will turn on him and his ilk like hounds to
the fox.
That's healthy, though, surely? In a lively democracy you need those who will
not take politicians at face value, who are ready to chide, to challenge, to
put the view of the ordinary man in the street. We do not wish to return to the
days of ``is there anything you would like to tell us, Minister?'' Of course
not. Yet we should remember that most of the big stars of air and screen are as
far removed from ordinary people as those whom they question.
Instead of Peter Snow dancing around with his graphics telling us what the
Budget will mean to this family or that, would it not be more interesting for
him to tell us how it affects him. After all, do we not pay his wages?
I just worry a wee bit when the interviewers become more important than their
subjects. Mr David Dimbleby: ``Will you allow me to finish my questions and I
will allow you to answer?'' This to the Deputy Prime Minister. A little
humility might go a long way.
For my part I always thought it totally unlikely that the Chancellor would
produce a gimmicky, electioneering budget - that is not the nature of the man.
Mr Clarke is thoroughly disliked by the starry-eyed right for the very reason
that he does not accept their simplistic notion that everything comes down to
tax cuts. Good governments have to protect the services as well.
Nor do I believe that elections are won by Budgets though they can help to
instil confidence. As for this one I, for once, agree with the assessment of
Norman Lamont when he says: ``It is an honest Budget that a Labour Chancellor
could not deliver.''
I will do what Peter Snow failed to and tell you how the Budget affects me and
those I care about. If my calculations are right, and the maths master did
suggest I miss the exam for the sake of the school's reputation, I expect to be
about #8 a week better off.
This is not a fortune, nor is it to be sneezed at. I shall most certainly enjoy
the cheaper spirits.
But what I am most pleased about is the better deal for elderly people. I
represent the ward with the highest concentration of pensioners than any other
in the city of Edinburgh.
Many of them are worried about having to go into long-term care, and losing the
assets they have so carefully saved with the intention of passing them on to
their families. Until this Budget those who had more than #8000 received no
financial support from the Government.
Now that the upper threshold has been raised to #16,000 and the Inland Revenue
is to be consulted on the possibility of extending the option to take a
variable pension to members of occupational pension schemes. These are
important measures; they are also good politics.
The Conservative Party must never alienate the grey vote. What is required to
retain their support and regain that of the middle classes is not huge
hand-outs, it is reassurance that their lives can be planned with some kind of
order . . . not so much feel-good as feel-safe. The Chancellor must travel
further down this road, and he knows it.
Of course, if we listen to the pundits, the forecasters, and the sound-biters,
the game is over before the whistle blows. This Government, declared that
famous old Highland dancer Lord Healy, is the most unpopular in history and
cannot now recover. It is a recurring theme and, if repeated often enough, may
even come to pass.
In that case, as I watch Mr Blair pout, point, and postulate without saying a
damned thing, I look forward to the day he falls under the arch of Jeremy's
eyebrows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
