<DOCNO>GH951130-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Areas of interest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Currie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126689</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Gardiner Environmental Services Limited is actively involved in water
treatment, cold stores, and thermal/acoustic insulation.
Some of these terms may seem a little vague, but basically water treatment
takes in everything from the prevention of scale and corrosion in steam boilers
right through to bacteriological protection of cooling and air conditioning
plant, Legionella monitoring in all types of water-based systems and the
sterilisation of domestic hot and cold water services to British Standards.
On the thermal/ acoustic insulation front, work undertaken can include a
complete insulation service and on-site surveys. Pipe sections, valve covers,
flanges, slabs, trace heating, cylinder covers and colour/flow direction coding
are just a few of the things that are dealt with on a day to day basis.
The company can also construct cold stores and blast freezers in either
traditional in-site construction or composite panel construction.
Ancillaries, such as shelving, heater tapes, automatic release and security
locks are all part of the package, as are repairs to existing units.
To be able to respond quickly to  any of these matters, an Edinburgh base was
established under managers Stuart Cowan and Gordon Thomson. Dave Nixon is
contracts manager at Larkhall and Robert Wallace acts as water treatment
manager.
``We have a solid nucleus of staff who are largely skilled tradesmen in their
own right,'' said Anthony Broadway.
Sheena McCallum, aware of the importance of establishing uniform standards in a
business that was growing and operating in a highly technical environment, was
given the job of putting everything in place for the drive towards ISO 9002.
"With the help of an outside consultant we put the systems in place and were
then left with the homework," she said. "The workforce recognised the
importance of it all and were extremely co-operative. They worked very hard to
get it in the first instance and will do the same to maintain it."
</TEXT>
