<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man held after gun incidents</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 28-YEAR-OLD man has been arrested following alleged shooting incidents in
Edinburgh and Dunfermline in which two men were injured, one seriously.
Mr Alexander Telford, 56, was in a serious but stable condition in Edinburgh
Royal Infirmary last night after a firearms incident at his home in Greendykes
Road, Edinburgh, on Tuesday night.
Another man received hospital treatment for a minor groin injury after the
Dunfermline incident at a flat in William Street early yesterday.
Fife Police said the 28-year-old would appear at Dunfermline Sheriff Court
today following the Dunfermline incident. A report had been sent to the
procurator-fiscal.
Lothian and Borders Police said the man also had been arrested in connection
with the Edinburgh incident and that a report was being prepared for the fiscal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Untying a terrible knot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jimmy Reid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126691</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE'VE been married now for 37 years and it don't seem a day too much, but,
before some of you out there start counting on your fingers, trying to work out
my age, let me tell you that when we were wedded I was 13. My birth certificate
had been altered to make it appear the groom was seven years older. I was
physically precocious and had been shaving since the age of nine. I looked the
part. That's my story.
Now you might find all this hard to believe but clock the coupon at the top of
this column. It's the face of a man who'll never see 30 again, but just. OK,
it's a free country and you can dispute everything else but the 37 years of
marriage is beyond challenge. There were plenty of witnesses to our getting
hitched in the sheriff's office at Dalmuir on the 9/8/58. Witnesses with a
thirst the size of the Grand Canyon.
We ran out of drink at the reception in the Masonic Hall, Clydebank which had a
gripping atmosphere, and had to send for a carry out from the nearest off
licence. The three-piece band was symmetrically composed of three local shop
stewards who played all the time in the key of C and knew only one song - Hey
Jock McCuddy. Their tango to that tune was memorable, so were many other things
that day.
When the best man, my brother John, declared the bar open my teetotal relatives
were trampled underfoot in the stampede by my wife's aunts and uncles,
particularly the aunts. You're being told all this so that you may understand
that my attitude to divorce is somewhat academic, more or less, and more less
if my betrothed continues to rubbish my viewing of Italian Serie A football on
a Sunday afternoon, with asinine comments about 22 men tearing up the grass
with studs on their feet and bolts in their necks.
So it is unlikely, to say the least, that we will ever seek a divorce, but I
can understand others, locked in a marriage that isn't working at any level,
rightly seeking release from what can otherwise only be called, a life
sentence. I find it difficult to understand people who have no need of divorce
for themselves denying others that right. In fact I deny the right of a
majority to deny a minority this right.
Democracy is more than majority rule. In a healthy democracy minorities have
rights. During the darkest days of Stormont rule in Ulster, Catholics were
treated like second class citizens. This repression was spuriously justified by
the principle of majority rule.
Last Friday in the Irish Republic there was a referendum on whether divorce
should be a legal right for those whose marriages had irretrievably broken
down. The All Ireland Roman Catholic Church campaigned for a No vote. The Pope
and Mother Theresa joined in.
A Yes vote didn't mean that Catholic couples would be compelled by the state to
get a divorce, but a No vote meant that all Irish citizens, whatever their
beliefs, could not get a divorce. It is not the function of a state to legally
impose the teachings of a church, any church, on its citizens.
The question of divorce and Catholicism is a matter between the Church and its
members. If the Roman Catholic Church cannot persuade its members of the moral
validity of its teachings then a democratic state, worthy of the name, must not
impose these teachings by force of law.
Then there are the rights of non-Catholics in Ireland. That they should be
denied the right to a divorce, or to family planning, because a church to which
they do not belong dominated the politics of the country, and framed laws to
enshrine their teachings, and nobody else's, was a disgrace. As bad as the
worst ravages of Protestant sectarianism in the North, where home rule was seen
as Rome rule, a claim which had more than a ring of truth.
The failure to disentangle Church and state tarnished the Irish Republic,
subverted its politics, and gradually undermined the authority of the Church
itself. It played into the hands of Ulster Unionism. Devalued the democratic
credentials of Irish Republicanism, and was certainly not the Ireland for which
James Connolly died.
To their everlasting credit a majority of Ireland's citizens voted last Friday
for divorce, not for themselves, but for those who have to decide for
themselves whether to escape from a relationship, which, for all we know, might
be a living hell.
In almost every case where religion or a church has dominated the politics of a
state the consequences have been damnable. Look at those countries in thrall to
Islamic extremism, or to Menachem Begin's Israel.
I will never forget when Calmac first decided to run ferries during the summer
months to the Outer Hebrides. The first cars and buses to land on an island
dominated by some branch of the Wee Frees were confronted by a minister lying
in their path, with rimless glasses, thin lips, and the expression of a man
totally inaccessible to the reasoning or arguments of others.
There was a large photograph of him all over the front page of a Scottish
newspaper. He looked like Lavrenti Beri, the man in charge of the KGB at the
height of Stalin's reign of terror. In fact the analogy is worth exploring.
Leninism was not a political philosophy, in any real sense, but a secular
religion with its own dogma, high priests, and inquisitions. Stalin was
educated in a Russian Orthodox seminary and was an apprentice priest. He
swapped dogmas.
When Lenin died he was made a god, ensconced at the top of a pantheon of
Bolshevik saint and angels. His mausoleum is essentially a shrine reeking with
religiosity. Edwin Muir many moons go even wrote an essay on the theological
and philosophical connection between Scottish Calvinism and Scottish communism.
Harry Pollitt once told me that Willie Gallagher, the bravest of the Red
Clydesiders, was always destined to be either a communist revolutionary, or a
Calvinist minister. Harry's comment itself had a certain resonance of Calvinist
predestination.
I think the lesson of history is that the running of secular society is best
left to those who have principles, and a moral code, but minds still open to
the possibility of being wrong. There is something else it teaches. The one
thing worse than a religion that wants to be a political power is a political
party that wants to be a religious power. God save us from both.
</TEXT>
