<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mortgage battle breaks out among lenders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE, City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126692</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S biggest building society, the Halifax, yesterday triggered a flurry
of activity in the mortgage market when it announced it was cutting its
variable rate mortgage by 0.25 points from 7.99% to 7.74% while removing
cashbacks for new customers in a move to benefit existing borrowers.
Other lenders soon leapt on the bandwagon, Abbey National almost immediately
announcing a reduction of 0.2% in its variable rates ``in anticipation of a
0.5% base rate cut'', while the Nationwide Building Society reduced its rate by
0.3 points to 7.65%.
Bradford &amp; Bingley said it would at least match the Halifax's move, and the
Woolwich said it would it would review its rates to make sure it remained
competitive. Britannia Building Society sliced 0.25% off its rate from 7.99% to
7.74%, matching the Halifax, while Northern Rock cut its by 0.4% to 7.59%.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke did nothing specific in the Budget to help the
housing market, despite many calls from the industry for him to do so. Except
for any boost that might be provided by tax cuts and the prospect of a base
rate reduction, now expected either next month when he and the Governor of the
Bank of England meet on December 13 or early next year, there was no artificial
boost for housing.
But since potential borrowers might have been holding off ahead of the Budget
in the hope he would cut stamp duty, lending could bounce anyway over the next
few months.
The mortgage war between the lenders which has now broken out could provide a
fillip to a currently moribund market, and this would also be of help to the
Chancellor.
On the downside, though, it means savers are likely to see some reduction in
their income so margins in the industry are not squeezed too hard. This, of
course, is the usual corollary of lower mortgages - savers, many of them
retired and dependent on income from their savings, have to pick up the tag.
Reductions in the past after the progressive fall in lending rates resulted in
many of them shifting their savings to areas where they could earn more of a
return, such as relatively high yielding PEPs, despite the risk factor.
Mike Blackburn, chief executive of the Halifax, said: ``We want to help
existing borrowers and home buyers. With the housing market poised for an
upturn and combined with tax cuts from the Budget, this measure will help to
encourage a sustained recovery.
``The current trend of interest rates is downward and we believe that when it
is possible to do so, we should pass on lower rates to our customers.''
The Halifax move reduces monthly payments on a #30,000 repayment mortgage by
#4.07 to #206.45; a #50,000 loan falls #15.67 to #352.68, and a #100,000 loan
#15.67 to #734.37. On an endowment or other interest-only mortgage, reductions
are #5.32 to #164.48 on a #30,000 loan, #9.49 to #293.48 on a #50,000 mortgage
and #19.91 to #615.98 on a #100,000 mortgage.
No move has been made yet on returns to savers, but Abbey National said that in
making its decision, it had to balance the needs of its 10 million savers.
``Savings rates will have to come down as well but we do not want to bring them
down any more than necessary,'' Charlie Toner, managing director retail, said.
In most cases the reductions will come into effect immediately for new
borrowers and on January 1 for existing ones, though some will have to wait
until February.
</TEXT>
