<DOCNO>GH951130-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mums-to-be are put in the picture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Judy Mackie, Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126694</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Judy Mackie reveals how a hospital gives a touch of assurance on pre-natal
care, while Ann Shaw finds that a Glasgow research initiative could save
babies' lives
PREGNANT women waiting for ultrasound scans at Aberdeen Maternity Hospital can
now put their fingers right on the pulse of pre-natal care, thanks to a new
multimedia marvel.
Instead of flicking through magazines in the waiting-room, women and their
partners can discover all they need to know about ultrasound scanning,
pre-natal tests - and even meet the hospital staff - simply by touching a
screen.
The interactive multimedia touchscreen is the first of its kind in Britain,
using full motion digital video and sound to answer the thousand-and-one
questions pregnant women - especially first-time mothers - have about their
unborn baby's health.
A joint initiative by Aberdeen Royal Hospitals Trust and Aberdeen University,
the touchscreen is being piloted in the ultrasound department at the request of
Dr Pat Smith and her colleagues.
``We found that a lot of women were coming for scans with no idea what was
ahead of them, or why they were being carried out. Many did not realise that
scanning can pick up problems. The touchscreen is an ideal way to give them
easy-to-digest information in advance,'' she says.
``It's not designed to replace staff, but to complement our services by giving
women and their partners a basis for asking further questions.''
With the colourful new touchscreen, waiting suddenly becomes a pleasant
pastime, as its wealth of information appears at your fingertips. A basic menu,
which includes "meet the staff", "scans", "blood tests", "some problems", and
"your baby", leads the viewer down a multitude of paths, introducing clips of
individual staff, who tell you about their job; explaining the different types
of scans offered at different stages of pregnancy; giving information about
amniocentesis and other blood tests; outlining possible problems which may be
picked up (while reassuring that these are in the minority), and showing
detailed ultrasound pictures of the baby in the womb, with close-ups of its
face and vital organs.
Kelly and Stuart Stephen, from Aberdeen, have explored the entire programme
during their scanning visits and Kelly, 21, who is 21 weeks pregnant with her
first baby, says she has found it both fascinating and reassuring. ``I've read
books about all these subjects, but the touchscreen brings everything to life.
My favourite section is seeing what the baby looks like at different stages of
its development.''
Stuart, 24, a nurse at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, is impressed by the
programme's simplicity.
``I know how confusing medical language can be, but this programme gives
information - including what can go wrong - in a straightforward, concise way.
The great thing is, people can go over it again and again in a way they feel
they can't when they're speaking to doctors or nurses.''
Dr Smith is delighted with the amount of positive feedback from patients and
visitors to the department and she points out that the new system's
implications may reach far beyond pre-natal care alone.
According to the Aberdeen Royal Hospitals Trust, this type of multimedia
programme, designed under the direction of Dr Neil Hamilton, of the University
Faculty of Medicine's computer-aided learning unit, may also be used in
teaching medical students and training post-graduate, nursing, and paramedical
personnel.
BABIES born prematurely are more likely to suffer from physical and mental
handicap, to be smaller, and to have breathing problems, or even die, than
those born full term. Yet the mechanism that triggers labour remains a mystery.
While enormous strides have been made in paediatric care and babies as young as
26 weeks can survive successfully, medical research is keen to establish why
some women should go into labour prematurely. After all, for the baby to have
the best start in life it should remain within the womb for the full term.
In animals it is known that nitric oxide, a newly discovered substance,
controls the start of labour. But the production of this powerful agent
declines sharply before labour starts. In addition, once the animal is in
labour much larger quantities of nitric oxide are required to stop the womb
contracting.
Now a new research project in Glasgow, based at the Queen Mother Hospital and
Royal Infirmary, hopes to establish if the same mechanism applies to women. If
it does, it will be possible to develop new treatments or drugs to stop labour
occurring before the baby is fully developed.
Dr Jane Norman, a senior lecturer at the Glasgow University of obstetrics and
gynaecology, who is one of the research team, says: ``We know very little about
what triggers the onset of labour except that women who smoke and those from
poorer social backgrounds are more likely to go into labour early.''
The Glasgow study will involve taking small sections of tissue from women
undergoing Caesarean section both at nine months and those having a section
earlier.
If the key to premature labour can be unlocked it means that in the future
suitable drugs could be given to prevent the onset. Meanwhile, the first task
facing Glasgow doctors and scientists is to establish the mechanism by which it
happens in the first place. Ultimately, this could prevent the deaths of around
300 babies a year and prevent handicap in many more.
This two-year research project, jointly funded by Wellbeing (formerly
Birthright) and the Medical Research Council, started a few weeks ago and over
the next couple of years 40 women will be recruited to it.
More than half the required #64,000 Wellbeing contribution has been raised in
Glasgow during the past year, earning the local branch the title of number one
fundraiser in the UK. Chairman Maria Dorrian says: ``We are delighted that
money raised in Glasgow should go to fund research taking place here.''
n Scottish Ballet are staging a gala charity performance of Peter Pan on
Friday, December 15 at the Theatre Royal, Glasgow, in aid of Wellbeing. Tickets
from the theatre box office or phone Maria Dorrian on 01360 620758.
</TEXT>
