<HEADLINE>North Sea production set for new record</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126695</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTH Sea oil output climbed to its highest level for nearly 10 years in
October and, with four more fields coming on stream this month and next,
production is set to exceed its previous all-time high by the year-end.
The Royal Bank of Scotland Oil Index, published yesterday, reveals that output
rose by 150,000 barrels per day last month to an average of 2.74 million bpd.
Production was only marginally adrift of the record level of 2.78 million bpd
recorded in January 1986.
Mark Shea, Royal Bank's energy economist, said yesterday that he expected oil
production to reach a record level before the New Year.
Two new fields came on stream during October, accounting for nearly half of the
increase in output.
Amerada Hess's Fife added 44,000 bpd to the production total, while LASMO's
Birch boosted output to the tune of 21,000 bpd.
Production at existing oil fields was also buoyant.
The four new fields due on stream are expected to add at least another 140,000
bpd to output.
During October, the average Brent crude price was 0.8% lower than the previous
month at $16.55, partly as a result of unwarranted fears that Iraq might be
allowed to make a one-off sale of oil on humanitarian grounds.
In spite of this, average daily oil revenues were up 3.6% at #28.7m.
Commenting on the North Sea outlook, Mr Shea said: ``I think it is pretty
promising and the figures to date are supporting that.''
As more new projects come on stream, oil output is expected to continue to rise
next year and in 1997, before reaching a plateau.
Part of the rise in production can be attributed to the ever more sophisticated
techniques being used by oil companies, as well as their increasing reliance on
large service companies' specialist knowledge.
However, although this is all generally good news for the local economy, Mr
Shea believes the efficiency drive might see some of the smaller service
companies put out of business.
An increase in heating demand during October pushed gas output up 9.1% to an
average of 5679 million cubic feet per day.
Taking oil and gas together, average daily revenues were 5.2% higher than in
September at #39.46m.
</TEXT>
