<DOCNO>GH951130-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pressure mounts as CBI calls for immediate reduction, while Halifax leads way to cheaper borrowing Clarke plays down rate cut moves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry called for a cut in interest rates and
the Halifax Building Society led the way to cheaper mortgages after the
Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, played down the chances of an
imminent move.
Mr Clarke denied that his forecast of 3% growth next year was dependent on
rates being cut. ``The one thing I am not going to do is play fast and loose
with interest rates in response to political pressures,'' he said.
He insisted that rates would be decided on the basis of all the evidence
available at his monthly meetings with the Governor of the Bank of England,
Eddie George.
The next meeting is due to take place on December 13, and speculation persisted
that rates would be cut by half a point then.
Mr Clarke told a news conference at the Treasury that rates would continue to
be set with the aim of hitting the Government's underlying inflation target of
2.5% or less.
Speculation about a cut in rates swirled around the City and Westminster and
continued to drag down the pound on foreign markets. Sterling lost ground to
both the dollar and the mark and its trade weighted index dropped 0.5 points to
82.4, close to its all-time low.
Share prices broke fresh records and gilts, hit by the greater than expected
public borrowing figures in Tuesday's Budget, held up well in anticipation of
lower rates. The FTSE-100 Share index closed 6.7 points higher at 3655.5, some
way below its peak earlier in the day of 3671.0.
The Halifax cut its mortgage rates from 7.99% to 7.74% to kick start the
housing market, which received no special treatment in the Budget. As others
followed its lead it became clear Abbey National was anticipating a cut in base
rates.
The mortgage cuts have taken some of the pressure off the Chancellor to deliver
an early reduction in rates, which have been held at 6.75% since February.
The CBI, however, turned up the heat on Mr Clarke. Its president, Sir Bryan
Nicholson, said: ``The CBI believes the conditions are now right for a
sustainable reduction in interest rates.''
The Budget was a responsible one, with falling borrowing, and only a mild
stimulus to the economy, he said. ``As a result the inflation outlook remains
favourable and, in the light of continued slow growth, we believe that the time
is right for a 0.5% cut in interest rates.''
Sir Bryan described Mr Clarke's forecast of 3% growth in the economy next year
as optimistic, but said it was achievable.
The CBI itself is forecasting 2.5% and Sir Bryan said the main difference
between the CBI's and the Government's forecasts was the outlook for consumer
spending, which Mr Clarke is predicting will increase by 3.5%.
Financial markets have been wrong-footed by the Chancellor's forecast of
#22.5bn PSBR for 1996-97, well above City projections, and the strength of his
economic forecasts. The pound has borne the bulk of the strain.
Independent economists are now divided on whether a cut in rates is needed yet,
and the weakness of sterling has persuaded several that any reduction should be
deferred until next year when fresh evidence will be available about the state
of the economy.
The Bundesbank council meets in the morning to decide whether the German
discount rate should be cut from 3.5% to 3%. There was speculation that if
Germany's central bank failed to deliver, the pound could come under renewed
pressure.
The Budget also revised the current year's PSBR from the mid-summer forecast of
#23.6bn to #29bn. The Bank of England announced yesterday that it would need an
extra gilts auction on February 28 to bridge the gap between revenues and
spending.
``The Government and the Bank have reviewed the remit for funding in 1995-96 in
the light of the Government's forecast of the PSBR published in the
Chancellor's Budget,'' it said.
The next auction will take place on December 7 when the Bank will offer #3000m
of 7.5% gilts maturing in 2006.
</TEXT>
