<DOCNO>GH951130-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stun gun buyer is fined</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126699</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER minder for footballer Duncan Ferguson was given 200 hours of community
service yesterday for importing 20 stun guns.
Andrew Spence, 24, of Cecil Street, Stirling, was also fined #500.
Sheriff Eric Galt said Spence had tried to hoodwink Customs when he had the
100,000 volt electrical weapons mailed to him.
A jolt from the weapons was capable of knocking a man flat and leaving him
helpless for several minutes, prosecutor Kenneth Donnelly said.
Mr Joe Beltrami, defending, said the guns had no lasting effect on their
victims.
The parcels, from a Washington firm, were described as containing personal
alarms. Spence had asked the firm to say that the guns had been sent by mistake
if asked by authorities.
</TEXT>
