<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951130-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951130-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>951130</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S that time of year again - the hot breath of Christmas like a charging
rhino on the back of the neck. Auditions have begun for the Baby Jesus. The
limbless and the disfigured have been discarded. Seems hard, I know, but if
you've ever tried scrubbing ball-point pen squiggles off a baby's head you'll
understand. The arms and legs screwed back in, but frankly they weren't going
to rate a chance against fierce competition. Don't want to be stitched up by
someone who's spent an entire weekend hand-sewing sequinned swaddling clothes.
Our main contender, formerly Sadie, now known as The Stump, sadly won't even
get a shot. Her head vanished. We found it, eventually, impaled on a wooden
stake at the back door. A forgotten victim of Hallowe'en, all tangled hair and
washed-out rosebud mouth. Then there's the fear that she might fall apart, lose
her head as it were, at the crucial moment.
Imagine the embarrassment if your star's head bounced down the stage steps?
Only a director of the calibre of Mike Leigh or Tarantino could deal with that.
Whereas Mrs Turner is more into set-piece tableaux, I think. She could always
pretend she was aiming more for Damien Hirst than Nativity Retro. That it was
an ironic stab at Mother and Child Divided as seen through the glistening eyes
of Primary One parents of Stockbridge, something like that.
Safer I suppose to make do with second choice then, one of a set of twins. We'd
like to enter the male, just to keep to Mrs Turner's strict production values,
but we can't remember which is which since they lack anatomical precision and
their matching babysuits, in pink and blue, disappeared ages ago. A broody cat
was implicated.
Dread sets in at the very prospect of auditions for the supporting cast. Look,
I said, this is ludicrous. There's absolutely no way everyone can be Mary, or
The Angel. It's absolutely fine to be cast as one of the crowd. Just so long as
they don't try that one on you. Ho, ho, only joking. Am I hell.
THE panic attacks are late for the time of year. Only, how many days is it
again till Christmas? No, don't tell me. Not yet. Strategic denial, I think is
called for here. I'm too busy dealing with anxiety attacks over the birthday
party next week. Red-ringed panic in on the Filofax for a week on Friday.
That's a lie. I did once own one of those horrible organisers - it was a gift
from another former friend - but I never found the sticky Urgent notes on the
day-by-day diary until it patently wasn't any longer.
Still the party's organised, sort of. The invitations went out yesterday. No, I
said, we can't invite everyone. It's just such a terrible wrench to choose who
should be left out. No, I said, I know I'm being negative but couldn't we just
sort of hide the invitations, you know, in their schoolbags? It's terribly
cruel to those who're left out. As we know, don't we darling, because of what
happened last week.
Here, hang on, you haven't invited her have you? Anyway, I did the sensible
thing. Ran away, left her to dish out the invitations and inferiority
complexes. Plugged fingers in ears dimmed the sound of Ruth's sobs which caught
up with me at the playground gates. Oh couldn't we just sort of slip her in as
an extra . . ? No. You're right. You can't invite everyone. God, it's tough
being only five and being rejected. It's even tougher being to blame.
The party of course happens to be on the same day as the drama show. Well why
not? Why should Sod change his law just to prevent hysteria in overwrought
working mothers? We'll cope. Of course, we will. It only involves some rigorous
organisation. Precision timing, such as Olympic judges only dream of. We will
bring the party forward half an hour, arrange for the Munchkin costume to go in
the boot along with the cake. Oh no. The cake . . .
What you need to do is learn to prioritise, go on a time-management course,
said a friend, who was until she made her suggestion. She's probably right, but
how can I? I don't have time.
If there's one thing I've learned it's how easy it is to push worries away when
you're racked with guilt. Consuming guilt. Ravaging guilt. Such as how can I be
in three places at once, the carol concert, the ballet show, and do the gift
buying? Oh and get to the office. Polishing off 1200 words of budgetary
analysis is a doddle by comparison. Then I only have to pretend it's important.
See Christmas. I love it.
</TEXT>
