<HEADLINE>3000 voluntary jobs may be lost, warns group</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE thousand temporary jobs in the voluntary sector will be lost as a result
of the Government's decision to cut the Community Action programme for
long-term unemployed adults, according to the Scottish Council for Voluntary
Organisations.
Community Action, introduced in 1993, is delivered through the Employment
Service and offers temporary work opportunities to adults unemployed for more
than six months.
Work undertaken on the programme has to be of demonstrable benefit to the
community and not a substitute for jobs that existed already in the public and
private sectors. Community Action has therefore largely been sub-contracted out
to voluntary organisations. The move, announced on Tuesday, has angered
voluntary organisations which deliver Community Action, particularly as the
Chancellor did not refer to the move in his Budget statement.
Mr Ian Brown, enterprise and training officer with SCVO, said: ``Kenneth Clarke
barely referred to unemployment in his statement, but Employment Service
officials were press-releasing Community Action's obituary before he had even
sat down.
``The cynicism is even more apparent given last year's Budget, when the
Chancellor promised that Community Action funding would continue until 1997.
There is no pretence that this cut is anything but a Treasury-driven saving to
offset Budget giveaways.''
Community Action providers said the programme was popular with long-term
participants and that its wide range of projects benefited the community.
Margaret Thorne of the Scottish Wildlife Trust said: ``Unless we can find
alternative sources of funding within the next four weeks, our programme of
environmental projects will be cut by a quarter, with a corresponding number of
staff redundancies.''
Mr Jim Cooper, speaking on behalf of the Scottish Council for YMCAs, said:
``Clearly this is a tragedy for the long-term unemployed. Yet again the
Government has spent a lot of time and resources building up a programme, only
to scrap it. This is bound to lead to redundancies among our staff.''
</TEXT>
