<HEADLINE>Yorkshire profits buoyant</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975126702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YORKSHIRE Water has increased its half-yearly profits and dividend at a time
when its customers face the possibility of having their supplies cut off
because of drought.
Profits before tax jumped by 48% to #99.5m but that was before taking into
account exceptional costs and the profit from the sale of investment. On an
underlying basis profit growth was 10.1%.
In the first half, coping with the drought occupied both the company and its
customers. Measures to maintain supplies were introduced in the summer
including transportation of water by road into West Yorkshire.
The company also obtained a series of emergency drought powers to extract water
from two rivers to maintain supplies to Bradford and Leeds.
The exceptional operating costs incurred to date - including the #4.6m reported
to end-September - are estimated to be in the region of #20m. The on-going
costs (principally of tankering water into West Yorkshire) are around #3m a
week. These measures are expected to continue until reservoirs reach what are
described as ``safe levels''.
A number of capital projects are being introduced at a cost of #75m to provide
additional resources, principally from river abstractions. Some #13m has
already been spent on schemes to help maintain supplies.
A #12m pilot programme has been established to investigate leakage reduction in
addition to the existing #330m mains and leakage reduction programmes.
Yorkshire rebuts criticism that its under-investment contributed to this
summer's problems. It says investment in both water resources and the
distribution infrastructure has been in line with, or exceeded, the ``K''
investment programme over the last five years.
Non-regulated activities continued to be profitable, albeit at a lower level.
Yorkshire Environmental's profit of #800,000 compares with #1.3m for last year.
Profits were hit by costs and delays in its waste incineration business, White
Rose Environmental. Its turnover rose by 8.2% to #25m.
The group's property interests continue to expand and profits moved up slightly
in the estates business. Yorkshire Water International continues to examine
overseas opportunities within a tightly controlled business development budget.
Group earnings per share jumped by 47.6% and the interim dividend is raised by
10% to 9.1p. The outlook for the second half will be determined by costs
associated with managing the drought situation. However, the group remains
confident of its medium-term prospects, not least because of the expectation of
a growing contribution from its non-regulated activities.
Shares in Yorkshire Water dropped 2p to 612p.
n SWALEC said it would reject an indicative cash and share offer from Welsh
Water at 825p to 840p made at talks yesterday.
The indicative price was for Swalec shares excluding its holding in the
National Grid but with its interim dividend, which will be announced with
first-half results today. Welsh Water offered a full cash alternative at a
discount to these levels.
A further meeting between the two companies today could yield a higher offer.
